    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>>> Used the idea before ... if it [nuclear damper] can either enhance
>>> or suppress nuclear reactions, it *has* to be able to affect fusion
>>> reactions.

> No, it doesn\'t. I always assumed the damper damped
> _fission_ reactions, which are entirely different to
> _fusion_ reactions. I am assuming that the nuclear
> missiles which the dampers are designed to make
> harmless are largely fission bombs; these are easier
> to make (at any tech level, just like it\'s easier to
> make a knife than scissors) than fusion bombs, and
> current fusion bombs require a fission bomb as a
> "trigger". This is because fusion only takes place at
> very high temperatures. At our tech level we achieve
> these high temperatures with a fission bomb. So
> damping fission effects would stop any of our tech
> level\'s bombs going off; the fission reaction fails,
> so the hydrogen/deuterium/tritium just vapourises into
> space.

> Damping _fusion_ reactions would be a whole different
> thing.

The dampers are stated to work by manipulating the weak nuclear force.
Said force turns out to be involved in fission *and* fusion. So while
it may take a different "setting", there\'s no reason they *can\'t*
affect a fusion reaction, and lots of reasons to think they can.

> I still hold that the intention of the dampers was
> that they\'d damp fission.

Nope. They are *specificly* describes as being able to speed or or slow
down fission. And I\'m pretty sure that fusion is mentioned also.

BTW, when used against missiles, it\'s virtually certain that the damper
is used to *accelerate* decay, so that the sub-critical masses in the
warhead will melt and ruin the warhead before it gets close enough to
hurt you. 

Slowing down down the reaction would only be useful if you caught the
warhead at the exact millisecond that the explosive charges compress
the fissionables past critical mass. Hit it outside that window and the
warhead can still go off as soon as the beam moves to another target. 

It\'s been specifically noted that "cleaning up" after a nuke blast on a
planet surface involves making the radioactive material decay faster.
This makes the contaminated area much more lethal (and hotter in the
*thermal* sense) whgile you are doing this. But in a relatively short
time, there\'s no more shortlived isotopes in the area, and long-lived
isotopes give off negligible amounts of radiation unless *extremely*
concentrated. 

