    'date' => 'Sun, 21 Nov 1999 09:51:40  0800',
    'body' => '>I\'m surprised the Imperium doesn\'t utilize mass-driver technology on
>warships when they need to do pin-point bombardment. It CAN be done, the
>physics prove this. Besides, you don\'t have to mess with that nasty Pu
>(plutonium).

With Traveller starship technology there\'s nothing special about mass
drivers; using the ship\'s own engine for "deadfall" ordinance makes much
more sense for bombarding city-sized targets, and smaller targets need
guided ordinance, which might as well have its own engine.
(A typical Traveller missile has ~200 km/s of delta-V, much higher than
you could ever get out of a mass driver; and of course a starship can provide
several km/s with a few minutes burn of its engines before dropping the
rocks.)

The high performance of Traveller engines somewhat negates the advantages
of being in orbit - you can get that same 200 km/s (or something close to it)
with a missile launched from the ground on a suitable trajectory, though
of course that\'s easier to shoot down. Only in societies with chemical rockets
does the energy advantage of being in orbit (10 km/s) make a significant
difference. The positional advantage does remain (it\'s easier to protect
your own troops from orbit.)

Bruce
