    'topic' => ' Traveller Navigation and Gunnery',
    'body' => 'From: Leonard Erickson <shadow@>


>In this situation "big rocks" have a decided advantage. You can nudge a
>rock into a collision orbit, and anybody on world with much of a
>telescope can *see* you do it. Doesn\'t take but a few observations and
>a calculator to determine the new orbit. And you\'ve got *months* to
>watch it come at you.


Ouch.

>And as long as the Imperium holds the "high ground" you can *see* it
>come at you, and not be able to do a damn thing about it. And there\'s a
>definite deadline as *nobody* is going to be able to stop or deflect it
>once it gets within a few days of impact.


It almost goes without saying that the Imperium can hold the high ground
when it wants to, at least when it\'s dealing with internal problems. *Now* I
can see why nobody leaves the Imperium under their own will. ;)

Still, it would also seem that the first thing a country wishing to rebel
*must* do if its rebellion is to have any chance of succeeding is to manage
to create one, but preferably more, deep meson cannon sites. Of course, this
will frequently have to be done in secret.

It\'s not so much for nailing the big rocks but for making such a scenario as
expensive as possible for the Imperium.
