    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>>But there *are* some problems. You aren\'t going to get nuke level
>>strikes from a spinal mass driver. The impact energy is a function of
>>.the mass of the projectile, and the launch velocity. The launch
>>velocity is dependent on the length of the driver and the acceleration
>>it can provide (I can dig up the formula). You won\'t get anywhere
>>*near* lightspeed with a ship mounted weapon (I once did the figures
>>for a 1000 km longer mass driver and it only got a few percent of c)
>
> What if you had a huge cyclotron that accelerated the mass to near C then
> expelled it?

You\'d tear the ship apart long before you got near c. Remember, running
a mass around in a circle requires that you exert a force to push it
towards the center, so it\'ll stay in the circular path. And that means
that the frame of the ship needs to exert a counterforce to keep the
cyclotron from flying apart (an inward push on the mass results in an
*outward* push on the cyclotron).

You get *exactly* the same stresses you\'d get if you had the mass on
the end of a long arm and tried to spin it around at some fraction of
c. 

Cyclotrons work because the particles they are accelerating have so
little mass. try accelerating a 1 kg mass to the same sort of speed and
the side forces get unreal. 

