    'month' => '11',
    'index' => 'ee539',
    'body' => 'On 11/21/99 at 12:30 PM,  shadow@ (Leonard Erickson) said:

>> Still, it would also seem that the first thing a country wishing to rebel
>> *must* do if its rebellion is to have any chance of succeeding is to manage
>> to create one, but preferably more, deep meson cannon sites. Of course, this
>> will frequently have to be done in secret.

>> It\'s not so much for nailing the big rocks but for making such a scenario as
>> expensive as possible for the Imperium.

>Problem is, the rock will get the course mod *way* outside the range
>of an meson site. Say 1 or 2 AU. That\'s 150 to 300 *million* km. The
>imperials can stay out around the 100 diameter limit and pick off
>anybody jumping insystem. And they\'d be fairly hard to hit (actually,
>I\'m not sure they *can* be hit at that range from an "average" sized
>world). 

No, a meson cannon couldn\'t stop the rock from being put on an
intercept course.  It wouldn\'t have the range.  I got to thinking,
though, about another idea.

Would it be possible to use the meson cannon to deflect the rock?
You aren\'t going to have many shots because of the closing velocity,
but it doesn\'t have to be moving all that fast to be deadly, so it
*might* be possible to hit a rock a few times between the time it
comes into range and it hits the world\'s surface.  

You don\'t want to break it up so aiming would be critical.  What you
would want to do is decay the mesons just under the surface of the
big rock causing an explosion that changes it\'s vector.  All you
have to do is deflect it a little and it hits at an angle and skips
off.  I suspect even near misses would be quite unpleasant for a
world\'s ecology, but infinitely better than a direct hit.

Eris
