    'body' => 'From: "Chris Seamans"

>>It\'s so much easier to convince your enemy that you might enhance
>>their radiant luminosity if they don\'t accept your reasonable offer of
>>protectorate status, and quickly get about the business of
>>import/export, than it is to actually wipe them out, wait for the ground
>>to cool, plant a fresh colony, and then start up the import/export
>>business.


>Ah, okay. So now you\'re saying the mere threat of rock dropping will be
>enough to bring a world around. The only problem is that from time to time
a
>world\'s going to say, "Hey! You\'re not *really* gonna whack us with rocks!"
>
>Then what happens exactly... start a land war? Or follow through on the use
>of cheap and brutal "terror weapons"?
>
>
>Where do things such as the firebombing of Dresden, the atomic bombing of
>Hiroshima and (tongue planted firmly in cheek) the God smiting of Sodom and
>Gommorah fit into those conceptions?

Hiroshima happened because the U.S. was the only country to possess nuclear
weapons. There was no chance that Japan could retaliate.  The whole
Manhattan project thing, with the USAA bombing water pipelines from Norway
to prevent heavy water deliveries to scientists in Germany was based on the
fear that Hitler would get the bomb first. Had he done so and dropped it
on....I don\'t know...***London*** for example the European war would have
been over. (Especially if it had been delivered by a V-2.)

The cold war happened because the USSR was spying on the American/British
nuclear projects and had the bomb themselves. If they had not, I feel that
sometime in the 1950\'s, during the major anti-red scare, the U.S. would have
nuked them. Once they had the ability to retaliate the balanced changed, and
it became unthinkable (to all but Barry Goldwater) that the U.S. would use
nuclear weapons in a regional war.

Obtrav: As long as the other major interstellar powers can use near C rocks
or mass drivers for orbital bombardment this method of warfare will not be
used. In side the 3I it won\'t be used because destroying a high pop world
would result in a general rebellion. The local Reserve and System Navy
forces would never support it, even if the Navy Admiralty did. Quite
possibly even nobles in other sectors might not support it (because of
pressure from their vassals), and support of the citizenry in general.

Terry C
