    'body' => 'At 05:17 PM 11/21/1999 -0500, you wrote:

>Which brings up a question for me; assuming the forces have control of the
>\'high ground\', whats the best way of dropping your troops in oder to capture
>the planet?  Together in armored shuttles (I think this is a bad idea
>myself) or like in Starship Troopers, where they drop individually
>\'halo-style\'?

Preview of Ground Forces (a real rough preview):

Making a forced landing is one of the most difficult exercises the Army or
Marines are called upon to perform.  Planning and executing these invasions
require several steps:

I.  Reconnaissance

	The target world needs to be scouted.  Ideally, Army Intelligence will
have maintained information on the planet\'s defenses for years before the
conflict.  Sylean Ranger or Marine Special Operations units will attempt to
infiltrate the world.
	What they are looking for is command and control centers, communications
nodes and planetary defence sites.  Recon troops work hand in hand with
Intelligence assets to make the best use of available information to
produce a complete picture of the enemy defenses.  Of course, this
information has to make it back to the Army commanders to be of any use.
If possible, recon teams are extracted by IISS ships.  If not, the
information is sent to IISS ships which then leave the system.

II.  Space Superiority

	For anything other than quick Marine raids, it is necessary to establish
reasonable control over orbital space.  It is rare to be able to completely
clear enemy activity, but the commander can not allow hostile vessels any
penetration of the Fleet screen.

III. Orbital Bombardment/Initial Raids

	Once orbital control is established, selected targets are engaged by fire
from Navy ships.  Highest priority is given to planetary defense sites that
have the ability to hit the fleet.  If necessary, fire is allocated to
secondary targets such as power generation centers, transportation nexi, or
population centers.  Imperial doctrine is to avoid unnecessary collateral
damage when possible, so ortillery fire is closely contained.
	At the same time, Marine units begin dropping to seize high value targets
such as the planet\'s starport.  Other raids are launched to both distract
and demoralize the defenders.  At this point in the operation, the overall
commander will make the final decision on where the main force will land.

IV. Pathfinder Landings

	Rapid Interface troops and Marines will make meteoritic reentry to seize
the dedicated landing zone.  At the same time, orbital fire will shift to
suppression of any enemy presence within 250 miles of the center of the LZ.
 The troops on the ground can count on heavy support from naval fighters as
well as their own attack speeders.

V.  Main Force Landing

	Under the cover of their fleet escorts, the massive Keith-class Brigade
transports begin reentry.  Supporting fire reaches it\'s most intense level
during this period of vulnerability.  Electronic Warfare units attempt to
reduce the enemy\'s ability to detect and communicate to such a low level
that they are effectively immobilized while the transports land.
	Once grounded, each transport disgorges it\'s load of two combat battalions
and support units.  Depending on the tactical situation, the transports may
be ordered back into space or told to remain on the surface.

VI.  Movement to Contact/Consolidation

	Once the combat units have formed up, they begin moving to their
objectives.  At the original landing zone, Beachmaster units begin the
difficult of setting up the necessary supply and medical units.

	The Imperial mode of combat emphasizes quick action and overwhelming
firepower.  Army leaders are taught the Fleet can not afford to linger over
a single planet, so never depend on endless support from the skies.  When
in the attack the Army and Marines use their firepower liberally. 
