    'topic' => ' Traveller Navigation and Gunnery',
    'body' => 'From: DaveShayne <daveshayne@email.msn.com>


>I\'m sorry if I misconstrued your argument. I thought you were refering
>to the Centauri treatment of the Narn.

No real problem. It\'s alright.

>And can\'t support their own people who begin to think maybe being a part of
>the
>Imperium, "arna sa bad afta all." The peasants revolt and prety soon the
>same
>shmos who wanted the imperium off their backs are begging for a marine
>detachment for protection against their own people.


Really? So a world can\'t support itself without Imperial help. That\'s
interesting, \'cause we\'re not doing that bad here on Terra right now. ;)

Still, there are some worlds which require technological assistance to keep
their population alive. Of course, the Imperium wouldn\'t need to drop big
rocks on them to win them over.

>I supose it\'s posible if everybody on the planet is mortally opposed to
>imperial rule this might have to be done but I don\'t see any planet with a
>pop
>greater than 2 where this could posibly be the case.

Well, the large number of nationalist movements, self-determination
movements, and so on that exist and have existed in the real world seem to
be placed in opposition to your reasoning.

>who\'s gonna notice." In all other situations enough people will be found
who
>are willing to accept Imperial rule to keep things going on a more or less
>reasonably profitable level.


"In all other situations..." watch those generalizations, sir! ;)

Seriously, though, this is an awfully strange view of the way human beings
have been, and seem to be in the real world. Granted, this is descriptive
and not prescriptive (the problem with "human nature" is that it\'s
neccesarily descriptive) but even so, what happens when you\'re confronted
with a charismatic, nationalistic dictator, or ideology, or both?

>>1.) If you want to control a city / country / planet in a traditional
>sense,
>>somebody\'s got to be there. The Imperium doesn\'t *want* to control cities
/
>>countries / planets in the traditional sense. They simply want them to pay
>>taxes.
>
>In which case they\'re going to choose the least damaging way of convincing
>them to accept imperial rule that they can.


Least damaging to whom? The planet or the Imperium?

If it\'s the former, dropping rocks is effectively the same as dropping
ground troops. You\'re still going to lose civilians, and it\'s more than
likely that you\'re going to decimate industrial centers. If it\'s the latter,
dropping rocks is a hell of alot cheaper and less time consuming than
dropping marines in battle dress.

>Or try bribing the local leaders. If a planets power structure is left
>intact The
>local leaders may well decide that the Imperium is, "okaybyme."


Bribes only go so far. That\'s been tried at various points, and that
frequently fails as well. How easy would it be to bribe a Hitler, or a
Castro, exactly, or any other leader who manages to convince people, for
whatever reason, to do things that seem amazingly non-rational in
retrospect?

>>Neither does a determined populace. So, we\'re back at square one.
>
>I supose. But just how determined is the populace? If the Impies come
>in with a batron and a few regiments of marines, bribes in the right
places,
>and some cosmetic reforms (say renaming the taxes negative income
>enhancements or some such) would the peasants still revolt?
>In most cases I doubt it.


Just out of curiosity, how did we end up on the Marxist "peasant revolt"
line? It doesn\'t have to be "peasants" or "proles" who are doing the bulk of
the revolting at all. In fact, in cases like the American of French
Revolutions the peasants weren\'t even the real driving force behind the
rebellion.

>Yes I was being inelequent. Some other reasons countries go to war
>are: "Glorious Leaders" huge ego needs a stroke, religious disputes (These
>wars
>are among the dirtiest wars), to avoid being anexed by another country.
>(Yes it actually does take two countries to fight a war)


Actually, religious disputes, historically, have been among the least
"dirty" wars, depending on how you look at it. This may simply be an
accident of history, since the same force that allowed mankind to make
really impressive weapons also happened to marginalize those religious
institutions that would be able to make war to a great degree.

However, if you were to add up the death toll of only two of the ideological
and nationalist wars of the twentieth century (World War I and World War II)
you\'re gonna find that the dirtiest wars weren\'t fought over religion at
all.

>And no doubt many other reasons/justifications. Wars still boil down to a
>violent dispute over who gets to call the shots.


Fair enough, but you\'ve already stated that your previous statement was open
to misinterpretation. There\'s no reason to belabor the point.

;)

>>It doesn\'t have to be genocide. Let me state again that total destruction
>>does not have to follow from rock dropping.
>
>Depends on how big the rock is.


Still, it doesn\'t have to follow that the use of a brutal terror weapon
means that you have to turn the surface of a planet into slag and start over
again with a new crew of colonists.

>>This would be different from the situation in what way after a land war in
>>what way precisely?
>
>In general in a land war you only shoot at things that are in your imediate
>way and/or shooting back. As opposed to the rock that\'s going to get
>everybody it lands on whether their fighting back or not. Killing people
>who aren\'t otherwise involved usually results in fence sitters joining the
>foe more often than convincing your enemy to give up.


Really? In a land war, it can be amazingly difficult for combatants to tell
who\'s a civilian and who\'s not. Of course, the blurring of distinctions
between civilian and military targets that invariably happens in modern
warfare makes this even more problematic.

>>Ah, okay. So now you\'re saying the mere threat of rock dropping will be
>>enough to bring a world around. The only problem is that from time to time
>a
>>world\'s going to say, "Hey! You\'re not *really* gonna whack us with
rocks!"
>>
>>Then what happens exactly... start a land war? Or follow through on the
use
>>of cheap and brutal "terror weapons"?
>
>Um yea I guess that last paragraph of mine does tend to support your thesis
>more than mine. But if you nuke say a convenient uninhabited moon that
>hapens to be nearby.... Well maybe convinced fanatics would doubt your
>willingness but nobody can doubt your capability.


Oh come on, who the hell\'s going to doubt the Imperium\'s capacity to drop
big rocks on their population centers at will? Anyone in the Imperium who
has the most rudimentary education is going to understand that it\'s a
painfully simple process.

Still, your "moon" scenario is just delaying the inevitable. Okay, the
Imperium does that once, and the populace folds. The Imperium does it again,
somewhere else, and the populace folds. What happens if the Imperium whacks
a moon a third time and the population says, "Nuts!"?

>>Where do things such as the firebombing of Dresden, the atomic bombing of
>>Hiroshima and (tongue planted firmly in cheek) the God smiting of Sodom
and
>>Gommorah fit into those conceptions?
>
>Dresden was more or less irellevent to the outcome of the war. In

Was it now? I know, people can tell me how there were no real industrial
centers there, blah blah blah...

Still, do you happen to have access to some information the world isn\'t
privvy to? Perhaps morale levels among soldiers and civilians in Germany
after the news got out? Can you say with certainty the bombing of a civilian
target - which Jens noted was where civilians were going to avoid being
incinerated - had no effect whatsoever on the war?

>Japan was already beaten in every sense except the actuall occupation by
the
>time
>the bombs were dropped. The japanese knew this and were attempting to
>negotiate surender terms at the time. The bomb merely pointed out that we
>were
>willing to kill all of them in order to get unconditional surrender.


Yes, and this message was sent in a big, atomic fireball... This further
supports my point, actually. After all, what happened to the fence sitters
who would (under your model) rise up and strike back at their foes as a
result of the bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki?

>In both cases large occupying armies were required to control the conquered
>teritories and we wound up spending a large sum of money rebuilding their
>destroyed infrastructure. If both of the previous were not true we would
>probably
>have had another world war sometime in the sixties.


Again, you go on to support my point, since the infrastructure of both
countries was decimated by more traditional forms of warfare. ;)
