Actually, PCs in a planetary assault situation would tend to find the
tactical situation (what is our immediate mission objective, how do we
get there, what support do we have, and who will relieve us) far more
important than the echelons-above-gawd (EAG) strategic view (why are we,
at _this_ time, seizing _this_ world, and how will we assemble the
needed forces to seize it).  Thus, while an EAG game (such as _Fifth
Frontier War_), with a ground force scale of units up to field army
size, can abstract space, ground-space interface, and ground combat, the
typical PCs will _need_ to have all the details we\'re discussing in this
thread.

(Yes, I know that I skipped the operational level of war.  In my
defense, I would expect most warfare-related campaigns to place the PCs
either in the units actually engaging in combat [see _Striker_ for
details], or in positions on the General Staff, deciding how to
prosecute the war as a whole [as in FFW].  Even operational-level
campaigns [with the PCs as commanders of combat operations involving a
single world] would require knowledge of the tactical doctrine being
employed by units under those commanders\' direction.)

