    'body' => 'Sethkimmel@aol.com wrote:
> 
> In a message dated 11/21/99 2:12:33 PM Pacific Standard Time, j-man@iname.com
> writes:
> 
> << Which brings up a question for me; assuming the forces have control of the
>  \'high ground\', whats the best way of dropping your troops in order to capture
>  the planet?  Together in armored shuttles (I think this is a bad idea
>  myself) or like in Starship Troopers, where they drop individually
>  \'halo-style\'? >>
> 
> I like the FASA Renegade Legion method of dropping grav vehicles from
> orbit....

Actually, all three methods are important components of a planetary
assault.  Large (battalion or larger) jump troop formations will be used
either to seize the initial "spacehead(s)", or to secure key terrain
features to prevent or delay the enemy\'s early counterattacks on the
spacehead(s).  Smaller formations (battalion and smaller) would conduct
diversionary raids, to disrupt the enemy\'s ability to respond quickly to
the assault.  For assaults on low-population worlds with few high-payoff
targets, jump troops, possibly reinforced by small grav vehicle
contingents, may be sufficient to secure the world under attack. 
Attacks on these target worlds would most likely consist of Imperial
Marine regiments, with little or no Army participation in actual
combat.  OTOH, if Army units of corps size or larger are to be involved
in active ground combat (as compared to counterinsurgency, pacification,
or occupation duties), then the preferred units would be Army Rapid
Interface formations.

The jump troop lodgments would then be reinforced (if necessary) by grav
vehicles descending from orbit.  These forces would provide the
firepower needed to enable the invaders to expand the spacehead(s)
enough to provide fairly secure rear areas.

However, the vast majority of troops, equipment, and supplies would
reach dirt via shuttle (and/or landing-capable starships), landing in
the now-secured rear areas seized and expanded by jump troops and
direct-assault grav vehicles.  After all, the biggest problem with
direct-drop forces is that resupply is too difficult to maintain for
long periods of time without use of shuttles and/or landing-capable
ships.  The shuttle-borne flow of supplies, reinforcements, and
replacements to the spacehead(s) will enable the invader to secure both
important objectives on-planet and travel routes betwen those
objectives.  These forces will almost always consist of Imperial Army
forces that have been mobilized from regular or colonial subsector
elements.

