    'body' => 'From: "Chris Seamans" <semo@pil.net>

<<Lots snipped>>

<Chris>
Actually, religious disputes, historically, have been among the least
"dirty" wars, depending on how you look at it. This may simply be an
accident of history, since the same force that allowed mankind to make
really impressive weapons also happened to marginalize those religious
institutions that would be able to make war to a great degree.

However, if you were to add up the death toll of only two of the ideological
and nationalist wars of the twentieth century (World War I and World War II)
you\'re gonna find that the dirtiest wars weren\'t fought over religion at
all.
</Chris>

However, it does often seem that wars in which religion is a major motivating factor are inclined to get nastier quicker.  Many of the more notorious cases of atrocities and attacks on civilians seem to happen more often in religious conflicts that nationalist or ideological conflicts.  Whilst the two \'World Wars\' had many documented cases of atrocities, I suspect that in proportion to the numbers of combatants involved many of the smaller conflicts in history founded in religion were far nastier.

<<Lots more snipped>>

