    'topic' => 'OFF TOPIC (OT): Taikonauts!',
    'body' => 'I don\'t know who\'s all aware of this, but last weekend the People\'s
Republic of China launched, orbited and landed an unmanned spacecraft.
this space flight is at least one of the two precursors to the actual
launching of Chinese citizens, or what they term "taikonauts" in
English. The word comes from Chinese "taikog" (sp?) = cosmos/space, and
"ren" for men. The spacecraft itself is called "Shenzhou" for "magical vehicle."

It\'s an exciting prospect and the Chinese have put their own touch onto
what looks like an effort based upon the Russian Soyuz. Of course the
Americans have also "donated" (and I use the word cautiously, in light
of the current spy scandal on our shores) their technology to the Long
March launch vehicle, in service since 1996.

Nevertheless, it should generate a lot of inquiries and comments from
people around the world. When they pull off their first manned space
flight, it is my hope that both the USA and Russia, as well as the
European Space Agency, will welcome the Chinese accomplishment with open
arms and invite them to participate in future space missions as an
instrument of international good will.

There is an unofficial web site dedicated to the Chinese manned space
flight efforts. It\'s called "Go Taikonauts!" and it is located at:

http://www.geocities.com/CapeCanaveral/Launchpad/1921/

I think this would be a good Off-Topic discussion for Traveller fans.

- --
Josh W. Spencer (macmanjws@earthlink.net)
Ypsilanti, Michigan, USA
