Please note that in the quote above I said "within the Imperium".

>A contingent of Marines can be surgical. Take out the leaders, take out the
>troublemakers, the balance of the population, who probably doesn\'t care
>who\'s in charge as long as business is good doesn\'t get hurt. Well mostly
>anyway.  Start using weapons of mass destruction: Bio-weapons, Nukes, big
>rocks, and their general apathy starts to turn to rebellion pretty quick.


No doubt that a contingent of marines can be surgical. However, a surgical
strike is *anything* but what the Imperium would need in a scenario like the
one that forms the basis for this discussion.

I am curious as to how you\'ve come to the conclusion that "general apathy
starts to turn to rebellion pretty quick"? While it seems to me that,
historically, armies in the field tend to fight better when they hear about
atrocities commited on their civilian populations, there\'s no real evidence
that atrocities *generate* revolutions.

Besides, the Imperium is in that boat already. In the scenario we\'re talking
about, there already *is* a general rebellion on the surface of the planet.
If a few fence sitters change sides it really doesn\'t matter. What are they
going to do, thumb their noses at the Imperial warships, effectively
invisible and untouchable, somewhere past the sky?

