> > doesn\'t really exist, it was just put there by an early survey team who
> > couldn\'t think of any better explanation for the dead colony they came across.
> Maybe it does. Filter masks are worn to prevent causative spores,
> (whatever). from lodging in the airways, the only place in a human they
> can inhabit.

Yeah, I think I will change this a bit...

(on removing all the post-processed food):
> You don\'t have to with fusion power. Turn it into simple hydrocarbons.
> If abundant energy isn\'t available, burn it, bury it, or terraform the
> place with it.

Yeah, true. I suppose a planet is a pretty big place, even a measly 
size 6 one. I don\'t have the stomach to calculate how much "stuff"
there would be after a few centuries of tourism, but it would be
pretty manageable, sure. Terraforming the place with it is an interesting
idea... (ski mount Crapmore!)

My only open question is that I wonder if the agricultural worlds of
the Imperium notice the loss of biomass over time? I mean, if you have
"Alberta-zon", the planet covered with wheat (and right-wing politicians)
that\'s perpetually being shipped out to feed the legions or whatever, do they
start to suffer after a few centuries? Do they notice the loss of
nutrients, minerals, etc?

Anyway, on to the idea of an un-farmable garden world.

The basic idea is that the planet\'s plant life grows fine, like Terra\'s, but
there exists a combination of factors that makes monocultural farming difficult
to impossible.

For example, when you till a field on Whanga, a week later you\'ll have a nice
green patch of thick grass & weeds. It\'s difficult to farm effectively when the
weeds choke out the crops before they even sprout. (On the other hand, Whangan
potatoes would probably make a great crop off-planet... imagine crops that grow
faster than the weeds.)

The normal solution would be to apply a selective herbicide, but wow, Whangan
plants are remarkably adaptable to herbicides and you\'ll run out of herbicidal
formulations pretty fast (say, in a decade or so).

Another option might be to farm something that doesn\'t mind weeds, like fruit
trees, but, unfortunately, there\'s a mould/fungus/insect grub that tends to
spread from tree to tree quickly, wiping out the entire orchard once the fungus
taken root (so to speak). Whengan trees deal with this by using a wind-born
seed/spore distribution method that tends to keep individual plants of the same
species fairly distant from one another, except for certain species, like
non-fruit-bearing trees, which soak themselves with a natural anti-fungal agent
(which is, unfortunately again, highly flamable, making the trees a poor choice
of building materials).

The wind-born spores would probably reach a peak seasonly, thus the atmospheric
taint. For most of the year the air would be fine, but there\'s this two week
period every year and that just happened to be the time when the survey team
landed...

I didn\'t orginally envision any native animal life on Whenga, thus removing
mechanisms like using animals as seed carriers (via berries) as an option.

Using the chlorophyll virus in combination with all of that would make
a nice touch, preventing existing genetically engineered plants from
being imported (no RoundupReady canola!).

The final possibility is using plant-to-meat converters (i.e. cows) for which I
have no good defence. Maybe everything on Whenga is poisonous to cows too, I
dunno.  At any rate, the whole thig is just a handwave to explain why such an
otherwise nice planet is being wasted on casinos and grav-ball stadia.

Ethan
