Enslavement doesn\'t mean that you think of your enemies as subhuman,
especially the older forms of slavery that aren\'t based on race or other
easily identifiable characteristics.  (Americans in particular get
confused about this because American slaves were black in a mostly white
country, which made it intellectually easier to think of them as a
different species.  Even so, they were still treated as people in many
households.  One or two slaves who lived with the family was much more
common than vast plantations, and even on vast plantations, not everyone 
was Simon Legree.)

Among the Romans, the Norse and many other peoples, slavery made you part
of a household.  

Since the master of a household in Rome had the right of life or death
over everyone in it anyway, slavery basically only made you transferable
property and also affected your civil rights outside of the household.  
Many slaves were regarded as part of the family and people looked down
upon those who abandoned or mistreated old slaves who could no longer
work.  

I\'m not saying that slavery is OK, but when close ties continued past
manumission, as happened with many freedmen and women in some of these
cultures, and there were clearly emotional as well as legal bonds-- I
think that slavery of the sort prevalent in the ancient world cannot
really be regarded in the same light as death camps, concentration camps,
rape camps, "comfort women", nuclear warfare, and other atrocities.  

It\'s wrong, but it\'s a different kind of wrong.  Making someone peel your
potatoes, become your concubine (different from being repeatedly brutally
gangraped and then murdered), hoe your fields, etc is rather different
from cutting them up in bizarre experiments, dashing their children\'s
brains out in front of them, or loading them into ovens or gas chamber
"showers".  Slaves get to live, get treated as people even if not with the
same rights, and sometimes even get freed.  Many slaves were even loved
after a fashion by their masters, though the slave did not always return
such feelings.  And while slaves were often beaten and occasionally killed
in these times, so were wives and children.  People in those eras had a
different idea of what it meant to be a human being, which did not
include immunity to corporal punishment or the right to make your own
decisions conferred absolutely somewhere between age 16 and age 25
regardless of gender, birth order, or economic situation.

None of this is intended as a moral justification for slavery.  But if you
had a choice, you\'d be better off as a slave in an ancient household than
you would be in Dachau.  Commodifying people is not the same as completely
dehumanizing them, and commodification was almost never absolute in the
ancient world because people had to spend too much time together in
households not to think of each other as human beings.

Are their any cultures in your TU that practice slavery?  Do you believe
that slavery is economically unworkable after a culture reaches a certain
TL?  I am curious as to how people have dealt with this issue.  I am sure
that there\'s no slavery in the 3I, but what about other places?  Traveller
is really a space opera, and slavery is prevalent in lots of those.

Kiri

