    'body' => '>is concerned.  =)  Forgive my space brain and tell me if there was an
>ideological component to Carthage or if it was one of those hundreds of
>years of ethnic hatred due to close competition things.

It was essentially a dispute over territory. The Phonecian-decended
Carthaginians had a wealthy trade empire, and Rome, as an expansionist
power, wanted in on that action. Sicily, Spain, and North Africa were all
in dispute.

There is little evidence that there were higher-than-normal ethnic tensions
involved, and none at all of religious dispute, AFAIK.

The razing of Carthage and the salting of the ground seemed to have as much
to do with revenge for Hannibal Barca\'s long rampage in the Roman homeland
as anything else.

IMHO, greed tends to be the biggest factor in why wars get started, with
ideologies providing a convienient rationalization to justify the cause.

Ciao,

