    'body' => 'Kiri Aradia Morgan wrote:
> 
> Commodifying people is not the same as completely
> dehumanizing them, and commodification was almost never absolute in the
> ancient world because people had to spend too much time together in
> households not to think of each other as human beings.

The key word here is \'commodifying\'. They were worth something, in many
cases, worth quite a lot. People own horses, oxen, dogs, they, well,
they provide living space and food for cats ;-) Slaves were viewed in
much the same way...a good slave was worth a heck of a lot, and it was
stupid to mistreat them, same as it is to mistreat a good horse...it
makes them worth less. 

Enslaving people because they are part of the untermenschen (sp, I\'m
sure), as the Nazis did, is another kettle of fish. They were seen as
disposable, worthless, but you might get some use out of them before
they wore out and were thrown away, which was the ultimate goal anyway.
The Nazi\'s were hell bent on exterminating those they found to be
subhuman, but they were also pragmatic to a germanic fault...why waste
good labor while you had it?
 
> Are their any cultures in your TU that practice slavery?  Do you believe
> that slavery is economically unworkable after a culture reaches a certain
> TL?  I am curious as to how people have dealt with this issue.  I am sure
> that there\'s no slavery in the 3I, but what about other places?  Traveller
> is really a space opera, and slavery is prevalent in lots of those.
>

Chattel slavery, \'people as property\' is specifically outlawed as an
Imperial Crime. Curiously, this does not seem to include indentured
servitude.

I\'m sure that there are any number of Megacorps who are happy to provide
their workers with all their needs at the company store, housing them in
the company quarters, schooling them in the company schools....charging
them a little bit more than they make all the while...

\'...another day older and deeper in debt...\'

The difference between this and chattel slavery is pretty much mere
window dressing. 
While the law forbids passing the parent\'s debt on to their children, a
particularly callous megacorp might well charge the children, not their
parents for schooling, medical care, etc, so they hit 18 with an
unmanageable debt to start with.

I wrote a T4-era adventure around a world where indentured servitude =
chattel slavery. It was set outside the Imperium, but could easily occur
somewhere inside, depending on how devious the megacorp execs are.

http://www.u.arizona.edu/~bjohnson/slavers_of_gennare.txt

(A prettier version of this is on Freelance Traveller.)

Slavery is only workable when you have something that needs human labor,
rather than machine labor to do it. Robot work 3 shifts, no
lunch/coffee/potty breaks, no life support is necessary, no pesky worker
safty rules apply, they\'re pretty much immune to unionization.

I don\'t think it\'s very workable on a mass industrial scale.

On an agricultural one, well that depends greatly on how cheap robots
are.

As household servants, OTOH, slavery will be practical as long as rich
people are lazy. However, that is a vanishingly small segment of the
workplace.

OTGH, lots and lots of people will be contract laborers, blue and white
collar, and the Company will own their contracts. If you have no choice
but to work for Eneri\'s Widget Works until Eneri decides to release you
from your contract, what again is the difference between that and
slavery?

That was the basis for the MLB players association successful suit to
allow free agency by the baseball players; it reached the Supreme Court,
and the (then) existing system of player contracts was overturned on
14th amendment grounds, as being equivalent to slavery.

