There wasn\'t any significant ideological component, AFAIK. It was 
simply a matter of finishing off the job. Mind you it took a fair bit 
of stirring by rabid anti-Carthage senator, etc to get the Third Punic 
War rolling, and I suspect that the agitators were probably those who 
stood to profit most.

However for an even earlier example that (arguably) wasn\'t economic or 
territorial I submit the Persian Wars. They were largely fought on the 
(mainland) Greek side out of a belief that Greeks were superior to 
everyone else, and therefore should be under Persian domination. Of 
course once the Ionian Greeks started to actually succeed in their 
mainland assisted revolts the Persians turned it into an invasion of 
mainland Greece.
 


