    'ts-index' => '1999-11-22.ee677',
    'body' => 'Who says Imperial culture is Western?

If the archaeologists/anthropologists/whatevers are right,
human culture didn\'t put any value on the human at all
until around 2000 BC (with, of all people, Abraham).
It was with certain Semitic peoples in Mesopotamia that
developed the idea that the person was worth something;
from there we have the birth of "Western" civilization.  The
older ways hung around as well, and gave rise to Eastern
thought, though there is a mix of East and West in each
of us now due to the cross-pollination of ideas over time.

The old ideology commanded us to accept the inevitable,
dance with the wheel of life... the world of the ascetic or
the fatalist.  The Western ideology is a bit more intrusive,
I think, with the idea that each person is an individual, with
value, and that struggle is meaningful, time is linear, etc etc.

On all human empires there will be swaths of competing
ideology, over history, work, wealth, rights, etc.

IMTU there are ideologies that come with each culture.
Cultural regions IMTU follow these rules of thumb:

Interior: Cultures are gathered in subsector- and sector-
wide regions (see the MegaTraveller books).  Some allowances
and prohibitions are valid for the entire region.  Expect local
corporate offices to be staffed significantly by locals, who
follow their culture.  Also expect a vocal minority of
protesters to oppose the seemingly arbitrary and unfair
cultural biases inherent in the culture.  Activist will call for
change.  Money will exchange hands, and political fortunes
will be won and lost.  People will die, and will either be
hailed as heroes or conveniently forgotten.

Interior cultural borders: On the borders of two cultural regions,
ideology will be an interesting, sometimes conflicting blend of the
cultures.  Expect there to be sporadic violence and terrorism.
Don\'t expect there to be full-blown war, because of the Imperial
Marines.  However, you can bet yer boots that some corporations
have "tradewars" more for cultural reasons than economic ones.
People will die, and will either further polarize the factions at
each others\' throats or will be forgotten.

Frontier worlds on the X-boat route: Expect these cultures to be
related to other cultures which were grafted to the boondocks
from the interior.   An important world will spread its culture
to neighboring worlds, and a cluster of important worlds will
probably have the same culture... or a few antagonistic ones.

Frontier worlds off the X-boat route: Cultures will vary wildly from
planet to planet, and even continent to continent.  Expect wealthy
worlds to have influence over their neighbors.  However, the frontier is
where you\'ll find all the fringe groups, off the X-boat routes.

- -Rob
