>You don\'t consider the Zho / Imperium relationship
>that of feuding superpowers? It fits the classic 
>example, down to the support of the conflict between 
>the Darrians and the Sword Worlds as sponsored 
>governments.

A superpower in contemporary times means a nation that
can effectively exert its will anywhere in the world
in a very short time, without any other power\'s
cooperation.  The United States is presently the only
nation with that capability.

In the Far Future, a superpower would have to able to
exert its will anywhere in known space in a very short
time, without any other power\'s cooperation.  Given
distances and travel capabilities, no power can be a
true superpower.  

Local regions may experience two or more great powers
as pseudo-superpowers, who have to be considered in
taking any action, but that still doesn\'t rise to the
level of one-world superpower capability.  

Another key difference between the recent past and the
Far Future is that no one in the Far Future has a real
and immediate ability to destroy all life everywhere. 


- --Glenn
