>>neccesarily descriptive) but even so, what happens when you\'re confronted
>>with a charismatic, nationalistic dictator, or ideology, or both?
>
>Some people become adherents of the said dictator/ideology many don\'t.
>The trick is to kill the adherents whilst leaving as untouched as posible
>those who aren\'t.


If you\'ll pardon my saying so, that\'s an awfully shallow view. Charismatic
dictators are not mesmers. They do not suddenly shift populations with their
stunning rhetoric. They are charismatic because they are a product of the
culture that they are making their appeals to. Don\'t get me wrong, I\'m not
saying that their actual *presence* doesn\'t matter. I\'m just saying that it
goes far deeper than that. Ideologies, on the other hand, are not simply
born overnight.

They accrete and develop over the course of long decades, even centuries.
Let\'s keep going with the Nazi example. It\'s a good one. You kill the
adherents. How do you find the adherents? There were hundreds of thousands
of German citizens who had no qualms about going out and killing Jews. There
were members of police and para-military groups who sent back pictures of
dead Jewish Poles - women and children and old folks - in the streets to
their wives and children back home.

There have been anthropological and sociological studies done which seem to
strongly point the finger not at any one leader, nor any one group of people
(indeed, those who participated in the really nasty and atrocious acts were
a decent cross section of the German populace), nor any general moral
breakdown on the part of the German people it was the result of a long
process and includes philosophy, religious development, folklore, political
movements, outside influences, and many, many other factors.

In other words, how do you figure out who adheres to an ideology and who
doesn\'t?

>>Least damaging to whom? The planet or the Imperium?
>
>Well if the goal is integration of the planet into the imperium I\'m
thinking
>that
>these are one and the same.


Not at all. After all, rocks are cheap, battle-dress, grav tanks and trained
operators are not.

>>If it\'s the former, dropping rocks is effectively the same as dropping
>>ground troops. You\'re still going to lose civilians, and it\'s more than
>>likely that you\'re going to decimate industrial centers. If it\'s the
>latter,
>>dropping rocks is a hell of alot cheaper and less time consuming than
>>dropping marines in battle dress.
>
>If you don\'t mind who or what you hit you can just drop rocks.
>If the historical record on strategic bombing can be used as
>an analogy for the rock dropping you propose then it won\'t
>be as effective as MIB and will result in a good many more
>civilian deaths.


So what you\'re saying is that nailing, say, a city of 10,000, at no danger
to the Imperium, is going to be different from entering into a ground war
that could have many, many more casualties and could cost the Imperium a
hell of a lot more?

>Maybe not Hitler but how about the Krupps? Or the general staff?
>Or even confronting Hitler in 36 or 37 when the wermacht was still
>A small and mostly obsolete force instead of the much larger army
>of 39.


Fair enough, but do you honestly think that bribing Hitler, or Lenin, or
Castro would have succeeded? Do you think that Hitler would have been
interested in money?

Besides, we don\'t need to speculate. There were many attempts to get Japan
to open up to trade after they closed themselves off. When China tried to
close itself off from imperialist Britain, they probably would have
succeeded. The only problem was that Britain resorted to nasty tricks in
order to keep up the trade, tricks that were, at least in my estimation, at
least as bad as nailing a population center or two.

>On the subject of Castro. I was going to go there but I won\'t.


It\'s a good idea not to, considering the fact that he\'s still in power. ;)

>>Just out of curiosity, how did we end up on the Marxist "peasant revolt"
>>line? It doesn\'t have to be "peasants" or "proles" who are doing the bulk
>of
>>the revolting at all. In fact, in cases like the American of French
>>Revolutions the peasants weren\'t even the real driving force behind the
>>rebellion.
>
>Either the planetary leaders or the planets population intend to leave the
>Imperium. If the leaders don\'t or if the leaders can be co-opted then
>that leaves everybody else. I\'m just trying to remind you that planets
>aren\'t political monoliths. Just because a group of plotters wants to
>seperate from the benevelent 3I doesn\'t make that the will of the
>populace. And just because the working stiffs want to suceede doesn\'t
>necesarily imply that the holders of political power will go along.


Well, no, it doesn\'t have to be either the peasants or the leaders. It can
be both, and the reasons can be deeply rooted in the culture of the people
on the world.

>>Actually, religious disputes, historically, have been among the least
>>"dirty" wars, depending on how you look at it. This may simply be an
>>accident of history, since the same force that allowed mankind to make
>>really impressive weapons also happened to marginalize those religious
>>institutions that would be able to make war to a great degree.
>
>I was thinking dirty in the sense of less likely to obey "civilized rules
of
>war"
>rather than more deadly per se.


Fair enough, although I\'m not sure that anybody *really* follows "civilized
rules of war" these days. Folks tend to avoid the nukes, chem and bio
weapons simply because they know that the situation will most likely
escalate to the point that they\'d be wiped off the face of the earth.

>Allow me to expand your reasoning here. Lets suppose that you drop your
>carefully limited rocks to enforce your will. Sure this works for a while
>untill
>someone says "Well they always stop short of causing real damage we can
>call their bluff."

Yep. No doubt.

>And sooner or later it escalates to needing to slag
>planets to
>prove you are willing to slag planets.

Nope, the Imperium only needs to do it a couple of times to prove that
they\'re willing.

>and eventually you can\'t keep the
>fiction
>of a benevellent Imperium going and lots of worlds and probably quite a few
>fleets rebel and the next thing you know....


I didn\'t know that there was a fiction of a benevolent Imperium.

>The war wasn\'t over untill the gropos had occupied germany. The fire
bombing
>of Dresden did\'nt materially hasten the occupation. Ergo the firebombing
was
>"more or less irrellevant...."


<snip>

>Again at that point it was obvious that the Japanese had lost the war.
>The question was at that point what concessions could they get from
>the US. The bomb just convinced Hirohito that all of his people would die.
>He ordered the unconditional surrender (which wasn\'t quite unconditional
>they got to keep their emperor). If this still supports your thesis (in
your
>opinion) well so be it.


Um... Okay, sure. In one case the war wasn\'t over until the infantry
occupied the country, in the other the war was over before the infantry
occupied the country. You\'ll have to excuse me when I say it sounds like
you\'re trying to have your cake and eat it too.

>I\'m sorry but the infrastructures of both countries were destroyed by
>strategic
>bombing (mostly) which is closer in spirit to your rocks than to my MIB\'s.


Actually, no. It\'s not closer in spirit to what I\'m talking about. I\'m not
talking about strategic bombing in any way, shape or form. I\'m talking about
the use of terror weapons. Two entirely different things.

What do you think happens when you let loose the battle-dress marines and
the grav tanks? Do you think the infrastructure of the country remains
intact? Do you think that the Imperium will avoid nailing strategic targets?

So, no. Strategic bombing is not what I\'m talking about here, not in any
way, shape or form.

>Also. The point I was trying to make is that we forestalled another war by
>A) Physically occupying both countries with large forces.


I\'m fine with the occapation angle, actually, considering the fact that
after the war was over the job of the infantry was no longer taking ground.
Would you consider what the Americans did in Japan after their surrendered
was "fighting a land war"? Same with Germany. Same with Kosovo right now.

It\'s something of a moot point anyway, because... (scroll down)

>B) Rebuilding the destruction we had caused in our attempt to drive them to
>their knees.


...the difference with rock dropping is that you don\'t *really* damage the
infrastructure all that much. After all, you nail a city and the civilian,
industrial and military infrastructure of that city is *gone*. Poof. Not
there to rebuild in the first place.

Compare that to the effects of a ground war, in which you\'re going to have
to destroy the enemy\'s industrial capacity if you want them to stop
fighting.

>The cost of these paliatives would far outweigh any monitary savings for
>orbital bombardment and the cost of not occupying/rebuilding would be
>the need to go back and do it twenty years later with the added bonus
>that more of your enemy will be convinced that you are evil.


People forgive and forget pretty quickly. Even ground wars can end with the
same kind of feelings that you\'re talking about. Take Germany\'s position at
the end of World War I, for example.
