ideological
> and nationalist wars of the twentieth century (World War I and World War
II)
> you\'re gonna find that the dirtiest wars weren\'t fought over religion at
> all.

You don\'t, of course, get wars that are fought for just one reason.  But
still:

Enter the Taiping Rebellion!   

The second bloodiest war in human history was fought in China between 1851
and 1864.  The body count has been estimated at around 30 million or so. 
The Taipings\' central leader considered himself the younger brother of
Jesus.  

Yes, there was a lot more to it than "just" religion, but that\'s true of
every "religious" war.

