    'body' => 'From: Robert Eaglestone <eaglesto@nortelnetworks.com>


>Who says Imperial culture is Western?


I always assumed that Imperial culture had some basis in Western culture
because the lingua franca of the Imperium is galactic anglic / galanglic,
the noble titles are taken from the Western tradition, and, most importantly
that the Imperium is firmly rooted in the genre of "libertarian sci-fi" with
its emphasis on merchant and mercenary style games.

Your own mileage may vary.

In my own Traveller Universe (the "Petty States" universe) the Interstellar
Wars were a war of words and ideas as much as soldiers and spaceships. The
assumption I\'m working with is that the Vilani tradition and way of life was
forced on the worlds of the Ziru Sirka. This view of the Ziru Sirka as
pretty much homogenous isn\'t really at odds with canon. The Terrans found
that information warfare, and I mean that in the truest possible sense of
the word, was extremely effective in getting individual worlds and systems
to shrug off Vilani rule.

Only one problem: Due to the fact that the Terrans rushed into the war, and
that Terra was still more or less balkanized, the ideas that made it to the
stars were not always compatible. In addition the manner in which different
cultures integrated these new Terran ideas into their own cultures was
frequently surprising. There were heavily Vilanified worlds with deeply
submerged cultures, for example.

The economic decline of the Second Imperium was hastened as a result of all
of this turmoil. That\'s where my own timeline diverges. The Long Night is a
period of wars, Renaissances, Enlightenments, Cultural Revolutions,
uprisings, insurrections, etc...

The Sylean Federation forms, turns into the Third Imperium... but the task
of taming the stars is considerably more difficult than Cleon thought it
would be. He discovers he doesn\'t have a monopoly on grand visions of
interstellar unity.

I\'m still working out the history and the details, but the end result (circa
1107 or so) is that there are quite a few distinct interstellar states bound
together in a web of alliances, treaties and obligations. Think of the world
on the eve of World War I...

Yep, I pretty much threw the Third Imperium out the window, because I\'m
starting to think that even without Terran intervention an interstellar
empire the size of the Imperium would be nigh-unto impossible to maintain,
or even attain in the first place. I\'m only adding in the Terran
intervention to provide some degree of familiarity for the sake of my Terran
players.

That\'s not to say that the familiarity will always be to their benefit. ;)

In communicating ideas and concepts between different cultures, there\'s
frequently some degree of "packet loss", if you get my meaning. Imagine
knowing how to read German, but not knowing how to read it very well. Now
imagine reading Hegel in German and explaining the philosophy to some
high-school student from a completely different culture who knows only a
little English and and who has had no introduction to, say, the philosophy
of Kant.

"So, what you\'re saying is that Hegel saw this Napoleon fellow on a horse
and exclaimed that he must be some sort of time-demon?"
