>I\'m not quite familiar enough to deal with the 
>American revolution, so I will just deal with the 
>French case.  Basically, the peasants provided the 
>bulk of the force behind the revolution, along with 
>the urban masses, the sans-culottes.  This is for
>the good and simple reason that the peasants were the

>_overwhelming_ majority of the French population.
>"Elite" revolts that face opposition need mass 
>support, or they will fail.

We should remember to distinguish between bourgeois
revolutions, like the English Civil War, the American
Revolution, and the French Revolution, and poor
peoples\' revolutions, like the Revolustions of Russia
(1917), China (1949), and Cuba (1959), and perhaps
some of the 1848 uprisings in Europe (and the Commune
of Paris).  (The far off topic question:  Do we
consider Russia 1985, and China since Deng Xiaoping to
be bourgeois revolutions?)  

Every revolution requires mass support to topple the
existing structure.  Who can get and keep that mass
support is the interesting question.

- --Glenn
