    'body' => 'On Sun, 21 Nov 1999 19:58:45 -0500
"Chris Seamans" <semo@pil.net> wrote:

>Yet, strangely enough "energy" ortillery will be alright, even though the
>effects can be exactly the same. There are plenty of strange rules of
>warfare in the real world, so I\'m not raising my eyebrows too much. So, what
>you\'re actually saying is that these various interstellar civilizations,
>each with *vastly* different views on... well, *everything* are going to all
>decide to play by the same rules?
>
>I do find that a little bit difficult to believe.

Strange though it may be, both sides in a war normally do play by the rules.
(Though when they don\'t is when things get *interesting*).
It\'s hard to describe why, except in vague terms, but think of it this way:

Actions have consequences.
Some consequences are undesirable.
Therefore your possible actions are limited.

The goal you are trying to achieve in combat precludes you from using
certain actions and tactics. For example, if you are trying to capture a
factory you would not use a nuke on the forces defending it. It would
destroy them but also prevent you from achieving your objective. So,
as a consequence, your actions tend to fit within what we loosely
call the "rules of warfare". The "rules" are not so much arrived at
by sitting down in a committee, but by what actions don\'t give
unfavourable outcomes.

Similarly on a strategic level, your ultimate goal will constrain what
lengths you can go to to achieve it. Read Clausewitz. Politics and the
military are intertwined. Political goals are behind all combat. Why
doesn\'t the IRA assassinate the queen? Because the *political*
consequences of that act would be undesirable for the IRA.

Now, though the various interstellar civilizations may have different
views about things they have many similar goals. Like survival.
Colonization. So, the technology and tactics used might be alien
but the objectives would be similar.

</FONT><FONT  SIZE=3 PTSIZE=14><BIG><BIG><BIG>
>If it\'s the former, dropping rocks is effectively the same as dropping
>ground troops. You\'re still going to lose civilians, and it\'s more than
>likely that you\'re going to decimate industrial centers. If it\'s the latter,
>dropping rocks is a hell of alot cheaper and less time consuming than
>dropping marines in battle dress.

Now, as to why near-c rocks don\'t get used in the Traveller universe
more often I have a simple answer.

Control.

No commander likes to have weapons under his command that he can\'t control.
Near-c rocks are about as uncontrolled as you can get. They take weeks
to prepare, can\'t be directed at small targets, and have an unpredictable
area of effect (because bits flake off before impact, the rock might
explode when it hits the atmosphere, etc). Worst of all for any commander,
once sent they cannot be recalled. Just as the poor sods you point it at
cannot stop it, eventually neither can you. If they surrender unconditionally
before impact, or you find they have something you need intact, or the
EMPEROR calls off the attack you *can\'t* do anything about it. You are no
longer in control of your own weapon.

No commander would chose to be in such a position, and no politician would
LET the armed forces get into such a situation.

It\'s sorta like the plans for an automated response proposed during the
cold war, where computers were to launch missiles automatically. The
idea got nixed/changed to keep the humans in the loop, so that they
could still *decide* whether to go to nuclear war or not.

Now, I\'m not saying that near-c rocks *cannot* be used in Traveller.
I\'m just explaining why, *by choice*, they aren\'t used more often.

Graeme Batho
