    'body' => 'From: Kiri Aradia Morgan <tiamat@tsoft.com>


<I snipped some stuff about religious wars as the stuff has already floated
around the list a bit. Those who have been following the thread already know
what\'s going on. Those who haven\'t been, I disputed the claim that
"religious wars" were among the dirtiest wars.>

>I think I\'m the one who started this by saying that religious wars are the
>nastiest and bloodiest, and I should have been clearer about what I meant
>by that.

I\'m not sure that your thread led into this one. It may have though. At any
rate, the cops will never prove complicity. ;)

>I should have said "ideological wars" but I was talking in
>shorthand-- while I have a strong faith, ideological wars exemplfy what
>bugs me about Religion with a capital R, which doesn\'t necessarily have
>anything to do with any real conception of God/dess.


Then the ground you\'re standing on begins to get less firm, at least in my
opinion. I don\'t mean that in an insulting way, but drawing lines between
ideological wars and non-ideological wars begins to appear rather arbitrary.
Ultimately, there\'s always going to be some at least *some* element of
ideology in any war.

What I\'ve seen begin to happen when a line of thought like this is used is
that there is a difference between ideological warfare and warfare which is
intended to annex or hold territory, depending on the side. I\'m not saying
that there\'s anything wrong with that, but it opens up a whole new can of
worms.

>I have a degree (MA) in History with concentrations in Medieval Studies,
>Women\'s History (don\'t hate me, I still shave my legs OK?) and History of
>Science and the Occult.


I don\'t mind Women\'s History at all, in and of itself.

>My favorite professor said that it was during the Crusades that people
>really began to make the intellectual leap toward dehumanizing others and
>that prior to this, even though there may have been a religious aspect,
>wars were fought mostly over territory.


As I stated above, I find it kind of odd when people try to delineate
different sorts of wars. All wars have an ideological component, and
frequently ancient wars had ideological components that are invisible to us
moderns.

For example, the culture of the ancient Greeks was one that was literally
*awash* with competing ideologies, religions and philosophies, as was the
culture of the ancient Persians, for example. The Persians and the Greeks
were two cultures which had a real difficulty seeing eye to eye in general.

You\'re right, though, there were distinct differences in how they viewed
other groups of people.

>When you are fighting over territory and you just want to take other
>people\'s lands and stuff away from them, you aren\'t going to salt the
>fields or use a nuclear weapon because you want to preserve what\'s
>there.


To some extent. It depends on the culture or civilization. Even predating
the crusades, though, you had some really nasty warfare. There is
archeological evidence that quite a number of cities were rebuilt and
destroyed many times as a result of many wars. That\'s hardly in keeping with
the theory that ancient wars were simply fought to capture intact land. Make
of it what you will.

To switch continents, the American Indians fought some pretty nasty wars,
and some of the customs that different tribes and nations had toward
prisoners of war were pretty different. Once you get down into Central and
South America things get pretty odd as well. The same can be said of Africa.

>Nine times out of ten you will restrict your predations on the populace
>to some degree because you will probably want them as servants.


Depends on the culture. Historical records tend to be all over the place
with regard to their treatment of the populace at large. Some wanted massive
armies of servants, some didn\'t.

>Wars of genocide and wars of mass destruction, whatever weapons are used,
>are always the wars that are fought over ideas, and religion was the first
>big idea that people were willing to fight over that way.


I can see where you\'re coming from. Still, genocide on a large enough scale
to make the history books is really *most* viable with modern technology.

>In the 20th century, of course, religion has largely been replaced with
>various ideologies in the industrialized world.  Capitalism vs. communism

>(though there is a lot of religious crap attached to both ideas-- there
>are fundamentalist Christians who talk as though the current economic
>system of the US were divinely ordained in the Bible, hahaha, and one of
>the things communists are most vilified for is the suppression of
>religion, which I hardly think is the worst thing that say, Red China, has
>ever done!) and other such ideologies, like religion, can be used to
>dehumanize the enemy.


The enemy *always* gets "de-humanized" though. When the Greeks warred with
the Persians they felt pity for the Persians, but still felt that they were
superior to them. By the logic of the day, the Persians would have been just
like the Greeks had they, too, been lucky enough to live on land with harsh
soil.

They still weren\'t as *good* as the Greeks.

<much snippage after this point, I\'m getting kind of tired and I suspect
that I\'d begin repeating myself to some degree>
