>>
>>I do find that a little bit difficult to believe.
>
>Strange though it may be, both sides in a war normally do play by the
rules.
>(Though when they don\'t is when things get *interesting*).
>It\'s hard to describe why, except in vague terms, but think of it this way:


Well, no, it\'s easy to explain why: all rules concerning modern warfare are
meant to stop the wars from escalating out of hand. You don\'t use nukes
because someone else out there has nukes and in a few hours you\'ve got a
really serious setback to modern civilization, to put it lightly.

After World War I, everybody was really horrified by how chemical weapons
had escalated out of hand. In World War II, interestingly enough, I can\'t
think of the use of chemical weapons on a large scale in World War II
(actually, I can\'t think of their use on a small scale either, but I\'m
hedging my bets here since there are quite a few people on the list with an
astonishing mind for detail) with the exception of the death camps, but the
dynamic was quite different from the battlefield.

>Actions have consequences.
>Some consequences are undesirable.
>Therefore your possible actions are limited.


Unfortunately, we\'re not talking about Earth here, where all of the
combatants are part of the same species *and* the same planet. The Aslan,
the Hivers, the K\'Kree are all radically different, psychologically.

Hell, if you accept TNE canon the Ithklur (the Hiver\'s pet troops) weren\'t
above *eating* the K\'Kree! ;)

The Vargr are at least descended from real dyed in the wool Terran
mammals... *but* on the other hand they can\'t really agree on anything as a
race, I\'m not sure why they would be able to agree on anything with folks
*outside* their race.

In the Imperium, the distinction is blurred between the Solomani and the
Vilani, although I think I recall that in canon the Vilani are all business
when it comes to warfare.

