  {
    'body' => 'I spent a few minutes looking over some of the Hague conventions and 
Geneva conventions online, and found an interesting detail:

In general, you only have to follow the laws of war if *all* your enemies
have agreed to follow them as well. You\'re still bound by things like
"International Law" and "the Requirements of Humanity", but some of
the more restrictive limits on such things as confiscating property,
handling POW\'s, or restricting collateral damage no longer apply.

Let\'s say A and B signed the treaties, and C didn\'t. If A and B have
a war, they are both obligated to follow the rules. If C has a war with
either A or B, no one is bound to follow the rules.

Here\'s the interesting part, though:
If A and B are having a war, and C allies with B against A, then
A no longer has to follow the rules - but B is still bound by them!!

ObTrav is a little fuzzy, as I don\'t expect these conventions to have
made it to the stars with the 2nd Imperium...but the odd side effects
treaties can have should make for some interesting plot twists.

Walt Smith
