    'index' => 'ee740',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Dr. Jerry Pournelle, in _King David\'s Spaceship_, points out that the
> horse collar eventually led to the end of human slavery as a routine
> institution.  [Note:  Figures used are from _KDS_.]  Before the horse
> collar was invented, a horse could do the work of five human slaves,
> because the harnesses in use at the time would strangle the horse if you
> had it pull too much.  Since a horse also eats about as much as five
> human slaves, human slave labor is reasonably attractive.  However, once
> the horse collar was invented, a horse could do the work of _ten_ human
> slaves, while still eating as much as five human slaves.  Given the
> obvious economic benefit of using horses for heavy work (twice as much
> work per unit of food), slavery becomes more rare, and is generally
> imposed on peoples thought of as inferior.  Once the Industrial
> Revolution began, slavery became even less viable economically, as
> machines began to replace human labor in many fields.

The big catch being that the horse could replace slaves as far as sheer
muscle power went. But when it comes to things where manual dexterity
is involved, the slave wins until fairly late in the industrial
revolution. 

Heck, stevedores were better than machines at several phases of loading
and unloading vessel right up until containerized freight caught on. 

The original reason the American South needed all those slaves was to
pick cotton. And that came about *because* the invention of the cotton
gin made it *practical* to raise huge amounts of cotton. Before that
there was *too much* hand labor involved in removing the seeds.

> Thus, S.M. Stirling\'s Domination of the Draka notwithstanding, I would
> not expect to see chattel slavery in a semi-rational technological
> civilization.  

Remember, the Draka are a *highly* unusual situation. They started out
with an "ideological need" for slavery after the ex-Confederates joined
them after the US Civil War.

