> or cultures that the referee comes from, modified by what historical
> reading the ref has done and what sort of SF the ref likes to read.
> This isn\'t particularly logical but it makes for better gaming.

Just consider the temptations for a ref who is interested in Japanese
culture, and is fond of Shogun and samurai movies. 

Now *that* would be an interesting Imperium. And oddly enough, you
could even justify it, by extrapolating from Japanese dominance in
various industries and their interest in space. 

Other possibilities:

Chinese Imperial bureaucracy.
Cultural Russians, "reviving" the Czarist model.
Roman Revival.

And so on. This planet has seen a *lot* of "empires" with rather
different details. Even *gross* details.

If you want to take obscure (but known) "empires" and make them the
dominant culture of some planet with it\'s own humaniti and have *them*
be what the Imperium is descended from, things *rapidly* get weirder.

If I won the lottery, I\'d be tempted to hire a few anthro majors and
dig up what\'s known about *all* the cultures on Earth, and see what we
could do in the way of trying to "grow" them into industrial cultures,
and then on to planet-spanning cultures, spacefaring cultures,
starfaring cultures, and finally to interstellar cultures. 

It\'d make for one *hell* of a sourcebook. Probably more like a *series*
of sourcebooks.

