    'body' => 'From: Alan Bradley <alanb@elf.brisnet.org.au>


>I\'m not quite familiar enough to deal with the American revolution, so I
>will just deal with the French case.


One has a devil of a time fitting the American Revolution into the peasant
revolt model, considering the fact that the closest thing we had to
"peasants" in any traditional sense were the slaves.

>Basically, the peasants provided the bulk of the force behind the
>revolution, along with the urban masses, the sans-culottes.  This is for
>the good and simple reason that the peasants were the _overwhelming_
>majority of the French population.


Overwhelming is putting it lightly ;)

The only problem being that the bulk of the action was really in the cities,
politically, philosophical, and physically,  and that\'s not where the
peasants were. There were a number of relatively minor peasant riots, and
the peasants seized the land from their aristocratic landlords, but after
that they really didn\'t really do that much.

It\'s even more complicated because the Gallup Poll wasn\'t yet in general
use...

"Our recent poll shows that 71% of the peasants in the field are in favor of
the revolution, 12% think that the Committee for Public Safety isn\'t
guillotining enough aristocrats, spies and political opponents, 6% wish to
be let alone and allowed to eat cake, 6% are against the revolution because
they miss the snazzy outfits the aristocrats used to wear before times went
sour and 5% are undecided."

Granted, I\'ll give you that it really helped that the various revolutionary
factions had the support of the peasantry... *but* as far as I understand,
that support really began to dwindle, and by the time things got bad enough
that they called in Napoleon, the peasants had little say in their destiny.

One of the real problems with applying a Marxist class-based model to the
French revolution is that classes, as such, didn\'t really exist in France.
Class structures are "horizontal". The social structure of France was
"vertical", or privilege based. Of course, a really proper Marxist
revolution requires a degree of industrialization, which was really slow in
coming in France.

It\'s tough too, because apparently the major scholar on the French
Revolution was himself a Marxist. Damn, I wish I could remember his name.

Anyway, while I have friends who are Marxists, one of the failings that they
tend to have is that they try to hang a Marxist interpretation on anything
that has something resembling a hook. I tend toward being a Skocpol fellow
myself, even though I\'ve got two major problems: One, I don\'t understand her
as well as I\'d like, and two I\'m not familiar with the various critiques on
her structuralist view of social revolutions.

>"Elite" revolts that face opposition need mass support, or they will fail.


Only if the "masses" actually have some sort of direct connection to the
elite. Of course, the French Revolution went through a number of phases, and
the peasants were pretty active quite early on. Later on, they sat it out.

>You don\'t, of course, get wars that are fought for just one reason.  But
>still:


Of course not.

>Enter the Taiping Rebellion!
>
>The second bloodiest war in human history was fought in China between 1851
>and 1864.  The body count has been estimated at around 30 million or so.
>The Taipings\' central leader considered himself the younger brother of
>Jesus.


Youch... It\'s interesting, though, I hadn\'t realized that Jesus was Chinese.
;)

ObTrav: You can have *lots* of fun with revolutions, especially when the PCs
are involved, even accidentally. All that the characters wanted to do was
deliver a package, now their ship has been impounded by the "people" and
their Imperial credits are looking really good to the population of the
planet, since the economy has gone hyper-inflationary.

Do the characters join on the side of the well-dressed aristocracy... or do
they raise their fists and say, "Down with The Man! Power to the people!"?
If you\'re using the French Revolution as a model you can toss in artistes,
such as David, and any number of philosopher types to really increase the
fun you can have. You could have the "Grav-Ball Court Oath"! Of course, you
can have fun with the later "minor" revolutions as well.
