    'date' => 'Tue, 23 Nov 1999 01:18:58  0800',
    'body' => '> From: "Chris Seamans" <semo@pil.net>
> Subject: Re: Traveller Navigation and Gunnery (longish)

> After World War I, everybody was really horrified by how chemical weapons
> had escalated out of hand. In World War II, interestingly enough, I can\'t
> think of the use of chemical weapons on a large scale in World War II
> (actually, I can\'t think of their use on a small scale either, but I\'m
> hedging my bets here since there are quite a few people on the list with an
> astonishing mind for detail) with the exception of the death camps, but the
> dynamic was quite different from the battlefield.

The Japanese made extensive use of chemical and bacteriological warfare
in China.  They had a large installation in the middle of the country
dedicated entirely to experimenting on Chinese prisoners (and some
Allied P.O.W.s) with new germs and chemicals.  Then they used these
germs and chemicals on troops and civilians.  One example I remember
involved putting mosquitos that carried some disease (probably malaria)
into big clay jars and dropping out of airplanes into Chinese villages.  

The scientists were never prosecuted as war criminals.  The bargain was,
they provided their research results to the United States and the United
Nations would not prosecute. If I recall correctly, some of them came to
work for the United States military, much as the more famous German
rocket scientists did.  

It\'s very well documented.  Last year I saw a quite horrifying
exhibition about it at the old navy base on Treasure Island in San
Francisco Bay.  If the exhibition comes to your town, go see it. 

- --Glenn
