  {
    'body' => '> From: "Chris Seamans" <semo@pil.net>
 
> One has a devil of a time fitting the American Revolution into the peasant
> revolt model, considering the fact that the closest thing we had to
> "peasants" in any traditional sense were the slaves.

> One of the real problems with applying a Marxist class-based model to the
> French revolution is that classes, as such, didn\'t really exist in France.
> Class structures are "horizontal". The social structure of France was
> "vertical", or privilege based. Of course, a really proper Marxist
> revolution requires a degree of industrialization, which was really slow in
> coming in France.

Marx referred to these as bourgeois revolutions.  They were the
revolutions that marked the transformation of European society from
agrarian/feudal to industrial/capitalist.  A class analysis still
applies, but the classes are the feudal classes -- basically the land
owners and the land workers, who split the production of the land
between themselves.  The classes in capitalist society are the owners of
the means of production and the wage-earning workers.  

- --Glenn
