    'body' => '> From: dadams@parracity.nsw.gov.au
> Subject: Re: Inetability of government failure

> There are still governments that still excist from antiquety (Tonga,
> Thialand,
> Mouri tribes). Yet well designed systems have collapsed (Communism was
> really well set up, just porly managed).

The communists didn\'t read Marx, or ignored what they\'d read.  Marx said
that communism can\'t occur until the forces of production are maximized,
and that _the_ way that the forces of production will be maximized is
through capitalism.  The major communist revolutions took place in
agrarian, semi-feudal societies (Russia and China), not industrial,
capitalist societies.  The forces of production in Russia were
inadequate to maintain a communist society, so it collapsed, along with
its many client states (some of whom were mature, but not totally
maximized, industrial states, like East Germany). 
 
China under Deng Xiaoping is trying to manage the process of
transformation from agrarian to industrial, from feudal to capitalist,
society.  A communist state and then a communist world (that will also
be a Chinese state and a Chinese world) are the long-term goals.  (Yes,
I\'ve read too much of the Chung Kuo series, and studied too much Chinese
history in college and graduate school.)

Marx never set a time line for the maximization of the forces of
production and the collapse of capitalism under the weight of its
internal contradictions.  The advent of interstellar travel and the
discovery of great new markets to conquer will extend the growth and
development of capitalism for a very long time.  

The form of economic relations in the Far Future have a feudal gloss,
but are still capitalist relations.  In the Imperium at least, the means
of production are privately owned, non-owners are paid wages in return
for the fruits of their labor, and government exists to maintain the
status quo.  

This sort of Marxist analysis suggests some questions.  What conditions
would indicate that the forces of production in the Imperium are being
maximized?  What internal contradictions are being experienced now,
compared to those described by Marx?  How much of a threat to the status
quo would an efficient communist or anarchist world be?  How much of a
threat would it be perceived to be?  

- --Glenn
