    'topic' => ' Tourism in the Marches (much ado about Whanga)',
    'body' => 'Ethan Henry wrote :-
> Yeah, true. I suppose a planet is a pretty big place, even a measly 
> size 6 one. I don\'t have the stomach to calculate how much "stuff"
> there would be after a few centuries of tourism, but it would be
> pretty manageable, sure.

Ballpark figure : average 200 grams per person, per day of solids and
1.5L of liquid. The big volume in sewage is the water used to flush the
stuff away.
	The big problem is going to be with other trash, in terms of quantity.
Fusion torches really simplify waste disposal though, IMHO.

> Terraforming the place with it is an interesting
> idea... (ski mount Crapmore!)
The sewage will be full of \'friendly\' micro-organisms. Consider it a
\'low-tech nanite\' approach to terraforming - spray the stuff everywhere.

> My only open question is that I wonder if the agricultural worlds of
> the Imperium notice the loss of biomass over time?
The only real problem, over the very long term (millenia, as planets are
BIG places) will be the loss of phosphorous from the biosphere. Enormous
reserves of nitrogen are in the atmosphere, and tectonically active
worlds will have carbonate-CO2 cycling. 
	Phosphate containing rocks could be mined or imported. Again, fusion
torching makes material processing and purification relatively easy.

> (On the other hand, Whangan
> potatoes would probably make a great crop off-planet... imagine crops that grow
> faster than the weeds.)
Or a great weapon. The local agricultural authorities (not to mention
environmental groups) would not allow such material off planet.

> The normal solution would be to apply a selective herbicide, but wow, Whangan
> plants are remarkably adaptable to herbicides and you\'ll run out of herbicidal
> formulations pretty fast (say, in a decade or so).
Whangan plants are unlikely to use chlorophyll, if you\'re using
Leonard\'s (Weber\'s) idea (which raises the possibility of non-green
plant life ; what colour is Whanga\'s sun?).
	Target this molecule with a poison, as well as a number of other
metabolic steps in the local plant life. This should be relatively easy
with TL8-12 chemical and biochemical techniques. 
	\'Combination chemotherapy\' will be irresistible for a few years until
you come up with some method of biological control (but without animal
life the latter option may be problematic).

Pollination of imported plants is the big impediment to their use if
there aren\'t any useful local insects.

> At any rate, the whole thig is just a handwave to explain why such an
> otherwise nice planet is being wasted on casinos and grav-ball stadia.
I think someone mentioned tax loopholes and other legal and cultural
wrinkles - the easiest handwave, IMHO.


Robert O\'Connor
Medico, Gamer
