    'body' => 'At 09:01 PM 11/22/99 -0500, you wrote:
>From: Michel Vaillancourt <misha@empire.atlantic-online.ns.ca>
>
>>        I would disagree with your assessment.  The Vargr are driven by a
>>requirement to boost thier own standing with other Vargr (thier Charisma).
>>*Any* idiot pink-stink can drop a rock on a world and say "Gimme money or
>>I\'ll do it again"....  that isn\'t going to do *anything* for one\'s
>>Charisma...  no bravery, no bold action, no fears faced nose-on....
>
>By the same token though, any idiot pink-stink can, say, point a gun, or do
>whatever might be required in their raiding operations. I didn\'t know that
>*specific* sorts of "heroic" actions were required for Vargr Charisma.

        Its not like there is a list in AM:3.  However, one of the remarks
made is that Charisma is something that is hard to maintain because it is
something that is *personal*...  which is one of the reasons that the Vargr
are so factionalized from the Imperial POV.  So, I\'d extrapolate from that
concept the idea that "push button warfare" is not nearly as good for
playing hero as "Cutlass in Paw" warfare.  To me, that\'s the essence of
Charisma...  having the guts to go somewhere and do something noteable *in
person*.  Don\'t be stupid, obviously, but we Terrans rarely toast the boys
in Bomber Command the way we talk about Buzz Burling or any other number of
fighter pilots....  one-on-one or one-vs-superior foe stories are always
more dramatic, romantic and heroic than "went there, got shot at, dropped
payload, got shot at, went home" stories
        (Note:  I am *not* belittling the Vets of WW2 Bomber Command...  I
have a great respect for them.  I *am* generalizing about pop-culture.
Please save flames for summer barbque\'s, I don\'t want them).

>Besides,  I thought that the Aslan were supposed to be the honorable ones.

        Honor and Charisma are two different concepts entirely.  They are
not mutually exclusive.  An Aslan might find Honor in a particular Vargr,
just as a Vargr might find a particular Aslan Charismatic.

>>        A planetary assault or a boarding of a high-port on a snatch and
>>grab, or a pack raiding an Imperial  convoy... now, that is a *whole*
>>different matter.  For Charisma to work, its *gotta* be up-close and
>>personal, and your friends have to survive to be impressed and brag you up
>>to thier friends.  That is why the Vargr seem so fragmented into such
>>dynamically composed groups;  individual quests for Charisma will conflict
>>in direction.
>
>Again, I\'m not sure I\'ve come away from Traveller sources with the same idea
>of Vargr that you have. Keep in mind, I\'m not saying that they\'re drooling
>evil nasties just waiting to drop rocks on any planet that they get the
>chance to drop rocks on, which has been one of the dangers I\'ve become quite
>conscious of over the course of this discussion.

        Fair enough.  I got the impression you were voting the Vargr race as
a whole to be in the #1 position for rock-dropping or other WOMD first-use.

>Actually, a big part of my understanding of Vargr comes from my research
>into the Sioux and the lower echelons of the New York mafia of the 70s (via
>the book Donnie Brasco).

        I\'ll defer to you here, as I have read neither set of material.  I
am going entirely on my own impressions of AM:3.  However, I believe that
the Amerind (Apache,anyway) concept of "Counting Coup" is an example of one
of the sort of ideas that go into Charisma....  being personally there,
personally brave and personally victorious, even if its only in sneaking up
behind some Cavalry Lt. and tapping him on the shoulder before you
disappear...  you could do it, you *did* do it, and now your friends are
impressed by it. 

>>        Dropping a rock just says you can use a computer to do math.  Going
