There were lots of flavors of Christianity in existence before the Council
of Nicaea declared all of the others heretics and produced an "official
version" that was strangely amenable to being used as a tool of
imperialist conquest by Constantine, who sponsored the Council.  Then the
official Christians went out and stamped out all the other versions and
did their best to destroy the holy books that all the other versions had.

This is one of the reasons that I can\'t personally accept Christianity
based on Scripture.  There was a hell of a lot of Scripture that got
thrown out; the Bible Christians have today was heavily edited and revised
by many committees hundreds of years after the death of Jesus and none of
the Gospels were actually written down sooner than 100-200 years after his
death, though they may have been transmitted orally.  And as these were
not primarily oral cultures, I don\'t particularly trust oral transmission
from the Jews, Greeks and Romans of that era.

We have not recovered anything close to all of the Gnostic Gospels.  While
I\'m sure some of them were bogus I\'m sure that the official ones, which
were heavily edited and revised, are not pure either.  It\'s difficult to
say, without all the evidence, what Jesus really was all about-- but one
thing that is historically clear is that there was a lot of uncertainty
even then, if you look at all the different varieties of Christianity that
existed prior to Constantine and all the different things they did.

Of course, people who have had personal experiences with Jesus are a
different matter-- I don\'t question the personal experiences of others,
lest they should question what happened to me in Gokokuji Temple (when all
I originally intended to do there was find the grave of Ozaki Yutaka,
