I think modern research on German post-WWI reparations is along the lines of:

- - Germany refused to pay reparations *and* repudiated the loans they had used to
pay reparations up to that point, *and* added to the problem by a massive
currency devaluation, and if you add up the numbers then in fact they
didn\'t pay much reparations at all to the victorious powers

- - Reparations still had to be made, in the sense that someone had
to pay for the infrastructural damage of WWI, final result being that the
countries which had suffered war damage paid for it themselves

- - Germany was never occupied during WWI, and for all the loss in manpower had
suffered very little damage on the home front, so effectively it ended paying
far less reparations than most of the other European belligerents, in the sense
that its own recovery was cheaper.

The end result of the supposed enfeeblement of Germany was that by the 1930s
it was once again a superpower, capable of massive rearmament programs,
intervention in Spain and elsewhere, and ultimately the initiation of a series
of conflicts culminating in global war. 

And the second result is that Germany was able to engage in these adventures in
part because it was surrounded, in the West, by those countries which were
genuinely enfeebled by the cost of the previous war, and in the East by a
subdivision of Austria Hungary into a series of statelets which could
individually offer neither threat nor resistance to a revitalised Germany, but
which on the other hand acted as an protective buffer zone for Germany against
the Soviet Union as Germany recovered.

Lesson being, "once they\'re down, make sure they stay down" (NB that doesn\'t
necessarily mean repression - for example one of the things not countenanced in
Wilson\'s redrawing of the European map in 1919 was substantive division of
Germany, other than anomalies such as Danzig and East Prussia).

