Back in the good ol\' days of EC Comics, there was a story in Weird Science,
I believe, and it concerned a similar scenario.

The Galactic Exploration Authority was doing its survey work. They
discovered one world in the early iron age and one of the scouts was dropped
off to learn about their culture, customs and language. On the way back
home, the rocket ship that had carried him was destroyed in an accident (I\'m
pretty sure it got whacked by a rock). All records that this scout had been
assigned to this job were destroyed.

The GEA scout was a nice enough chap, and he was disgusted by the conditions
on the world. He started doing the little things he could do to help. He
healed the sick with his advanced medicines, he fed the hungry with his
advanced survival rations. Word of his deeds eventually reached the upper
echelons of society. They had him captured and brought before them. They
demanded he feed and heal them instead of the wretched and the poor. He
refused.

So, many years later, the GEA detects atomic bomb explosions on this planet.
They send out a group of scouts to make contact with this world they had
apparently missed the first time around. Once they get there, they discover
an advanced civilization, in the midst of 1950s style progress. They see
important looking buildings with stylized funny-looking symbols adorning
them, and they see folks with these same little symbols around their necks.
Finally, one of the scouts asks his guide what the symbol means. The guide
responds by telling them it represents the torture rack their saviour was
killed upon.

Interestingly enough, although that story never came under fire, another
story did during the days of the first "Comics Code", another one did. This
concerned a scout visiting a planet in a full-body space suit. He contacted
the planet\'s civilization and found that a dominant group of aliens with one
skin color were oppressing another group with another skin color. They wish
to become part of the interstellar community, but he tells them that unless
they start acting like civilized beings they can\'t be allowed to enter. He
gets back on his ship and flies away. When he gets a moment to relax he
takes off his space helmet and it turns out that he\'s black, and that he\'s
crying.

The first Comics Code authorities demanded that the character in the story
be changed to a white man. The folks at EC realized that the Comics Code
fellows had clearly missed the whole point of the story and they dropped out
of the organization.
