    'date' => 'Tue, 23 Nov 1999 16:24:47  0600',
    'body' => 'Tim MacPherson wrote:
> 
> I am looking to pick up a starter set of Traveller. I used to have Traveller
> Classic ...yeeeears ago. Now there is all kinds of editions. I don\'t have a
> group ...so if I did play it would most likely be by PBEM. CT? GURPS? T:NE?
> T4?

Yes. Yes, to all of them. <g>

When playing in a PBEM you don\'t need access to a lot of mechanics,
you can depend on the GM for most of that. I have people in my
Traveller PBEM who have preferences for all the above, and I run it
very loosely with a mixture of rules. I think my players could tell
you which set I most favor, but they don\'t have to have that set of
rules to play, and if you asked them they\'d probably tell you I jump
all over the place, rule-wise. <g> OTOH, I play in a CT PBEM and an MT
PBEM, where the rules set is pretty obvious from how the GM runs
things, so, it can vary. IAC, any Traveller rules set is fine for
playing and any setting or background that you find interesting is
fine too.

About the various versions and all in my opinion...

If you liked CT, and want to keep playing CT then get Marc\'s reprints
when they are released and use CT.  Nothing wrong with CT, then or
now.  There isn\'t a rule for everything so you have to make it up on
the fly, but that just means it\'s closer to a "freeform rpg" which are
the rage now days. <g>

If you want to dig around you can find used copies of MT, which is
good, but filled with errata.  It is similar to CT in feel, but can
quickly get complicated. I like the concept of the task system, but
not how it was implemented...but that\'s just me. Like most things with
MT, some people love it, some hate it. You won\'t know how you feel
until you try it out.

If you liked Twilight 2000, then you\'ll like the TNE rules, but that
means using "other" dice, and some folks love their d6\'s.  The rules
don\'t "feel" like "real Traveller" to some people, but it does to
me...YMMV. BTW, you don\'t have to use the setting to use the rules,
and you don\'t have to use the rules to use the setting. <g>

If you like CT, but want a more streamlined game, get the main T4 book
and Marc\'s T4.1 extensions. Or even better, IMO, get Ken Bearden\'s
KBv2.0 rules for T4. Out of the box, T4 has some problems, but I still
think it had potential...again, YMMV.

If you like GURPS already, then Gurps: Traveller is what you should
get. If you don\'t like GURPS, then *some* of the GT books are still
good for background. If you don\'t know GURPS, then get the free GURPS
lite and see if you like it.

For setting, the CT reprints are going to be great when they make it
out. So, are the GRUPS books for the "no rebellion" timeline.  Finding
the MT and TNE settings books are harder, to be honest, and if you are
an oldtime player you might not want them anyway.

In the final analysis it doesn\'t matter what Traveller you get, or
play. Just that you play....and welcome back to the game. <g>

Eris,
