><Glenn>
>A superpower in contemporary times means a nation that
>can effectively exert its will anywhere in the world
>in a very short time, without any other power\'s
>cooperation.  The United States is presently the only
>nation with that capability.
></Glenn>

<Me>
>Please bear in mind I\'m *not* on a Yank-bash here.
>
>Based on that definition alone, would the US really be a superpower 
>?  Could they have exerted their will in Kosovo or Kuwait without the 
>co-operation of any other power ?  I submit that these are only military 
>examples of exerting a nation\'s will, and that there are many other ways 
>(cultural, economic, ideological to name a few) of doing so.  If your 
>friends and enemies alike (of whatever nation or state) decide they don\'t 
>like what you\'re doing, it ain\'t gonna get done, no matter who you are.
</Me>

<Kurt>
Depending on the force mix, it could have been launched from the US (B-1, 
B-2, B-52) or by Naval Aviation off of carriers in the Adriatic.  Not quite 
as practical, but doable.
</Kurt>

Oh yeah.  Militarily doable.  Politically ?

My point sort of was that if everyone else had said "We don\'t want you to do this" and then the US had gone and done it, what would the consequences have been ?  In order for a nation to successfully exert it\'s will, it *must* have the co-operation of other powers.  In the case of both Kuwait and Kosovo (and others) when that will was exerted, it was with both the explicit and implicit compliance of other states.  If the pre-requisite for a superpower is that it must be able to exert it\'s will with or without the co-operation of other nations, then no-one has, as yet, achieved that status.

