    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Ethan Henry wrote :-
>> Yeah, true. I suppose a planet is a pretty big place, even a measly 
>> size 6 one. I don\'t have the stomach to calculate how much "stuff"
>> there would be after a few centuries of tourism, but it would be
>> pretty manageable, sure.
>
> Ballpark figure : average 200 grams per person, per day of solids and
> 1.5L of liquid. The big volume in sewage is the water used to flush the
> stuff away.
>         The big problem is going to be with other trash, in terms of quantity.
> Fusion torches really simplify waste disposal though, IMHO.

Yes and no. Anybody dealing with a more or less "closed" ecology is
*not* going to run perfectly good "complex organics" thru a fusion
torch. They\'ve got *way* too much time and energy invested in that
"complexity" to turn it back into raw elements without a *really* good
reason. 

But with "waste heat" from a fusion reactor, extracting the the water
from sewage and producing a dry, sterile "sludge" is fairly simple.
Well, actually, you cheat a bit on the "sterile" part. Either from the
reactor, or from a radioisotope source you expose the stuff to enough
gamma radiation to kill anything in it. 

The result is damn good fertilizer, or at least the first stage in
making such. 

The one thing that you\'ll see on ships and in closed environments is a
seperation between OWW (Organic Waste Water) and IWW (Industrial Waste
Water). And a lot of *household* stuff goes in the IWW category. Either
that, or there will be *severe* restrictions on what you can dump down
the drain and what you can use as a "cleaning compound".

This is because lots of chemicals *really* screw up reprocessing.
Especially strong acids/bases, bleaches, and even a lot of detergents.
They "poison" the sludge so it\'s not useful for fertilizer, except in
*massive* artifical marsh type sewage treatment systems.

>> Terraforming the place with it is an interesting
>> idea... (ski mount Crapmore!)

> The sewage will be full of \'friendly\' micro-organisms. Consider it a
> \'low-tech nanite\' approach to terraforming - spray the stuff everywhere.

Alas, it\'ll also be full of *unfriendly* ones. Like all the diseases
and parasites that any visitor may have had. That\'s why you sterilize
it and *then* inmnoculate it with the organisms you *want* it to have.

>> My only open question is that I wonder if the agricultural worlds of
>> the Imperium notice the loss of biomass over time?

> The only real problem, over the very long term (millenia, as planets are
> BIG places) will be the loss of phosphorous from the biosphere. Enormous
> reserves of nitrogen are in the atmosphere, and tectonically active
> worlds will have carbonate-CO2 cycling. 

>         Phosphate containing rocks could be mined or imported. Again, fusion
> torching makes material processing and purification relatively easy.

Still, it tends to be cheaper/simpler to just dry, sterilize and ship
the "sludge" that isn\'t needed/wanted locally.

