    'body' => 'Date: Sun, 21 Nov 1999 12:43:54 PST
From: shadow@ (Leonard Erickson)

<Shadow>
Whoa!

You appear to be suffering from a common misconception. It\'s not
*possible* to keep things like nukes "secret" if they *ever* get used,
and it\'s fairly unlikely even if they *don\'t* get used. 

The scientific method ensures that if you ask the universe a question,
you get a truthful answer. So, once you *know* something can be done, a
research program *will* find out *how* it can be done. Period.

<Bits snipped>

</Shadow>

I\'d have to say I agree with the first of the above statements but not the second.  Two different (and seperate) entities seeking the solution to the same problem will come up with two seperate solutions.  Witness the response to AIDS several years ago.  When it first appeared in NY and San Francisco roughly simultaneously, doctors in both places came up with different solutions for keeping their patients alive, and explained the cause and transmission differently.

It may be that one group/individual who happens to be a leading light in the field has decided that \'it\' can\'t be done.  As he/she/it/they are the acknowledged expert, the rest of the population goes "Oh, well, fair enough" and \'it\' doesn\'t get done.  So, there may have been an enterprising Vagr scientist




The *only* reason the Germans didn\'t get the bomb was that (depending
on who you believe) either a research dropped a couple of decimal
points when calculating critical mass from the results of an early
experiment, or he *deliberately* fudged the result. Either way, they
wound up thinking that it\'d take *tons* of material to go critical. So
they figured a bomb was impossible. Anybody who *knows* bombs are
possible would take one look at that result and recheck the figures and
find the mistake.

Please note that of the more than a dozen countries with nuclear
capability, the evidence points to every single one of them succeeding
in getting a working bomb on the *first* try. 

Nukes are incredibly simple, and anybody that knows the physics behind
a fusion reaction can figure out that a fission reaction is possible,
and enough of the parameters to start research on building a reactor or
a bomb. And given a reasonable amount of time and resources, they\'ll
*succeed*. It only takes massive resources if you are in a hurry. 

So anybody over TL 5 or 6 (too lazy to check the books :-) can build a
nuke. It\'s no more "restricted" a technology than gunpowder and other
explosives. 

In fact, nukes are likely seen as merely a bigger bang, with some
unfortunate side effects. They may actually get used (along with damper
tech "clean-up") in some large civil engineering projects. 

I expect that the "no nukes" rule in warfare is actually no "weapons of
mass destruction". No taking out cities just because there was an
observation post in it.


