    'month' => '11',
    'body' => 'On Tue, 23 Nov 1999, Glenn M. Goffin wrote:
>> From: dadams@parracity.nsw.gov.au
>
>This sort of Marxist analysis suggests some questions.  What conditions
>would indicate that the forces of production in the Imperium are being
>maximized?  What internal contradictions are being experienced now,
>compared to those described by Marx?  How much of a threat to the status
>quo would an efficient communist or anarchist world be?  How much of a
>threat would it be perceived to be?  
>

Not much of a threat overall, assuming they stayed on the right side of the
Megacorporations. As long as they support the Pax Imperium, and allow Tukera
and company to operate freely (including resisting the temptation to
nationalise megacorporate assets) they\'re OK - you can see from looking at the
UPP data for the various sectors that the Imperium isn\'t really concerned how
authoritarian particular governments are. But the megacorporations are stronger
than individual worlds, so they also get a strong say. To that extent the
Imperium is a corporatist state along the lines propounded by Mussolini and his
chums.

Note this is for worlds with longstanding internal arrangements. How does the
Imperium respond to local revolutions?

In terms of the tendency of individual worlds to revolution, and looking at the
way the Imperial economy worked, you\'d have to look at those worlds which
combine high exploitation (ie responsible for a lot of manufacture) with a high
level of immiseration (represented by a low tech level?). On those lines,
Industrial worlds with low tech levels would be bearing the brunt of Imperial
era capitalism, and be most prone to periodic revolutions. If those revolutions
disrupted supply to other local worlds, or threatened strong off-world
interests (back to the Megacorps) then the Imperium might be tempted to
intervene.

