    'index' => 'ee854',
    'month' => '11',
    'body' => 'Dear Folks -

My apologies for a late reply to this thread.

Steven said:
>>Also see "The Circus" from E. E. "Doc" Smith\'s "Family d\'Alembert" series:
[snip]
>>In terms of the nobility and empire background, the series is very
>>Traveller-esque - or maybe Trav was influenced by this series? The nobility
>
>Trav predates that series, AFAIK (which was also very heavily contributed
>to by a co-author whose names escapes me - Goldin?).

My copy of "The Imperial Stars", the first volume of the Family d\'Alembert
decalogue, is copyright 1976. Even the 4th book goes back to 1977.

Stephen Goldin is listed as "co-author", but I agree - I have a feeling that he
is doing more than that. Probably compiling and expanding from a basic skeleton
of "Doc\'s" ideas.

Traveller dates from 1977. The nobility and royal family were determined some
time after that.

Here are some similarities between the d\'Alemberts and Traveller (Methinks a
"tip o\'the hat" to the series?):

a. Names

Family d\'Alembert        Traveller
- ----        ----
Emperor Stanley          Emperor Strephon
Empress Irene            Empress Iolanthe
Crown Princess Edna      Grand Princess Ciencia

Oh - and only the one heir, so that:
     (i) she knows she would inherit (and therefore not think about ways to get
rid of her father), and
     (ii) to prevent sibling rivalry over the throne.

b. Nobility

Here\'s what the first book says about the nobility:

"As one of her principled reforms, Empress Stanley Five imposed on society the
formal hierarchical structure still in use today. Given the fact that
stratification was inevitable in any social system, she elected to introduce the
arrangement that had served mankind the longest - that of hereditary
nobility(*). Her logical mind took what was essentially a chaotic state of
affairs and, in a sense, standardised it. All inhabited space was divided into
thirty-six Sectors, with Earth considered to be the centre of the sphere. Each
Sector is ruled by a Grand Duke, and may contain hundreds of planets. Single
planets are ruled by dukes. Marquises rule continents or the equvalent thereof.
Earls rule over what would previously have been considered states or small
nations., Counts rule countries. Barons - the lowest ranking nobility - rule
cities or districts."
E. E. "Doc" Smith (with Stephen Golding), "The Imperial Stars", Granada
Publishing Ltd, UK, 1976, p 79.

(*) Hey Jeff, here\'s another argument in favour of the nobility!

c. Cover Art

Chris Foss did the cover art for the series AND for T4. In fact, some of the the
same pictures are used, as follows:

Book 5: The Bloodstar Conspiracy     T4 Book G: Missions of State
Book 10: Revolt of the Galaxy        T4 Book ?: Gateway (Long Way Home Pt 2)

Oh yeah, and in all cases, the cover pics bear no relationship to the contents.
;-)

d. Equal Fights

There is no discrimination between the abilities of Jules and Yvette (an ideal
upheld in Traveller character creation, as opposed to AD&D\'s weaker women -
something, BTW, my gaming group *never* followed). Both are heavy-worlder
gymnasts, just as capable as each other. Oh, the *only* difference is that Jules
is the only thousand-pointer currently alive, while Yvette "only" scored 999 (on
S.O.T.E.\'s thousand-point ability test).

e. Scope

They keep saying "The Galaxy", but they don\'t actually mean it. The Empire
really has only as many (or maybe even less) systems than the Imperium\'s "11,000
Worlds".



Finally, the series is a masterpiece for all you conspiracy lovers. The whole
thing deals with the heroes and heroines uncovering the conspiracy, one piece at
a time. Even things that don\'t appear to be part of the conspiracy (eg. book 2,
"Strangler\'s Moon") are eventually tied in!

...and those who play TNE may find it interesting, as well. ;-)

(You\'ve now got me re-reading the series, blasters, stunners, nitrobarb and
all!)
