>I\'m very sorry, you must have me confused with someone else. I have never,
>in this thread, nor any recent thread, referred to near-c rocks. I\'m not
>talking about near-c rocks here. Keep that in mind as you read the rest of
>my response where I ignore the prefix "near-c".

So I went back to the source post to check:

Chris actually said:
>"Destroying a high pop world"... Geez, would people *please* stop putting
>words into my mouth when they reply to my posts? I\'m not talking about
>destroying high pop worlds. I\'m talking about dropping big rocks, not
>busting planets in half.

Sorry Chris, I missed that. I really thought you were talking about the
near-c things and addressed my response accordingly. I musta been having
a bad day.

Chris again:
>Why would rules against using big rocks be in place between interstellar
>civilizations, but not energy ortillery which serves the same function and
>can be just as damaging.

Both energy ortillery and deadfall ordnance are, I think, accepted canon.
Deadfall ordnance is (basically) the same as dropping rocks from orbit. The
old "smart rock" concept. Your big rocks are just bigger ordnance. Apart
from the (again practical) problems with moving large rocks, there would
appear to be no problems with using them. - Your point I think?

However, the Imperial rule against using weapons of mass destruction would
apply to using really BIG rocks, but not to the smaller deadfall ordnance.
So the question becomes; At what point do weapons become weapons of
*mass* destruction? Just how big a rock can you drop? I can\'t fully
answer this one; perhaps it\'s covered by a treaty between superpowers;
perhaps there is an arbitrarily set limiting size (mass); more likely in
the Imperium, though, the decision would be made AFTER the fact whether
the force used was appropriate or not.

And:
>The reason that we don\'t use nuclear weapons on earth is because using nukes
>can very well result in the end of civilization for everyone with nukes.
>Once the birds are in the air, say goodnight, Gracie.
>
>It naturally follows that there must be some reason for not using really
>heavy weapons in the Traveller universe, and it can\'t be the same. It\'s
>handled internal to the Imperium by the Imperial rules of war.

I think my point about the IRA covers this. Sure you could use really heavy
weapons against a planet without killing yourself in the process. But that
will make you very unpopular with a lot of people. Like anyone from the
planet. Like any megacorp with interests there. Like any noble (and their
supporters) who have an interest there. This would apply to planets even
outside the Imperium, which will have trade with and megacorporation assets
from within the Imperium. So the Imperium is unlikely to use weapons of
mass destruction against either it\'s own sophonts or any of the races
with which it deals.

As to the other races, even if they do not trade with the Imperium, they
would probably not use weapons of mass destruction against worlds in
the Imperium because they fear that both the Imperium and other races
would retaliate in kind.

SO FAR all the races found in the OTU have (for whatever reason) found it
to be in their own best interest to generally conduct wars without resorting
to weapons of mass destruction. At least, I don\'t recall anything in canon
that says they have. That does not preclude it from happening. Indeed, that
may be what the Zhodani et al found so disturbing about the Empress Wave -
perhaps they saw a race that was prepared to destroy without any inhibitions.

Graeme Batho
