No we don\'t! :-)

ObTrav: In my copious spare time (not!) I\'ve been trying to build the ships
from FSotSI with GT. Yes, I know the ships in there are broken (the CA-15 I
have been working on has a crew of 1079 but a frozen watch of 12!), but I
am trying to go with the spirit of the designs rather than the actual stats.

One thing I have run straight head on into is streamlining. Many Imperial
warships are streamlined, so as to scoop fuel from gas giants. However,
streamlining in GT takes away a whopping 20% of the ships internal volume.
At first I felt I understood the reasoning behind this (wasted space that
is too small/awkwardly shaped to be used for anything else). However, the
more I think about it, the less I am in agreement -- especially on larger
ships.

For example, take the 100,000 dton CA-15 -- a big, streamlined cone. By GT,
20% of this cone is unusable because of streamlining. Now where, I ask, is
this wasted space at? Surely on the scale of a 100,000 dton, even the nose
cone of the vessel would be large enough to be used for something.

It occurs to me in writing this that the streamlining penalty on volume may
be an abstraction to simulate the volume differences between a box on a
certain length and surface area and, say, a wedge. By this thinking, a
100,000 dton cone is not *really* 100,000 dton in volume, but is as long
and wide at it\'s largest dimension and has the same surface area as a box
of that size. But this seems like an unnecessary abstraction -- why not
just use configuration modifiers (as has been the tradition in other
versions of Traveller).

If someone could make a good case for the GURPS Vehicles/Traveller way of
handling streamlining, I\'d like to hear it.

Ciao,

Joseph R. Dietrich
yikes@evansville.net
