    'body' => 'Joseph R. Dietrich wrote:
> One thing I have run straight head on into is streamlining.
> Many Imperial warships are streamlined, so as to scoop fuel
> from gas giants. However, streamlining in GT takes away a
> whopping 20% of the ships internal volume. At first I felt I
> understood the reasoning behind this (wasted space that is too
> small/awkwardly shaped to be used for anything else). However,
> the more I think about it, the less I am in agreement --
> especially on larger ships.
<snip>
> If someone could make a good case for the GURPS Vehicles/Traveller
> way of handling streamlining, I\'d like to hear it.

This is a common mathematical  problem  called  "packing".  Given
fixed dimension items such as standard height  deck  squares  its
true that a portion of internal volume will be wasted in  awkward
shapes.  However, there are 2 important factors missed out here:

First, there is something called (I believe)  "gradation",  which
basically means that the smaller the internal objects  *relative*
to the area/volume they are to be  packed  in  the  less  overall
waste.  In other words the  larger  the  ship  the  smaller  this
percantage should be.

Second, some items to be packed do *not*  have  fixed  dimensions
(but do have fixed volumes) ... such as fuel  tanks.  These,  and
other items, can  be  packed  into  most  of  this  wasted  space
provided the architect is competant.

The GURPS:Vehicles method  of  20%  loss  works  okay  for  small
vehicles such as ground cars and aircraft but does not make sense
for larger vehicles.

The non-G:T Traveller method of modiifers (explained as  external
equipment cowlings, structural reinforcement,  and  airosurfaces)
is okay for medium sized vehicles (eg. the Kinunir).

But IMHO large vehicles  such  as  dreadnaughts  and  battleships
would be  so  unstable in  an  atmosphere  that  streamlining  is
pointless.

A quick fix would be to have the GURPS:Vehicles  percentage  vary
with overall volume ... becoming smaller and smaller  the  larger
the vehicle.  For added flavour this could be improved by a  task
roll against the architect\'s skill.



Regards PLST
