    'topic' => ' GT Streamlining (was  Taikonauts!)',
    'body' => 'Joseph R. Dietrich writes:
> I understand this, but that extra 20% makes a huge difference. In the
> CA-15, its about 2Gs of manuever capability and a bunch of armor.

The extra volume is only significant because jump drives are volume-based.  If you were to specify that only internal spaces count for jump drive mass (or to be even simpler, are used for jump fuel computations) most of the problems people complain about would go away.
> 
> As Anthony pointed out, "unstreamlined" hulls in GT are what traditional
> Traveller called partially streamlined, and "streamlined" hulls are
> airframes. So tell me ... should there be a "partially streamlined"
> category in GT to represent Traveller streamlined ships?!?

Nope.  Per GV, any GT ship not specifically designed otherwise is capable of entering atmosphere (which means only an idiot builds streamlined merchants, but...).  The difference is that with less than the level of streamlining which is considered \'streamlined\' per GT, they must move at subsonic speeds (or disintegrate) while in atmosphere.

To be honest, most \'streamlined\' CT designs are basically unstreamlined, judging by the illustrations.
> 
> So *why not* name it like it is? IMHO, unstreamlined in GT should be just
> that: a hull with no streamlining. Streamlined hulls in GT should have
> basic streamlining, and not airframes. Airframes (and partially streamlined
> hulls) should be seperate categories.

Too late to really errata this one.
> 
> Hopefully this will be addressed in the upcoming goodies from SJG.
> 
> And it seems to me that Peter\'s comments on "gradation" should be taken
> into account when figuring streamlining for large hulls.

As the \'streamlining\' volume for a ship is actually outside the hull, no, not really.
