    'month' => '11',
    'index' => 'ee920',
    'body' => '> Date: Tue, 23 Nov 1999 19:46:31 -0800 (PST)
> From: Kyle Schuant <kyle3054@yahoo.com>
> 
> Okay, now William Hostman has alluded to a point
> that\'s always concerned me: the huge cost of Traveller
> ships. Millions always seemed ridiculous to me. It
> makes trade simply uneconomical. I think of the PC
> ship as a rather casually-run business.

PC ships may (often) be, but as usual, PCs are not typical.  Ask anyone
who has started his or her own business; the initial years (and often the
years after that) consist of 18-hour days and a constant struggle to keep
things in (or even near) the black.  Remember that a majority of new
businesses fold within two years.

The various trade systems are rather well-balanced with the cost of
shipping to make bulk cargo- and passenger-hauling by small ships a slow
path to bankruptcy.  This is both intentional and realistic; there\'s no
way 200-dton tramps are going to compete head-to-head with Tukera on
moving bulk machine parts along the Spinward Main.  Small merchants
succeed (if they do so) by filling niches the majors don\'t or can\'t
address -- charters, speculative cargoes, service to backwaters, that sort
of thing.  Adventure seeds, in other words. :)

Look at it this way:  Any mature business sector in a capitalist society
is going to be \'marginal\' (in the technical sense).  If ships were
cheaper, more of them would be operated until shipping prices fell to the
point that revenues were again hovering near the break-even point.

> Most businesses either start in credit (having savings to invest),

If the characters have alternate sources of capital, there\'s nothing to
stop them from arranging a shorter-term loan with a larger down payment,
or even purchasing a ship outright.

> or expect/hope to clear their original loan within 10 years, and make a
> living in the meantime. 

Not usually true.  Business investments may be amortized over spans of
decades.  And making a living is a separate (though related issue. 
Basically, for a privately-held business, you take your net revenue, pay
your operating expenses, service your debt, pay your minimal living
expenses, and then take what\'s left and either give yourself a bonus,
re-invest it in improving the business, or (most commonly) some mix of the
two. 

Note that a merchant company/ship which is doing well will probably be
able to refinance ship loans under more favorable credit terms.

> Naturally, those that succeed don\'t take the extra
> thousands a month they\'ve got from having paid off the
> loan and just spend it, they expand their business...
> (get a better ship?)

Or hire broker services on key worlds, or improve the current ship(s), or
establish permanent facilities, or...

> Obviously when natural lifetimes are longer at higher
> TLs, you\'ll be willing to have debt for longer, but
> still! T4 gives 40 years as the typical time...
> sheesh! If you need 20% down, why would you get that
> brand new 20 MCr ship when you could get a second-hand
> "engineer\'s dream" for 2 MCr?

Again, in a free market prices will tend to equilibrate at the point where
the total expected cost of ownership and book value for these correlate to
the asking price.  If the 2MCr ship is a net better bargain, demand for it
will rise, and sellers will raise their prices accordingly.

> Finally, I never bought the business of "we have ways
> of making you pay." How does a bank foreclose on a
> mortgage if the residence has Jump-3?

How do finance companies foreclose on cars which can drive away at high
speed?  You catch them when they\'re parked.

> And I don\'t want to hear about transponders and "late payment messages
> stopping the engine." If an engineer put it there, another engineer can
> remove it! 

No, it doesn\'t require tech wizardry.  Your ship puts down on Regina, and
during the week you\'re arranging cargo, a repo agent scanning the arrivals
list matches your transponder ID against the skip list, and files a notice
of repossession with the courts and port master.  She\'s worked on knowing
the right people and processes to expedite this.  Two days later the
impound docs are approved.  The first you know about it is when she (and a
few port security folks) walk up to the ship, ask to speak with the owner,
and hand you a thick envelope full of intimidating-looking legal papers.

Now you\'ll probably get a hearing with an admin judge, who will determine
that you\'re in default and give you 3 days to have personal belongings off
the ship.  Alternatively, you can take off without permission, blow
through the TCA and orbital traffic pattern, and run for it.  Now you\'ve
gone from being a deadbeat to being a wanted high-level felon (you
endangered a lot of lives, doing that, and stole the finance company\'s
property).  On some worlds, local air or space units may shoot at you if
they\'re positiioned well to do so on your way to jump.

Not a good thing.

So if you decide to skip, or if you\'ve done the break-and-run option
above, your only real hope is to go far, far, *far* away, outside Imperial
space.  While getting there you must avoid any legitimate starport, patrol
cruisers, and so forth.   Depending on how far you are from the border,
and which border that is, your chances range from poor to nonexistent.
Alternatively, you can \'go pirate\' -- stay inside the Imperium, perhaps
near your original area of operations, but operate clandestinely, avoiding
all contact with authorities (and civilians looking for reward money).
Again, I\'d have to say your odds of lasting long aren\'t good, especially
after that jump core failure that could be fixed in two days at a Class-A
port, but...

