    'topic' => '3D jump ranges - A solution',
    'index' => 'ee939',
    'month' => '11',
    'body' => 'Someone mentioned the idea of not having a J2 drive having twice the
range of a J1 one. This would (if done right) fix the problem of
reaching too many stars with an average jump drive.

I thought about this, and decided to calculate exactly how long range a
J1 (and J2 etc) drive should have in order to preserve the same
relationship between jump rating and number of possible destinations as
in canon.

First of all, I counted the number of possible destination hexes
(regardless of they contain a star or not) from one hex using different
jump ranges. For J1 to J6 drives, the number of destination hexes are 6,
18, 36, 60, 90, and 126. Thus, a J6 drive should be able to reach 21
(126/6) times as big a "destination volume" as a J1 drive, and so on.

Since a sphere with n times the volume of another sphere has a radius
that is [the cubic root of n] times that of the other sphere, it is
quite easy to figure out how big the jump ranges should be. I assume
that the range of a J1 drive is 1 parsec. If another basic range is
desired, just multiply all the ranges by the basic range (in parsecs).

In the table below, the symbol * means "cubic root of"

Jump rating   Jump range
===========   ==========
    J1            1
    J2           *3 (1.44)
    J3           *6 (1.82)
    J4          *10 (2.15)
    J5          *15 (2.47)
    J6          *21 (2.76)

/Jens \'Spacejens\' Rydholm
