    'topic' => ' Tourism in the Marches',
    'body' => '> Date: Wed, 24 Nov 1999 15:59:35 -0500
> From: Ethan Henry <egh@klg.com>
> 
> Not being an astronomer, where\'s the peak of Sol\'s light output 
> in the visual range and where the same peak for an A star? Presumably
> Whangan plants have their colour shifted similarly.

Not (necessarily) so.  Sol\'s peak output is in the green part of the
spectrum...the precise part that chlorophyl *reflects away* rather than
uses.  On Earth, it happened that the best sunlight-capturing chemical
evolution came up with had this disadvantage; it made up for the problem
by being more efficient at using the photons it did absorb, being
\'cheaper\' to synthesize, less prone to chemical attack, and so forth. 

An A star\'s peak output is in the blue-violet part of the spectrum, but
(like Sol\'s) it\'s a very broad peak.  It would appear "harsh blue-tinged
white" to the eye.  Note that brightly-colored stars are a rarity; normal
stars are simple black-body radiators with broad spectral peaks.  So an M
star isn\'t the glowering blood-red fireball we\'ve seen in too many
illustrations; instead, it\'s pretty much the same color as a 100
watt lightbulb running at about 50 watts of input power, a sort of
brownish-reddish-yellowish-white.

