    'topic' => ' Loans and Indentures',
    'body' => '> Date: Wed, 24 Nov 1999 13:53:31 -0800 (PST)
> From: Anthony Jackson <ajackson@molly.iii.com>
> Subject: Re: Loans and Indentures
> 
> Craig Berry writes:
> 
> <sane economics snipped>

Woo hoo, my minor finally pays off. :)

[snip argument leading up to...]
> If you make a 100 T ship actually normally weigh in the 100T range
> (which means, depending on version, a 5-10x reduction in volume) it
> becomes a lot less unreasonable; drop the electronics correspondingly,
> and you start seeing prices which are only in the few millions; still
> expensive, but much more believable than the 20-40 million for a free
> trader.  Actually, a 5x reduction in volume makes things like staterooms
> come much closer to real-world sizes. 

Dropping electronics is a question of what you think can be dispensed with
safely (or safely enough to satisfy potential passengers, freight agents,
starport authorities, and crewmembers).  Dropping volume, though, comes
straight off the bottom line; smaller ship equals smaller hold and
passenger quarters equals smaller revenue.  It does little good to reduce
ship payments by a factor of 10 if you also cut operating revenues by a
factor of 10.  In fact, it will hurt; certain fixed costs become more
relatively important when the volume is small.

To put it another way, one could express the business environment of a
ship in terms of its fixed expenses (e.g., crew salaries) and an
expected net revenue per dton of hold and passenger quarters.  The latter
is what you get when you subtract the revenue you expect to obtain by
using that dton for commerce, minus the costs of operating that dton
during the period (life support, etc.)  Note also that the size of the
debt payment will scale with the size of the hold/quarters; for
simplicity, let\'s call it linear.  So we derive

  P = V * H - V * D - F

where P is net profit, V is the ships\'s volume available for commerce on
some arbitrary scale, H is the expected net revenue per dton of commerce
volume, D is the debt payment per dton, and F is the ship\'s fixed
expenses.  Simplifying gives us:

  P = V * (H - D) - F

That H - D term simply tells us that if each dton can\'t earn enough
revenue to pay for itself, we\'re hosed from the start.  Note, however,
that in the limit of zero volume, the ship loses F credits per period.  As
V increases, we hit some breakeven point, and as V increases further, the
ship becomes profitable.

Which just reiterates what we all know already:  Economies of scale exist.
Large ships are more profitable per dton than small ones.  Small tramp
merchants are screwed if they try to compete with the big guys.  And
Anthony\'s super-small tramps will have to find even more specialized
niches where not even \'normal\'-sized tramps can operate.

To put it yet another way:  Nobody ever gets rich doing standard book-3
trading in a Type S, and you don\'t even need to make payments on those. :)

