    'month' => '11',
    'index' => 'ee960',
    'body' => 'William Hostman wrote:

IMTU, it\'s fairly simple: Banks won\'t finance J5 or J6 ships. Period. J4\'s
will only be financed when there is a viable collateral OTHER THAN THE SHIP.
J3 ships require a good buisiness plan, and while anything put in can be
removed or replaced, if you can\'t outrun the news, you\'d better keep the
payments in line. Most of the "Pirates" (by cgen career) are actually skip
tracers most of the time, starmercs when needed, and privateers when
available. The banks tend to send J-4 messages when a ship makes it\'s
payments, to all payment acceptance stations within 2 months hard travel
from point of payment. Most worlds maintain lists of ships in the area; if a
ship is more than two months out by local computations, they prepare a skip
alert... Not that they announce the ship has skipped, but that customs needs
to check for papers (if the law level allows) or the bank hires a skip
tracer to "take a look"; most (almost all) ship financing allows the banks\'
local agent to inspect or authorize inspection by their deputy as "part
owner". If the agent finds proof of payment, fine, he\'s got to leave.
Otherwise, including if the crew refuses access to the papers and/or ship
after seeing appropriate credentials, the agent may reposess the ship "On
suspicion". I only did this to a PC group once... it ended the campaign
(They wound up confined to an imperial prison world, since the note holder
was the Imperial Government, and the "Tracer" was an IMOJ field agent...
whom they shot.)
Since I use the "pirates" as skip tracers, it gives reason for banks to
subsidize or even finance pirate vessels... field authorizations! And a
letter or Marque and Reprisal, with clauses allowing inspection of records
of vessels financed by a given bank, or government, and siezure if not able
to prove current payments. That, and the pirates keeping tabs on skip
reports.

* * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * 


IMTU I handle payments thusly;

If a vessel has payments remaining, the vessel has to go to a Bank branch
every payment date to get the running codes for the ship (codes for the next
two years are X-boated to branches once the papers are signed). If this date
is missed by more than two weeks (and vessel is not in Jump, has not
suffered a malfunction preventing one or is not empty of enough fuel for a
jump), then jump drive will be disabled and \'registered\' weapons be not able
to fire. This is designed to prevent the vessel from skipping. 

However, banks do give permission for those with payment\'s owning, to
receive codes in advance, if they are going to be outside the interstellar
state where the bank is located (such as the \'outback\', for a Sylean M0 or
over the frontier for a M1120 Imperial ship). Obviously there has to be a
good reason and the vessel\'s owner\'s have to give a proposal (many
\'regional\' bank officers ask for a 5-7% commission on any profits made on an
\'outside\' trip . Some even might send a clerk to keep an eye on things). 

There are some rogue independent worlds (such as Class A or B star ports
with low pop and govt. but high tech far from interstellar states) that
offer \'code\' cracking or re-configure services, but these are likely to be
very expensive and are highly illegal (look, an adventure!) 

Re-payments are made every month. The cost is 1/240 of the cash price (new)
for the ship. If extra payments are made, then the monthly payment is
reduced concurrently (work it out on a spreadsheet or something). Banks
require proof of ability to finance re-payments, so this might make non
merchant vessels a tad tricky to fund ("So you want to buy a patrol cruiser.
How will you be funding the payments?" . . . "I\'m going to . . . er . . .
become a pira . . I mean an escort, yeah, an escort . . . matey!")

Michael 
