    'ts-index' => '1999-11-24.ee964',
    'body' => '>One thing I have run straight head on into is streamlining. Many Imperial
>warships are streamlined, so as to scoop fuel from gas giants. However,
>streamlining in GT takes away a whopping 20% of the ships internal volume.
>At first I felt I understood the reasoning behind this (wasted space that
>is too small/awkwardly shaped to be used for anything else). However, the
>more I think about it, the less I am in agreement -- especially on larger
>ships.

David Pulver (the designer of the GT starship design system) says that in
GT the USL hull is equivalent to a MegaTraveller Partly Streamlined hull.
In essence, it is not streamlined, but you can still travel at a reasonable
speed if you have contragrav. You have all the aerodynamic lift of a brick,
of course.

Here are the conversions:

GT	MT
SL	streamlined
USL	partly streamlined
PL*	unstreamlined
DS*	unstreamlined

* Planetoid and dispersed-structure: coming in future GT books.

GT: Starships will include a better explanation of this, as well as more
details on things like fuel scoops, jump grids, and the like. Chris Thrash
is writing it, and the draft is quite nice. Buy a Pyramid subscription to
be on the playtest team (when it hits playtest, which should be pretty
soon).
