> William Hostman wrote:
> 
> IMTU, it\'s fairly simple: Banks won\'t finance J5 or
> J6 ships. Period. J4\'s
> will only be financed when there is a viable
> collateral OTHER THAN THE SHIP.... The banks tend to
send J-4 messages when
> a ship makes it\'s
> payments, to all payment acceptance stations within
> 2 months hard travel
> from point of payment. Most worlds maintain lists of
> ships in the area; if a
> ship is more than two months out by local
> computations, they prepare a skip
> alert... Not that they announce the ship has
> skipped, but that customs needs
> to check for papers (if the law level allows) or the
> bank hires a skip
> tracer to "take a look"; most (almost all) ship
> financing allows the banks\'
> local agent to inspect or authorize inspection by
> their deputy as "part
> owner". If the agent finds proof of payment, fine,
> he\'s got to leave.
> Otherwise, including if the crew refuses access to
> the papers and/or ship
> after seeing appropriate credentials, the agent may
> reposess the ship "On
> suspicion". I only did this to a PC group once... it
> ended the campaign
> (They wound up confined to an imperial prison world,
> since the note holder
> was the Imperial Government, and the "Tracer" was an
> IMOJ field agent...
> whom they shot.)
> Since I use the "pirates" as skip tracers, it gives
> reason for banks to
> subsidize or even finance pirate vessels... field
> authorizations! And a
> letter or Marque and Reprisal, with clauses allowing
> inspection of records
> of vessels financed by a given bank, or government,
> and siezure if not able
> to prove current payments. That, and the pirates
> keeping tabs on skip
> reports.
Kyle replies:
Sounds all rather well-organised. I just can\'t imagine
it working that efficiently. To me, it seems rather
like a 15th century Florentine bank lending money for
a ship to do speculative trading in the East Indies...
"I\'ll be back, really I will!" Hmmm....

> If a vessel has payments remaining, the vessel has
> to go to a Bank branch
> every payment date to get the running codes for the
> ship... [etc]
Again, I don\'t quite buy it. Codes are crackable. If
your PCs have among them an engineer, it\'s going to be
his first priority, I\'d imagine. This is particularly
so if the ship is worth millions. Most crime is either
really petty (VCRs, TVs, marijuana), or really big
(insider trading). The PCs will want to skip payments,
temporarily or permanently, if it\'s a matter of a
thousand creds or less ("who cares about that
little?"), or a million creds or more ("think of what
else we could do with that money..."). 

I\'m thinking here of the Cash Value to Hassle Ratio.
When this is high, the likelihood of crime is also.

> There are some rogue independent worlds (such as
> Class A or B star ports
> with low pop and govt. but high tech far from
> interstellar states) that
> offer \'code\' cracking or re-configure services, but
> these are likely to be
> very expensive and are highly illegal (look, an
> adventure!) 
Again, what NPCs can do, PCs can do... though it may
take longer and be more expensive in buying computers,
etc...

****Re: Solutions to dilemna****
IMTU, ships are heaps cheaper... but then, I was using
the TU before G:T came out, using GURPS rules, the old
GURPS: Space... with the spaceship construction rules
there. _Much_ cheaper than CT et al...

I make available "engineer\'s dreams" (like the
"renovator\'s dream" in real estate) with the
occaisional unpleasant surprise.

Further along this road, there may be those among you
who know of this beach in India, I forget its name,
where old unseaworthy ships get run aground. A whole
city has grown up around the scrap industry there. I
figure the same will happen in the future. Some ships
get dumped in space or suns, but some get landed on
this planet... A small desert world, almost mined out,
only a few desperados live there... and old ships get
dumped in a 100x100 km area... the local government
charges mainly by the ton.

It\'s an adventure for the PCs, scrounging around. It\'s
great for starting groups, I tell them what\'s
available, and they tack together a spaceship out of
it all... not high-tech stuff, but the host planet
charges very little for it. In traditional GURPS rules
it was relatively easy, with advantages, for a party
to scrape up half a million or so, and they were able
to get a mediocre free trader out of this. A
"character ship" for them... starting off with no
staterooms, just blankets on the floor... Maybe
someone had a Contact or Ally in the local Imperial
Shipyards, so they were able to get a decent computer
(or they could stick with their TL6/7, two dozen
parallel-wired 286 type machines)... and so... thus,
ship construction becomes an adventure in itself, and
they get to learn about the ship construction system,
get explanations of what a meson gun is, and so on...

