    'ts-index' => '1999-11-24.ee985',
    'date' => 'Wed, 24 Nov 1999 23:31:45  0900',
    'body' => '>At 12:39 AM 11/24/99 -0600, Black ICE wrote:
>>Seriously, one of the quibbles I have about the various ship design
>>sequences in Traveller is that one gains no extra benefit from
>>increasing the number of computers (over the required number) linked
>>into ship operations.  Perhaps for each additional doubling of computing
>>power, the crew requirement could be halved.
>>
>>Feedback, anyone?
>
>My experience at work shows that an increase in computers in no way allows
>us to lay off experienced programmers, engineers, or even program managers.

In my line of work, automation HAS reduced the number of people required to
do the job. I just finished laying out a book, in page maker. The actual
layout took a mere 100 work hours (counting re-layouts due to editing
changes). If it had to be done by manually laying out type for the final
and proof, and retyping the pages for the various (20) drafts.

>We don\'t have anyone typing up dictation, and we could get rid of the mail
>room easily enough though.
>
>Steward is the only job I can think of that could be replaced by a computer.

Steward is the only one I can think of that CAN\'T be replaced by
automation. Since stewards have to handle customers, handle paperwork,
load/unload/ballance cargo, and provide for the cooking and cleaning
services... Yes, automation might reduce the efforts in paperwork,
loading/unloading/ballancing cargo. But not in direct customer service
areas.

Navigators could be replaced by extensive automation, provided there are no
legal impediments.

Engineers, under normal conditions, could be automated out of the loop,
again subject to legal requirements; damage repairs are NOT "Normal
operations", but routine maintenance could be automated to a large extent,
especially if one installs robotic manipulators that are close enough to
work on each other, too.

Pilots can be automated, too. Most piloting tasks would logically be little
more than triggering the autopilot and setting the correct waypoints; with
GPS good to 2m (There was a shot of some military engineers useing a GPS
reciever to set a survey marker, and it was on broadcast TV! Those are
supposed to be field set to within 10cm... draw your own conclusions), you
should be able to fly a ship that\'s 15m + in length on a landing pad fairly
accurately by using 2 or 3 GPS\'s. In theory, the GPS system should be
accurate to 5cm... once outside orbit, there really isn\'t much in the way
of piloting that couldn\'t be done on an apple IIe, with the correct
parameters and software. Even Jump Piloting can be automated, see also Jump
Tapes for proof in canon: Jump Tapes require no Pilot/Nav roll, just the
engineering rolls. In fact, I\'m aware that in the simulators, they\'ve been
able to plot autopilot courses for P-3\'s that simply reuire the pilot to
take over to do the flare and lower the gear.

Gunners: Gunners can easily be automated; in any real space combats either
ranges will be far enough that you\'re shooting on Probability of Contact
volley solutions, or close enough that the relative speeds will probably
make humans useless. Exceptions for orbital ranges. You need someone to
tell the auto-gunner whom to shoot, and whom not to. And in most cases, if
a gunner can line it up, a computer can line it up faster. Based upon the
few canopn descriptions, gunners don\'t actually fire the weapons anyway,
but rather select the target, and disengage the safety so the computer can
fire at the right point. Why have gunners? So you have someone to lay
liability on, and to perform maintenance on the gun. Maintenance can be
done by robots, or robitic parts linked into the computers.

Medical: Medicine really has expanded due to automation... but medicine as
a technology-intensive field is still not bloosoming in the same way office
work has. Computing power allows better manipulation of medical imaging
systems. It allows better (and automated) decision tree systems which
provide the most likely problems. Computer alone, however, are not MUCH of
an aid to medicine; but more an adjunct to timely decision making and to
the sensors.

Sensor Operations and Communications Operators: Look at what SETI is doing
with automation. Yeah, you still need to have someone look at what gets
through the hasing algorythm, but as the algorythm gets better, that makes
it much easier to check what is important. In theory, you should have the
sensors and commo monitored 24/7 when underway... that means you need at
least three people for reasonable safety, two if you are willing to cut
corners; on smaller ships, it is a safe assumption the pilot and navigator
alternate this duty with any dedicated electronics operators.

Loaders & Deck Apes: With TL 13+ Robots available, and the prices at which
a TL13 cleaning robot can be built, there\'s no reason not to replace
swabbies with bots. Likewise, loading is not an intellectual activity,
provided the steward has the loading plot ready. With containerized cargo,
there is no reason not to automate the process, as bot\'s WILL BE more
accurate than persons.

So, in almost all areas, the reduction really isn\'t from computers, but
from the roboticization of the workspaces, and adding the software for the
required skills. Not a big problem. Expensive. In the long run, probably
even cheaper than paying crewmembers. But, in the overall economic picture,
not a good idea. First, you want people to be liable... so if something
goes wrong, you need a user to have user error. Secondly, if you automate
the craft too much, it becomes far too easy to take over if you can gain
computer access... send a well charged up cymbeline chip on a mission....
Third, People need jobs. Capitalism is based upon payment for labor. That
requires labor as an input value. Lacking this, see vinge.

I definitely don\'t buy vinge\'s whole bit,  but I do know that moder
economics require a working public.

