> ship construction becomes an adventure in itself, and
> they get to learn about the ship construction system,
> get explanations of what a meson gun is, and so on...

Sounds like what I\'ll set up if I ever run a game again.

Yards *full* of old ships will exist, especially in airless worlds, or
in *distant* (for stability) parking orbits around mainworlds. This is
where ships go when they aren\'t worth fixing, or when the crew just
gives up (or dies). Ships that nobody is real interested in "as is" but
are felt to maybe be worth more (eventually) than their value as scrap
metal.

It\'s not like it *costs* anything to let them sit on an isolated corner
of an airless mainworld, or in that parking orbit. The only costs are a
nav beacon and a security guard (for the stuff in orbit, he just
watches a sensor display back at the highport, it\'s not as if you could
sneak up on them...

You may be able to find almost anything there. But the more specific
the item, the less likely. And many (most) easily strippable parts for
*common* ships will have already been removed.

So, for example, if you want replacement filters for your XGZ Mark 4
trader, they probably won\'t have them. But don\'t give up yet, says the
proprietor, I think we\'ve got an old Vargr ship that has filters you
could use if you build an adapter in your ship\'s machine shop...

And if all you care about is "we need life support parts, and we\'ll
*make* them fit if we have to" then you\'ve come to the right place. 

You may even find functional but ancient ships. Like this old TL-9
trader. Uses a fission reactor for power and for the reaction drive.
She\'s old and worn, but still sound. It\'s just that the last owner died
and the heirs didn\'t want it. So it\'s been sitting here for a couple of
centuries. Yes, it does take a bit of hunting to find yards that\'ll
overhaul the ship. On the other hand, you only need to refuel the
reactor every 5-10 years. You still need LH2 for the Jump drive and for
the manuever drive, but that\'s available everywhere. It\'s a tradeoff.
And you spend a lot more time coasting to and from the 100 diameter
limit. But if you are willing to take the extra time, it\'s cheaper to
operate than a modern ship. 

And thus your players wind up as the proud owners of a true "antique"
of a ship. A real Classic. And a definite "fixer upper". :-)

