ObAkus, Wolfgang met with the insurance agent yesterday.  It\'s not
*my* fault he didn\'t bring his Captain or partners up to speed, and
no I\'m not going to tell you what he found out. <g>

ObTrav, and ship insurance.  What you pay is going to depend on
several factors, the value of the ship (or ship systems) insured,
how and where the ship is used, the deductible and/or co-payments
required, and the frequency of payment.  

This is going to be coming up in my game RSN, and here\'s my thinking
on it. I\'d appreciate comments.


To insure a ship against loss or damage up to 90% of apprised value.
    3% of apprised value per year, payable in advance
   +1% to cover the remaining 10%
   -1% if the ship stays on especially safe routes
   +2% if the ship works outside "safe zones"
   -1% if the ship receives regular and necessary maintenance, as
       defined by the insurer, and proof of same is submitted to the
       insurer

   Insurance does not cover maintenance, upgrades, or repairs
   required from normal use.

   Insurance covers only damage incurred from causes listed in the
   contract at time of issuance.

   And, of course, the GM may modify payments, terms and conditions
   as needed based on the requirements of the campaign.
   
So, to cover the exploratory trader /Mae Lee/, valued at 10.8
million cr, to 100%, given that she receives regular maintenance,
will cost you 540,000 cr each year.  If you drop the coverage to 90%
and fly only the insurer\'s designated "safe routes", the fee drops
to 108,000 cr.  

Eris
