>>Also, *shattering* a rock in the "city killer" and up range can
>>actually make the damage inflicted *worse, because the smaller piece
>>"couple" the energy to the atmosphere and crust better. the bigger the
>>rock, the *less* you want it turned into a cloud of pieces.
>
>         Unless you can blow the pieces to sub-re-entry sized pieces.  Which
> a sufficient number of surface-set missile and meson batteries can do.

No, burning up on re-entry is one of the ways the cloud of chunks from
a *big* rock can screw the planet up *worse* than just letting it hit
in one piece. 

Instead of <way too many> joules concentrated at a single point and
punch through the crust and wasting energy trying to move rock, you get
<still too many> joules spread over much of a hemisphere, cooking
everything, or at least igniting everything flammable.

It\'s the difference between a cannonball and canister shot. Same mass
of projectile, but far more damage of the *desired* type from the
smaller pieces.

>         Better yet...  spend some time with a calculator and figure out
> which point on the surface of the roid to keep soaking the meson and missle
> fire into to change its course so it "skips" off the outter surface of the
> atmosphere.  As I understand it, the angle required for a sucessful, "will
> touch the ground" reentry is vanishingly small....  

Only for spacecraft. At shallow angles (very shallow) they\'ll skip. A
bigger object *won\'t*, because it has far more mass behind each unit of
surface area (the square/cube law strikes again). 

At steeper angles spacraft burn up or hit the grouind too hard for the
crew to survive. Again, a bigger object won\'t burn up, and you *want*
it to hit the ground hard. 
 
