Kyle Schuant:

Again, I don\'t quite buy it. Codes are crackable. If
your PCs have among them an engineer, it\'s going to be
his first priority, I\'d imagine.

* * *

Me2:

Absolutely all codes are crackable. However this is <cue kettle drums> the
future where  such \'codes\' could be hideously complex. Re-configuring
transponders in the Trav Universe for example are supposed to be along the
lines of \'practically impossible\' without muchos forgery, electronics and
computer skills and associated equipment. In RL, we\'re seeing the rise of
engine imbolizers so when the plods spot a reported stolen vehicle they just
cut the engine via a radio signal (though admittedly a mechanic could
disable the unit and it\'s more a case of catching the vehicle from where it
is stolen to where it is going for disassembly). 

Imagine <various wavy lines appear on scream as we view the future>. Skipped
vessel arrives in imperial starport. Local bank branch has a feed from
starport control, keeping an eye out for all vessels under its re-payment
plan. It automatically hooks up to the black box it has installed to prevent
skipping (an integral part of the jump drive without which the vessel cannot
jump were it removed) to check for tampering. What\'s this? Someone has had a
go at it? - awooga, awooga, awooga - ding ding ding - starport control
prevents the vessel from leaving so an investigation can take place. 

I don\'t imagine the banks loading up their \'how to prevent a skip\' computer
hardware/software with substandard or easily bustable codes. That would be
stoopid. Given the vast amount of monies invested, there would have to be a
way to prevent skipping. And given that communication is limited to jump,
and a vessel could jump anywhere, then that prevention would have to be on
the ship itself. Especially as the collateral for the loan is usually the
ship itself for small time merchants.

I like the idea of cheaper ships though. That would solve a lot of problems
(especially on the whole collateral issue).

Rambling yours,

Michael 
