    'topic' => 'ship cost',
    'body' => 'Eris wrote:
<<Getting the price of ships too low, though, has its
own problems. 

Military ships will always be much more expensive than
civilian
(even para-military/pirate) ships. They will have more
armor, more
expensive weapons and hiediously expensive sensors
that the civilian
ships won\'t have.

So, let\'s limit our discussion to civilian ships.  For
*merchant
ships* just how low can we reasonably go and not wreak
the feel of
the game?

20,000 per dton?
10,000 per dton?

And what systems do we reduce in price to get the
total price down?  

Power plant?
Jump Drive?
Sensors?>>

Kyle replied:
Well, IMTU as I\'ve said it\'s from the old GURPS:
Space, so everything\'s cheaper... There are different
classes of hull available, though. I think we can all
imagine the difference between the hull on a four seat
Piper and an Apache! Also, the electronics is a huge
part of the cost. Military ships have much more
sophisticated systems overall. There\'s a big
difference in cost between collision-avoidance radar
and military targeting head-up-displays, and so on. If
anybody is interested in the exact costs, email me
privately and I\'ll send them, but it works out that
your standard free trader, unarmed, no stealth
ability, just enough engines to get it off largish
earth-type planets, Jump-1, a hull that\'s internally
tough but not armoured, and staterooms for the PCs,
about a quarter its volume for cargo, that\'ll set PCs
back, new, 500 kCr. Whereas your military fighter
ship, hugely manoeuverable, well armed and armoured,
sophisticated electronics and so on, will set you back
18 MCr.

Basically, high tech and weapons cost a lot, ships
themselves, not so much.

Of course the cheapest ever in my game came when the
PCs had fled their ship from a Vargr boarding party
and left it to self-destruct (a la The Enterprise),
and landed on a TL 7 world. The engineer was able to
produce a Jump drive by enrolling in the Research
department of a local university... But a ship? What
could they do? They noticed in the papers that there
were disarmanent talks going on (Balkanised world), so
they sold their Jump drive design to the local
national government in exchange for an old missile
submarine... the government thought they were idiots
because the sub had had its engines removed, and of
course the warheads. The PCs took the missiles out and
strapped them to the sides of the sub, hooked up the
diesel generator to the jump drive, recast the hatches
so that they\'d resist pressure form the inside instead
of the outside, installed some comofortable seats, and
took off.
The Good Ship Jabberwocky, as it was known, did not go
far, but it got them off the world.

