    'body' => '> >I also submit that no-one has ever had the ability.
>
> Here we disagree.  The Cold War was not a bad dream.
> Both sides did have enough nuclear weapons to wipe out
> all life on earth several times over.  Actually, that
> capability still exists, but the reason for having it
> (that mutual destruction would be assured) does not.

I\'m sorry Glenn, but you\'re completely wrong on this one.

There are not, and have never been, enough nuclear weapons on the planet to
completely wipe out even a single moderate sized country , say France, let
alone the entire world.

Your contention is a common fallacy, but in reality it would take some where
around a thousand times the maximum number of weapons to get close to even
taking out just the heavily populated parts of the planet, (let alone the
vast majority of the planet which is not heavily populated) and even that
would rely on careful placement of the weapons, and wouldn\'t be possible by
ballistic delivery.

While it is possible a release of all the available nuclear weapons _might_
cause major climatic changes, based on previous evidence such as the Taupo
and Krakatoa events (Taupo being estimated as the equivalent of 5 Gigatons
of TNT, about what the world\'s nuclear arsenal is capable of now) , it is
actually extremely unlikley that the much-touted "nuclear winter" would
occur for more than one season, if at all.

And even if it did, that would be nowhere near "wiping out all life on earth
several times over". In fact, it wouldn\'t even wipe it out once over, as
previous ice ages  have shown.

I suggest you actually examine the evidence in future before repeating this
sort of popular bull.

Frankie.
