>Absolutely all codes are crackable.

That\'s not strictly true.

It is possible to devise a code with a completely random
encription. Ie every letter uses a different key and there
is no pattern to the sequence of keys.

The problems with this are:

a) the code book is bigger than the message (since you have
   a substitution table for each letter.)

b) only people with a complete code book can use the code.

c) how do you transmit and secure the code book?

However, none of these stop this being used in the real world.
(See under one time pad.) The simple example being a spy who
can collect their code book from their contact.

In Traveller, these code books can be sent out by secured
transport and only accessed from secure buildings.
This doesn\'t stop people stealing them, but it
stops your computer-8 guy breaking the code.

Now you could steal the code book, copy it and then put it back...
That would be an interesting scenario.


