    'topic' => ' Inevitability of government failure',
    'body' => 'On Thu, 25 Nov 1999, Glenn M. Goffin wrote:

> That\'s a good question.  One can fairly argue that China had the same
> government from the time Qin consolidated power in the central part of
> the region about 450 BCE (I think I have the date close to correct)
> until 1949.  While dynasties holding the throne changed at various
> times, the central functions of government -- bureaucracy, education,
> military, religious rites -- continued more or less normally.  Even the
> Mongols simply became Chinese emperors after a generation.  

One can make this argument only by ignoring everything about the
governments themselves.  (Qin consolidated power in -221 or -222 or
something, BTW).  The infamous "examination system" alone changed
drastically; how it operated, and its underlying assumptions, in the Ming
or Qing would have been unrecognizable to someone from the Tang, let alone
the Han.  The central functions of government were in a constant state of
reinvention.  That\'s *why* there\'s big fat sections in each of the
dynastic histories (plus piles of adjunct handbooks) dealing with
governmental institutions and procedures; they kept changing out from
underneath \'em.  Some key symbols and fragments of ideology persisted, or
more accurately kept resurfacing and disappearing, but once you start to
really look at it, there wasn\'t a hell of a lot.  Less continuity than you
could find, say, in political philosophy & symbolism between the western
Roman empire and 18th century western Europe.

(It\'s worth keeping in mind that the "Chinese empire" had some sizeable
gaps, between the Han and the Sui, the Tang and the Song, the Song and the
Yuan.  Not to mention the long periods where official dynasties still, on
the books, in power, had lost control over large sections of territory, in
which rival governments ("non-orthodox dynasties") existed.)

> One can even argue that the communists, too, just became Chinese
> emperors, but I don\'t want to get into a flame war with the Marxists on
> the list.

Because we can destroy all life on earth?  Well, anyway, I\'ll try just to
