    'index' => 'ef084',
    'month' => '11',
    'body' => 'On 11/26/99 at 01:11 PM,  Phil Kitching <postmark.design@btinternet.com> said:

>>So, let\'s limit our discussion to civilian ships.  For
>>*merchant ships* just how low can we reasonably go and not wreak
>>the feel of the game?

>>20,000 per dton?
>>10,000 per dton?

>>And what systems do we reduce in price to get the
>>total price down?  

>>Power plant?
>>Jump Drive?
>>Sensors?>>

>Under T4, ships work out about 100kCr/dT for merchants,
>500kCr/dT for paramilitary and 1MCr/dT for Military.
>Fighters and SDBs (not having all that jump fuel)
>tend to be 2MCr/dT or more.

I know what the *books* say, but that wasn\'t the question.  The
question was how low *could* the costs be without wreaking the feel
of the game. 

>>Kyle replied:
>>Well, IMTU as I\'ve said it\'s from the old GURPS:
>>Space, so everything\'s cheaper... 

But not as cheap as Kyle seems to think if you are building the
standard Traveller PC-class ships.

>>your standard free trader, unarmed, no stealth
>>ability, just enough engines to get it off largish
>>earth-type planets, Jump-1, a hull that\'s internally
>>tough but not armoured, and staterooms for the PCs,
>>about a quarter its volume for cargo, that\'ll set PCs
>>back, new, 500 kCr. Whereas your military fighter

>That\'s way too cheap. A book 5 party could probably buy
>one outright, just from mustering out benefits.

That\'s also about 1/10th of what I calculated such a ship to cost
using GURPS:Space.  A 200dt Free Trader type ship, unarmed,
unarmored, no stealth, 1g/J1, 4 crew/10 passengers cost about 8
million new, about half that for a serviceable, but old ship.  A PC
party get into one of them, given a required 10% downpayment.

The above ship works out to 40k per ton new, and down to about 20k
per ton used.  You could get this by reducing construction costs to
40% of standard, or for ease of conversion make it 50%.  How does
that sound to everyone?

Eris
