Hmm, must be november...time for the Traveller <> Real Life rant.;-)

In real life, yes. In real life Traveller wold be dull boring and no fun.
A real-life depiction of prison is boring, brutish and not very
interesting. Notice, in the game that started this thread, placing the
characters on that prison world ended the game.

While this may be acceptable to the particular players in that game (they
didn\'t like their characters any more, they were shipping out, got jobs in
other cities, etc) in general in ongoing roleplaying games it is a BAD
IDEA to stuff PC\'s in hopeless situations. _Almost_ hopeless is another
kettle of fish, but \'You\'re here, no hope of escape, no hope of parole,
you die of old age\' in a game I wanted to continue would (and has) made me
look twice before gaming with that person again, at least with them as GM.
(I had a good friend who lloved to put the PC\'s in these utterly
untenable situations: 

"You wake up in a cave, things feel weird."

"Weird how?"

"The light is wrong, and gravity doesn\'t seem to work right."

"We look out the cave"

"As you stand there, a huge portal opens in the air and hordes off demonic
looking things start pouring out. They are marching toward the cave."

"We try to leave."

"Too late, the vanguard reaches you. You are taken prisoner and marched
back through the portal."

"Huh?"

"You are lead to a huge, bloody altar, with thousands of dead bodies
heaped nearby."

"HUH??!!"

"The first of you are lead to the altar, where a goat-thing with huge
muscular arms splits you in half."

"Ok, lets play something different now...")

What Leonard, (and all those SF writers) are doing is setting up a far
more cinematic universe, where criminals are evil geniuses (repeat after
me: "Before I kill you, Mr. Bond..." ;-) Player characters could even
think about owning ships, let alone run around with battledress, and life
is interesting enough for people to play escapist games about it.

