> I think that you underestimate the level of possible damage.

No, I don\'t.

While your arguments are all valid, I was _specifically_ countering Glenn\'s
suggestion that there are enough nuclear weapons to wipe out all life on
earth several times ago.

Some specific points :

> Let\'s talk EMP  damage for starters.
> If you don\'t think the death toll in North America and
> Europe wouldn\'t be horrendous I think that you\'re mistaken. Hundreds of
> millions would die just because the infrastructure gacked when all of the
> electronics stopped working. Without the infrastructure the countries
would
> cease to exist. There would be starvation, epidemic, riots, looting, etc.
> At the height of the cold war multiple warheads were armed at almost every
> section of the American continent.  Almost every state had more than one
> target, even if only military assets were hit. The balance of the U.S.
> population lives in these areas. The separated enclaves that might survive
> would no longer be a civilization, at least not a 20th century tech level
> civilization.

I agree that the die-off rate in industrialized countries would be huge.
The estimates are something like a 8-10% kill immediately on the first wave
with about 70% secondary kill (i.e: through starvation, radiation, rioting,
etc.).

That\'s a lot of death and sufferring, but,  even a 99% kill of humans in
industrialized nations is _nowhere_near_ eliminating the human race or
destroying the planet, and the technological level of the survivors is
completely irrelevant to my argument (though if you want to argue that
seperately I do reckon technlogy would not just dissappear as all the
post-apocalypse stories seem to asume. )

> This ignores the general level of radioactive fallout that would exist.
The
> accident in Chernobyl result in a measurable increase in radionucleides in
> the milk of dairy cows as far away as Norway.

Although from memory, that research is questionable, as there were no base
data to show that there had, in fact, been an increase. It just showed that
the levels now were higher than expected.

> The probable levels of
> radiation from the blasts and level of contamination from the fallout
would
> make the lives of the survivors very unpleasant.

This is true, though again I feel the effects have been overrated. I believe
studies on the effects of the Hiroshima and Nagasaki bombs have shown that
while people at the time and their immediate descendants had/have noticeable
effects, third generation offspring are not any more likely to suffer
effects than others.

> Even just a couple of years of nuclear winter would result in a huge
number
> of deaths. We are a society where ever small numbers of people raise the
> food for the population as a whole. The loss of the ability to do this
alone
> would result in large numbers of deaths.

Note the point is that _you_ are in a society where small numbers raise
food.
The majority of the world\'s population are not in such a society.

I fully agree that the US, Europe, & Japan would be stuffed.
Whether I think that\'s a bad thing or not depends on my attitude at the
time.
<grin>

Frankie
