>         Um, could you substantiate your postition?  How many warheads are
> there and how many cities?

I don\'t have the appriopriate reference handy (and even those are edcuated
estimates as the exact figures are kept secret)  but from memory the US only
has _produced_ in the _tens_ of thousands of nuclear warheads since they
began production, (from memory around 40,000, of which the majority are no
longer viable & have been scrapped)  and the USSR has produced less . Even
adding in China,  France, England, Israeils, Indians and Pakisanis, I doubt
there are many more than 100,000 nuclear warheads extant today. Heck, based
on current figures I may be remembering the figures larger than they are.

How many cities ? I don\'t know, but I suspect there are more than a 100,000
cities in the North America alone, depending on your definition of city.

Even if I\'m out by a factor of ten in the wrong way, and there\'s a million
warheads out there, the effective radius of even the largest nukes is no
more than thirty miles. If you do the math, you\'ll find that even with a
million  nukes that\'s only a fraction of the surface of the planet.

And that assumes that the nukes are set off to cover maximum area, which is
_highly_ unlikely. In the event of a full scale nuclear war (again, highly
unlikely, but just assuming) , some nuke\'s would never be launched or not go
off, others would be destroyed by ABM and AA systems, others would be used
for exoatmospheric EMP and intelligence denial , some targets would be
designated for overkill, and others would be given military targets well
away from large population centers (such as naval fleet concentrations and
"second-strike" SSBNs )

BTW, from references I do have handy,  ( Strategy & Tactics) the numbers  in
the 70\'s were even lower. At that time the number of US delivery systems was
about 22,000 with the USSR having about 14,000. While they had more warheads
than delivery systems, including the nuclear shells for the old Long Tom,
and the fact that some delivery systems were MIRV,  the difference between
delivery systems and warheads is not practically useful.

Also, according to the latest S&T, the US currently only has 580 ICBM\'s and
432 SLBNs in 18 SSBNs. Russia has 800 ICBM\'s and 540 SLBNs in 22 SSBNs.

The second thing is that nuclear weaponry is no longer the main weapon of
detterrence. As it says in "In Athena\'s Camp" (John Arquilla, 1997) and
other recent  military doctrine studies, it is now quite likely that a
technological force, such as the US military, could destroy the majority of
amn enemy nuclear power\'s nuke forces on the ground in a first strike using
_conventional_ weapons, thus avoiding the PR problems of launching a nuclear
first strike.

People have always overestimated the nuclear power\'s capability to wage
nuclear war, and it is becoming increasingly a secondary capacity to other
doctrines such as AirLand Battle 2000, C2 (or C4ISR, depending on your
politics), and Informtuion Warfare

Frankie
