Kyle replied:
Frank\'s quite right. However, I\'d like to add some
points. Firstly, just one missile could ruin a
country\'s economy, and ultimately causes millions of
death. Picture this - just one series of warheads
(eight 250 kton on a Russian SS-21 missile) Los
Angeles flattened, 3 million people vapourised
instantly, 6 million others dead within a week, 3
million others burned and irradiated, the public
utilities all destroyed (roads, water, and so on.)
Disease strikes a week later from the millions of
corpses rotting in the streets. Most of the surviving
population of LA County becomes refugees, the
authorities suddenly need food and housing for 5
million people. Could the USA cope with this?
Undoubtedly. But it would wreck its economy, and the
troops in Kosovo would definately be coming home.

Secondly, it\'s true nukes couldn\'t kill every person
in one big blast, but they could come damned close.
Expand the LA scenario there to "just" two largest
cities in every nation of over a million inhabitants.
This increases the number of disease and famine deaths
since nations are unable to help one another, and
barely able to help themselves. The "just one season
of nuclear winter" is pretty deadly, since it would
cause worldwide crop failure. There\'s plenty of food
to feed the world; but our reserves aren\'t that great
(we eat it as soon as we get it) and of course nations
would be keeping food to themselves; net importers of
food such as Japan would be in big trouble. All that,
even without the movie-style "breakdown of law and
order", starts pushing the fatalities pretty close to
100%...

You can\'t compare the explosion of lots of nukes with
the explosion of a volcano. A volcano does not have a
3million centigrade fireball, nor deadly radiation.
Its blast is often supersonic, but it doesn\'t usually
explode in the middle of a city (disaster movies
notwithstanding). Also, one big bang doesn\'t make as
much dust (for nuclear winters) as lots of "little"
bangs. Lots of little ones cause more damage; this is
the principle of the frag grenade.

Lastly, I\'m not terribly worried exactly how many
would die. I think that the thought that human life is
not extinct would be of cold comfort to those
millions, or billions, already dead. And the
survivors, well, where would our civilisation be?
Picture an Aztec in 1450 being given a vision of his
nation\'s future (to, say, 1999). To say to him, "well,
Indians survived," probably wouldn\'t impress him much.



