>>Absolutely all codes are crackable.
>
> That\'s not strictly true.
>
> It is possible to devise a code with a completely random
> encription. Ie every letter uses a different key and there
> is no pattern to the sequence of keys.
>
> The problems with this are:
>
> a) the code book is bigger than the message (since you have
>    a substitution table for each letter.)
>
> b) only people with a complete code book can use the code.
>
> c) how do you transmit and secure the code book?
>
> However, none of these stop this being used in the real world.
> (See under one time pad.) The simple example being a spy who
> can collect their code book from their contact.

> In Traveller, these code books can be sent out by secured
> transport and only accessed from secure buildings.
> This doesn\'t stop people stealing them, but it
> stops your computer-8 guy breaking the code.
>
> Now you could steal the code book, copy it and then put it back...
> That would be an interesting scenario.

The problem is that "one-time pads" is that they are *not* suitable for
this sort of application. They work great for point to point
communications, because you only have to make sure that the two points
involved get their "pads" securely.

But for this, EVERY SINGLE BANK BRANCH on *thousands* of worlds has to
have a copy. There\'s *no* way to guarantee security of the key that
way. 

Sure *we* use "one time pads" for diplomatic communications with
embassies. But each embassy has its own "key". So even if you can
intercept and copy the "key" for the embassy in Nairobi, it\'ll be
useless for anything but messages sent *between* Nairobi and
Washington. Only Washington has all the keys, and they\'re *really* well
guarded. 

But since a bank doesn\'t know *what* world a ship will show up at, it
has to be able to read & verify stuff at *all* the worlds it covers. 

BTW, it occurs to me that unless the ship is required to make payments
at a specific world, there\'s going to be *weeks* of lag time between
when they pay up and when the bank finds out about the payment. Makes
it rather hard to tell if a payment is late or not. 

