    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> At 08:15 PM 11/26/1999 +1300, you wrote:
>>I\'m sorry Glenn, but you\'re completely wrong on this one.
>>
>>There are not, and have never been, enough nuclear weapons on the planet to
>>completely wipe out even a single moderate sized country , say France, let
>>alone the entire world.
>>
>         [SINP]
>>
>>I suggest you actually examine the evidence in future before repeating this
>>sort of popular bull.
>>
>>Frankie.
>
>         Um, could you substantiate your postition?  How many warheads are
> there and how many cities?

Actually, "nuclear winter" is rather likely. But not certain.

The key is *not* the explosive power of the bombs. It\'s determining how
much dust the explosion kicks up (ground and airburst differ *wildly*
on this), and what sort of smoke if produced by the fires started by
bomb flash and direct blast.

These are all *strongly* dependent on season and worse, on targeting of
the missiles. 

Last I heard the range of answers generated by more or less reasonable
simulations ranged from "it\'s gonna get *really* chilly" to "yeah, we
didn\'t have a summmer that year and lost a lot of crops" (which
happened in 1815, due to a volcano!). 

It\'s also fairly certain that if either the US or the USSR had cared to
launch a suicidal first strike, they had more than enough warheads to
wipe out civilization. Especially given that once such a launch was
confirmed, the other side would cheerfully nuke any cities or
installations that the "enemy" had left. This where subs come in. Until
recently, they weren\'t accurate enough to take out missile silos and
the like. But they were more than accurate enough to take out cities,
factories, transport nexuses and the like. 

And the effects on anybody who *didn\'t* get targeted wouldn\'t be
pretty. 

Remember those lovely displays of "escalation" in the missile launch
displays near the end of "Wargames"? I recognized enough of them to
suspect that they were using open literature defense/offense scenarios
as the basis. They didn\'t *have* to exaggerate much.

"Limited" nuclear war is possible. But nobody considers it *likely*.
It\'d require someone in charge with the guts to say "We are going to be
beaten. Badly. But there\'s no point in taking the rest of the world
with us." Leaders like that are too rare to count on. 

