>> Also, rather than find a world with no usable metal deposits, they just
>> did sensor sweeps and any time they found a concentration of metal
>> above a certain size, they\'d drop an ortillery round on it.
>
> Why? Who cares? If the prisoners are alone on the world, then who
> cares what they build? besides, if future prisoners are anything like
> modern prisoners, they don\'t come from a highly educated background
> (one of the reasons they\'re criminals in the first place...). I really
> doubt that even given a gigantic hunk of pure iron ore sitting right
> out in a field that they\'d get much above a stone age existance.
>
> There may be some assumptions that I\'m missing out on though.

There was. This was a POW "camp". A *Naval* POW camp (Space Navy, not
Wet Navy). Let *that* sort of person start refining metals and the like
and next thing you know, they\'ll be shoooting down the picket ships!

Just look at the sort of thing WWII POWs managed. Sure, they won\'t be
able to "extort" (or steal!) things from the guards. On the other hand,
they won\'t have to *hide* what they are working on. At least not any
small pieces.

> I think the problem is that the average sci-fi writer (and Leonard)
> pictures a planet full of criminals who have the amazing breadth
> and depth of knowledge... of a science fiction writer (or Leonard).

> I\'m not saying criminals are dumb, but they\'ve put most of their
> energy toward developing skills other than ore smelting and 
> metallurgy.

That depends. There *are* a lot of criminals with pretty high levels in
various skills. It\'s getting them to *co-operate* that\'s the problem.

>> I think there were regular drops of vitamin mineral supplements, and
>> minimal medical supplies, too. For all the goos a plastic crate and a
>> parachute did the prisoners as "raw materials".
>
> On even a semi-garden world the local flora is going to 
> have more than enough of what prisoners can make use of.

> If they\'re on the equivalent of a rockball, the whole premise 
> breaks down for me as I don\'t see how the prisoners are going
> to get that whole O2-CO2 thing working.

I once came across a story that had the prisoners more or less
"running" a prison on a rockball. They\'d been given adequate
technology, just *way* out of date. Enough so that the visting ships
weren\'t *really* worried when they dropped off prisoners. Among other
things, they didn\'t have the tech for stardrives and would take a
*long* time to build spaceships.[1]

It was a society that seemed to have a "one-strike" policy. The *stupid*
bullies tended to die rather quickly. They didn\'t pay attention when
told how to wear a suit properly. The cons running the place just
hauled the suit in (no point wasting air) and the body got dumped into
the "compost heap". 

The *smart* hardcases ran the place and protected any "white collar"
criminals that had useful skills. So you had an odd sort of fuedal
society. I think it could have worked, though at some point, it would
have enough of a knowledge and industrial base that they could tell the
"jailers" to quit dumping people on them, and become an "independent"
world. 

>> They managed to escape. And no, I don\'t remember how.
>
> Must have been a load of murderous Poul Andersons & Leonard Ericksons.

No, just your typical sneaky Naval officers and ratings doing their
duty to escape a POW camp.

[1] Just as an example, if we find enough water and a few critical
minerals on the moon, you could set up a "Victorian" tech level colony,
and they\'d be able to get by and even expand to the limit of their
resources. But it\'d take a long time before they had anything more
dangerous than some guns. Nothing to worry "21st century" tech if you
take a few simple precautions and make it clear what will happen if
they do anything stupid.

