>> c) how do you transmit and secure the code book?


Snip

>The problem is that "one-time pads" is that they are *not* suitable for
>this sort of application. They work great for point to point
>communications, because you only have to make sure that the two points
>involved get their "pads" securely.


Response:

I\'m not really all that familiar with cryptography but would the following
work:

Each "branch office" would receive at scheduled periods a unique code which
consists of two tables of simple equations whose results are non-repeating
decimals i.e., like Pi?.   Each table would be sent by separate secure
messenger.  Three digit blocks in the first decimal (from the first table)
starting at a value determined by the first eight digits of a second decimal
(from the second table) represent letters, numbers and other symbols deemed
necessary.  Each line of the message resets in the sequence in the first
decimal the value of the next eight digits in the second decimal and thus
resets for the required symbols. Repeat the procedure for each following
line.   Each day/selected time period or even, for the truly paranoid, new
message a new pair of decimals are used.

Even if individual messages or even the code tables for a single branch for
a specific time period are compromised,  the larger system is still secure.

The home office would originate and have all the keys.  It thus would be the
major security risk.

Just an idea for a relatively low tech rather unsophisticated message system
which doubtlessly has sufficient flaws for ingenious PCs to exploit.

Dan
