Right here in Portland, we\'ve got an "extinct" volcano (Mount Tabor)
pretty much in the middle of town. It\'s pretty well overgrown (grass,
trees) and they blockedup the caves (some lava tube segments?) *years*
ago. 

But if it ever *did* get active again, we\'d be in a *world* of trouble.
Most of Portland\'s water supply comes from a "reserve" on the slopes of
Mt. Hood (another "extinct" volcano, only it still has hot springs, and
the lava dome is warm enough to melt snow in places! Climbers often
pause for a rest there because its warm...). 

The pipes come up at Mt. Tabor and fill several *big* reserviors at
various levels on the slopes. And from there, it\'s distributed to the
rest of the city.

So if Mt. Tabor became active, there goes our water supply. And no,
*don\'t* suggest drinking the Willamette or Columbia Rivers. We aren\'t
set up for the required purification. 

If Mt *Hood* goes active, the only good thing is that the prevailing
winds blow *east* away from town. But we\'d still lose our water supply.

And please keep in mind that there are different *kinds* of volcanos.
Ones like Vesuvius (the one that got Pompei and Herculaneum) and Mt.
St. Helens don\'t do lava except in the actual crater. The lava isn\'t
fluid enough to flow very far. Instead you get ash clouds burying the
surrounding areas in meters of ash, and the nearby spots have to worry
about pyroclastic flows. 

Other volcanos are like the ones in Hawaii or Iceland. the lava is very
fluid, and you get large flows.

Frankly, I\'ll take either over the *third* "type". That\'s where you get
massive cracks in the crust and *thick* flows of lava covering
*thousands* of square miles. That\'s what formed much of Central and
Eastern Washington/Oregon and a fair chunk of Idaho. 

Just to give you an idea of the *scale* involved, some of the basalt
layers are *hundreds* of feet thick. And the total thickness of the
various layers is *thousands* of feet. 

Have a geologist discover that a populated region of a planet is going
to undergo *that* and watch the fun. Massive quakes, and then the
ground starts cracking into wide fissures, *miles* long, out of which
lava flows as fast (if not faster) than any lava flow you\'ve seen films
of from Iceland or Hawaii. 

Well, there goes the neighborhood. 

And *here* is an adventure seed. These sorts of magma flows create
massive mineral deposits (stuff like the Idaho copper and silver mines
or the Comstock Lode in Colorado(?)). They also tend to be ongoing for
hundreds or more likely *thosands* of years.

So picture someone getting the idea of building mining "platforms" that
can float on the lava, and use CG to cross the solid stuff. Equipped to
sample the fresh lava and *pump* (scoop?) it aboard for processing when
you find flows rich in valuable minerals. 

Some may even "drill" into the flows to find the internal "pools" or
the magma chambers where the *really* good stuff forms. 

Just imagine the possibilities. Imagine the profits. Imagine the things
that can go wrong. With or without "help". 

For an even *more* extreme version of this, you need a *young* planet.
Well under a billion years. Just after (most) of the "bombardment by
planetesmals is over. One where the surface is blocks of lighter
crustal material floating on top of molten magma. The blocks haven\'t
really consolidated, and new ones form as bubbles of lighter material
work their way up from the deeper areas. 

You\'ve at least got solid (if rather hot!) "bases" to work from. On the
downside, there\'s *no* oxygen, and the air is going to be the most
godawful mix of stuff, including lots of sulfur oxides and the like. 

This is a *prime* location because first, the planet is still
seperating into crust, magma, and core. The mix of elements is more
uniform, though there will still be large chunks of stuff that *had*
differentiated before impact. But more importantly, because it\'s so
young, the planet still has most of its initial supply of
radioisotopes. Definitely worth the trouble to seperate out of the
molten rock, even if they *are* more uniformly distributed.

Even better would be trying to harvest radio-isotopes from the
planetary nebula of a system wuile it was forming. But that\'s *really*
dangerous (such nebulas would resemble a cross between a *Star Trek*
"nebula" and a *Star Wars* "asteroid field". Ouch! And besides, you\'d
have to melt the rock yourself. :-)

ps. I gotta say it before somebody else does. Do you suppose that these
guys "mining" lava/magma would be called "soft rock miners"? :-)

