> volcanoes in the middle of a city go off because humans are not so totally
> moronic so as to build on the flanks of too many active hilltops.  When
> they have, they\'ve discovered their mistake and not lived to tell of it.
> Eruptions ala \'Volcano\' are historically rare.  However, can you say
> Pompeii ?  It doesn\'t have to spew forth lava to be deadly.
>
> As for spitting up ash, wrong again.  We find a fair few ash layers in
> sedimentary rocks that must have been many, many metres thick when they
> were laid.  Often, we find the same evidence from the same eruption
> hundreds of kilometers from the eruption point itself.  One eruption in
> recent history altered the climate across the globe.  Krakatua.  One single
> eruption.  Heard as far away as Sydney in Australia where the Governor
> thought Russian warships were bombarding his coastal defences.  Show me a
> nuke that can do that !

I live within sight of Mount St. Helens. We\'ve *seen* those meter thick
ash layers. Even hundred of miles away. But the trick is that the ash
has to get into the *stratosphere* to affect climate. That 1815
explosion caused *more* of that effect, even though it was smaller than
St. Helens (and Kratatoa, and that Taopura(sp?) blast someone was
talking about). That\'s because it  went more *up* than out. And it may
have produced finer ash, which stays up longer.

Nukes, because of the fireball, are *much* better at getting
particulates, especially *fine* particulates, into the upper
atmosphere. Sure, each one puts up less *indivually*. But they raise it
higher, and because there are a *lot* of them, widely spread, they
distribute it more evenly. 

Then there\'s the smoke from the firestorms. Anyplace where you get a
firestorm, the severe updraft in the center that drives the firestorm
will also carry smoke particles (quite close to "ideal" size for
staying up a *long* time) into the stratosphere. 

One of the big arguments regarding attempts to calculate the effecs of
a large, widespread attack is just how big the firestorms would be, how
many there\'d be, and how long they\'d last before spreading to far to
sustain the winds that drive them. 

The USSR would have had a lot of them, because they liked to hide silos
in *thick* forests. Cities with lots of older buildings are another
prime candidate. 

BTW, I forget who it was who kept harping on "there weren\'t enough
missiles to carry all those warheads". Well, I spent a lot of years
living next to a SAC airbase. Those B52 crews would have done their
damnedest to get their "warheads" (bombs, and later stand-off
shortrange missiles) thru. And I think a lot would have succeeded.
Ditto for their Soviet counterparts. 

And I have to wonder about the bombers that\'d get shot down. We know
that our bombs can survive explosions and crashes IF THEY AREN\'T ARMED
at the time. What happens if they *are* armed. For that matter, is
there a way the crew could detonate them in the time between "We\'re
going down!" and impact?

> ObTrav : Imagine a system where the populace of the mainworld is sitting on
> the flanks of a volcano they think is extinct.  Say, Olympus Mons on Mars.
> Big bugger.  What are they gonna do when it appears that it isn\'t extinct ?
>  How do up and move millions of people, even in a high TL Third Imperium ?
> Imagine the PC\'s fighting people off because they\'re the last ship out
> after all the nobles\' yachts and Megacorps freighters have left.  Ooh,
> that\'d be evil.

Check out a bunch of John Brunner\'s early SF. He had "involuntary"
colonies scattered all over the place. They were all ZFPs (Zarathustra
Refugee Planets". The only title I can remember off the top of my head
is "The Pirates of Zan".

Basic concept was that centuries back, it\'d been discovered that
Zarathustra\'s sun was going to nova. Soon. A massive evacuation attempt
took place, and towards the end, as the day side started to cook, the
last few hundred ships were launching from night side and trying to
stay in the planet\'s shadow as long as possible while trying to get up
to speed for hyperdrive (In traveller terms, make it to the 100
diameter limit).

This meant that due to the planet\'s position, they were headed out into
unexplored space (in Traveller, make it that the radiation from the
nova not only *caused* the misjumps, but biased them in that direction)

They were badly overloaded. So badly that there were almost immediate
life support problems. So when they came out of hyper (exited jump)
they *had* to head for any planets that were nearby, just to replenish
the air supply. 

Some ships forcibly unloaded the passengers, promising to bring help
and were then lost when their engines or crew weren\'t up to making the
return trip to civilized space. 

Other ships were in too bad a condition (or had lost too many of the
operations personnel due to life support and fighting with the
passengers. When they landed (or often "crashed" in a manner that let
enough people survive) they were *stuck*. 

Thus as folks expanded into this area they were always finding colonies
in the damnedest places. Planets that were "livable" but only just. And
sometimes, the folks that discovered them would keep it a secret. In
one book, someone had found a ZFP that was still a fair ways beyond the
"border" (misjump!) and when he got back, the megacorp he worked for
kept it a secret. they infiltrated the local theocracy, and
"redirected" the way sacrifices were done. In short, they used the
planet as a "spare parts" depot. 

Anyway, you\'d get some of the same effects (overloaded sgips,
passengers and crew fighting over life support, critical systems
getting damaged). Alas, you wouldn\'t be likely to get the massive
number of mis-jumped ships. :-(

