> Was Written:
>
>>> a) the code book is bigger than the message (since you have
>>>    a substitution table for each letter.)
>>>
>>> b) only people with a complete code book can use the code.
>>>
>>> c) how do you transmit and secure the code book?
>
> Snip
>
>>The problem is that "one-time pads" is that they are *not* suitable for
>>this sort of application. They work great for point to point
>>communications, because you only have to make sure that the two points
>>involved get their "pads" securely.
>
>
> Response:
>
> I\'m not really all that familiar with cryptography but would the following
> work:
>
> Each "branch office" would receive at scheduled periods a unique code which
> consists of two tables of simple equations whose results are non-repeating
> decimals i.e., like Pi?.

There are no "simple" equations for irrationals like that. Or, rather,
there are "simple" equations, and there are equations that will easily
let you produce the XXth digit of the number.

The simple equations can take *hours* to give you "merely" the 10th
digit of the number. 

But that really doesn\'t matter.

> Each table would be sent by separate secure messenger.

The problem that you are missing is that every branch you add to the
network adds another set of code keys OF WHATEVER FORM to be
distributed. And since they all have to be the *same* that means that
intercepting *one* gives away everything. The simple fact that there
are more *copies* makes getting hold of one (either by sneaking a peek
at one "in transit", or by bribing a clerk at a branch).

Dividing the keys into parts, only helps a little with the interception
problem. It doesn\'t help *at all* with the "insider leak" problem. 

> Even if individual messages or even the code tables for a single branch for
> a specific time period are compromised,  the larger system is still secure.

You missed the fact that *all* the branches have to have the *same*
keys, because they have to be able to verify or issue the stuff that
the ship has or needs. Remember, there\'s *no* way to determine *in
advance* which branch a ship will be at several months from now. So
they *all* have to be able to deal with it. 

> The home office would originate and have all the keys.  It thus would be the
> major security risk.

Except that as I pointed out above, to be of any use for dealing with a
ship whose future location can\'t be predicted, *all* the branches have
to have the keys. 

> Just an idea for a relatively low tech rather unsophisticated message system
> which doubtlessly has sufficient flaws for ingenious PCs to exploit.

It\'s too insecure for anybody to try it unless they don\'t bother
talking to anybody familiar with security and cryptography first. And
in that case, they\'ll *quickly* get taken for all they\'ve got.

In essence, the problem biols down to needing some "token" that the PCs
can carry that can be verified (to prove that contract terms are
correct and thus that *neither* party has cheated) and that can be
modified/updated (to note when, where, and how big the payments were).

This requires a "key". And whatever it is, *any* branch that the PCs
wind up at has to have it, or they can\'t verify the contract terms, nor
record the new payment on the "token". 

And frankly, the customers are going to be a lot happier if *two* keys
are required. One for them, and one for the bank. That way there has to
be *mutual* agreement before any new info goes into the "token". 

*Reading* the token shouldn\'t require a key, or else should require a
publicly known key that isn\'t easily usable to determine the pair of
write keys.

This sort of thing is *ideal* for the various "public key" ciphers. The
problem is that as computers get better you have to make the keys
longer. Luckily, adding one *bit* to a key generally makes it *at
least* twice as hard to crack. So if you add 8 bits, that\'s 256 times
the effort. Etc.

There is one *bad* problem that could crop up. Adding bits makes things
so much harder because the keys are based on certain mathematical
operations being *much* harder to reverse than to do.

semi-silly example: it\'s easy to determine that 5+4 = 9, but the only
way to determine that the 9 was produced by adding 5 and 4 and not 1
and 8, would be to try both as "keys". (say it was a 2 digit combo, and
you knew that it had to add up to 9) You\'d have to try 0 & 9, 1 & 8, 2
& 7, 3 & 6, and 4 & 5.

Now imagine it with 10 digit numbers. Bad huh? Even so, it wouldn\'t
take a computer long to search, simply because given a total of 65, and
a key of 23, it\'s obvious that the other value has to be 32.

But what most of the public key systems use involves multiplying pairs
of prime numbers instead of merely adding "normal" numbers. So while it
is possible to determine the *product* of my public and private
keys, to determine my private key you have to be able to *factor* that
product. 

So for a *trivial* example, try figuring out which two primes were
multiplied together to produce 1147. Then consider trying to do it with
a number in the billions.

The problem is that there\'s no *guarantee* that there isn\'t some *easy*
way to determine the factors of a number. Nobody has found one, but
mathematicians haven\'t proved that it\'s impossible either.

An early public key system depended on a math problem (the knapsack
algotithm) that someone found a fast solution to. And that rendered
that *method* of encryption invalid. Instead of adding 8 bits making
the things hundred of times harder it only made (say) 8 times harder.
Which meant it was just as hard to generate a longer key as it was to
crack one. Which was no good.

However, even if factoring becomes easy, there are other principles
that public key ciphers can be based on. So as long as there are
ciphers based on different *types* of "hard problems" we are ok. 

In reality, quantum computing could make *all* the hard problems easy.
Luckily, it makes enough *other* things easy that we don\'t have to
worry about it in Traveller. Because it\'d rip the Traveller universe to
shreds.

Thus I\'m confident that a Traveller type universe would have workable
public key encryption. Though they may have to use fairly long keys,
and the Imperium\'s history should include at least one time when they
had to scrap a widely used system and switch to another. 

This would either have led to major hassles during the changeover, or
if people had been smart, it\'d be a damned nuisance. You get the
"damned nuisance" level by *not* using the same algorithm for
everything.

Say you have three different cipher types. One, like PGP depends on
Factoring being hard. Another depends on X and another on Y. So if you
are smart, you use all three. So if one becomes worthless, you\'ve got
the other two to use. 

In the case of ship\'s mortages and payment records, when the bank finds
out that cipher A is no good, they\'ll switch anybody who was using it
to Cipher B. And paranoid types will have insisted in doing things in
triplicate anyway, one in each cipher.

Sound a bit umbersome? Maybe. But if they had a cipher become worthless
and *werent* doing things that way, they\'d lose *everything*, Heck,
that could be a the reason for a major depession or two. But once you
learn that lesson you aren\'t going to forget!

