all
> you want, and all I have to do is build a little bit bigger nuke, then all
> your hard work is for naught.

If you EMP-proof something, the size of the nuke doesn\'t matter.

For instance, one means of avoiding EMP effects is to not use wires to link
devices, switch to fibre-optics for data transmission and fluids for power
transmission. Can you explain how a bigger nuke is going to affect that ?

EMP-proofing processors is not done just by sheilding them, but by ensuring
they are built with small enough tracks that the pulse can\'t generate high
enough voltages to destroy anything, and by error correction mechanisms to
deal with any spurious data caused by the spike. .

If you\'re just talking about EM-sheilding, then yes maybe a bigger nuke will
generate a larger spike that might get through, but that\'s not true
EMP-proofing, that\'s just waht you do to try and protect existing old
equipment, an EMP-proof system needs to be designed from scratch. .

Frankie
