Well, based on my knowledge of the fiigures, and the references I\'ve been
able to come up with, 50,000 warheads is way too high.

My current estimate is that there was unlikley to have been more than 20,000
warheads at any one time, and it\'s more likley to have been much less. It is
quite possible they may have _produced_ 50, 000 warheads by then, but as
previously mentioned, early warheads were unstable and had to be regularly
scrapped.

( BTW, what do you consider the "height of the cold war" ? There were
definitely more warheads around in the late 70\'s than in the 60\'s, and I\'ve
always considered the Cold War was effectively over by the 70\'s )

> Now the damned statistics.  50,000 warheads x 10 megatons means, if
> they were scattered perfectly in perfect conditions, they would
effectively
> destroy 25 mi^2 x 50,000 or 1.25 mio square miles.  Would this wipe out a
> country the size of France?  I don\'t know the size of France, but
California
> is only about 150,000 sq miles.

I\'ll admit my choice of France was random with no real thought to the actual
figures, it was a bad guess
However you\'re right, even with my warhead numbers, France ( 211,000 squae
miles ) could be destroyed twice over.

But not the whole planet.

Even your 1.25M square miles represents only about 1% of the earth\'s
surface.

So I have to admit I was wrong about it being only a country the size of
France, maybe you could take out India (1.26 M sqm). But the basic point of
my statement is proved, at no time did we have the capability to "destroy
all life on earth ten times over", and we also have never had the capability
to destroy all life on earth even once over.

> Now, is this likely (perfect distribution, perfect condition)?  No,
> in fact, impossible.

Exacltly.

> But I\'m pretty certain that if even a decent fraction of these
> warheads landed, France would be functionally obliterated.

Yep.

> Of course, it depends also on how you define "wipe out"?  If you
> mean "disintegrate to atoms" - you\'re right.  But a single 50mt
> lithium-cobalt doped warhead could, over the span of a half-dozen years,
> wipe out human and animal (and a sizeable fraction of vegetable) life on
> this planet.  Leo Szilard pointed that out in what - 1957?  Basic physics
> hasn\'t changed since then, and our understanding of the catastrophic
> consequences of even small amounts of radiation in the natural
environments
> has only gotten better.

1950 I think.

1957 was when the Windscale accident in England proved the "Szilard
complication"

However, talking about what might be possible is a completely different
thing from actual capabilities.

Only one cobalt-salted bomb was ever produced, and was exploded  by the
British at Maralinga, Australia. It was considered a failure, and the
cobalt-60 "doomsday"  device, while theoretically possible may still not be
prove to be workable.

Frankie
