    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>>>Since we\'ve found the crater, the big question is was it a commet or an
>>>asteroid.
>>
>>So what is the difference between a comet and an asteroid ?
>
> Comet = Mostly ice and frozen gas. Some have used the fanciful term
> "dirty snowball".
>
> Asteroid = Very Large Rock.

It\'s a bit more complex than that. There are three types of asteroid
(and likely some combinations). 

Nickel-iron. Mostly nickel and iron with various amounts of other
elements in the mix. Think of them as giant, natural chunks of armor
steel. Average density around that of iron (7.8).

Stony. These are basicly big chunks of igneous rock. They can\'t be
sedimenitary or metamorphic, because those processes require a planet.
But simply *melting rock and letting it seperate into different
minerals as it cools can happen in a quite small body (tens of km,
maybe as low as a km or less). They\'ve got a density like rock. (2-4?)

Carbonaceous chondrites. These are basicly what you get ice you let a
ball of methane/ammonia/water "ice" bake in the sun long enough. The UV
hitting the surface forms more complex compounds, and volatiles get
driven off. These are low in hydrogen, but rich in carbon and nitrogen.
What hydrogen they have is tied up in complex organics. These are
rather porous, and somewhere between tar and charcoal in structure.
They are very low density. 

Comets that hang around the inner system long enough will become
chondrites.

The way you get these types is that planetary systems form from clouds
of gas and dust. The gas tends to form ice particles as the cloud gets
thick enough to shield the inner regions from starlight. And the gases
and other elements react with each other. 

Soon you have clumps of ice with embbeded dust particles. And they
collide and clump farther. 

Since these clouds tend to be formed at least partly from the aftermath
of supernovas, they are rich in shortlived radioisotopes. So even
fairly small "dirty snowballs" will generate enough heat to melt the ice
in the inner layers. Remember, when an object doubles in size, the
volume goes up 8 times but the surface area only goes up 4 times. So
you have 8 times the heat from decay trying to get out thru only 4
times the are. Which means the thermal flux at the surface goes up
linearly as the size increases. Expect there\'s a limit to how much can
be radiated, and it take time. 

So the ice melts and the "dust" settles to the center. There it
consolidates into rock. Especially since ity tends to contain more of
the heat generating elements than the ice does!

If the dirt/rock ball in the center is big enough, *it* melts. And the
nickel iron (and various elements that disolve better in iron than in
rock) settles to the center. After a while, the radioactivity has
dropped off enough that things solidify. 

So now you have small balls of dirty ice, bigger balls of "clean" ice
with dirt/rock centers, and still larger balls of ice with a thick
layer of rock over a nickel iron core. 

Meanwhile, these balls have continued to sweep up dust and gas and
collide with each other, getting even bigger. But once they get to the
stage where the smaller ones have solidifying, the collisions are just
as likely to knock chunks off. And it\'s easier to break a chunk of ice
free from the rock than to break off a piece that includes the ice
*and* more than a trace of ice. So you get most bare rockbals, and
various sized chunks of ice. 

Likewise if rockballs collide, they are more likely to fracture at the
stone/iron boundary. So you wind up with chuunks of ice, some of which
have small amounts of stone still attached. Chunks of rock, which are
somewhat more likely to include chunks of nickel-iron from the
boundary, and chunks of nickel-iron, a few of which may still have some
stone adhering. 

Meanwhile, the gas cloud has flattened into a disk, and some of the
larger chunks have been vacuuming up the smaller ones. You start to get
infant planets, small gas giants, brown dwarves, and finally a star or
stars. 

Once a star lights up, the gas and dust are driven out of the inner
system by the solar wind. And the heat from the star starts evaporating
and melting ices in the inner system. So the smaller bodies lose their
volatiles, which get swept up by planets farther out. Eventually, the
icy bodies get baked down to chondrites.

And the infant planets have gotten big enough that ice flows under
gravity, rocks accumulate under it at the center, and even at the lower
levels of radioactive decay there\'s enough heat to melt rock (and the
pressure helps. 

And any chunks left close enough to the star that haven\'t consolidated
into a planet wind up as asteroids, which the types I listed.

> The largest asteroids are several hundred miles across; if I recall
> correctly, comets top out at several miles, not several hundred...

Actually, there\'s no reason there can\'t* be comets that big. But they\'d
be *very* rare. 
