    'from' => 'Jeff Zeitlin jzeitlin@cyburban.com',
    'body' => 'On Sat, 27 Nov 1999 22:40:51 -0500 (EST), Russell Bornschlegel
<kaleja@estarcion.com> wrote:

>Classic Traveller goobers: A new system for Book 4-7 style generation 
>of Rogues (with Private Eyes and Cops thrown in as a bonus) is 
>available, along with 77 Starship Quirks and Youth In CT, on my web
>site, which has moved:

>http://www.estarcion.com/kaleja/sohl.html

>Comments and constructive criticism always welcome.

I can\'t comment on the Rogue or PI careers, but I _can_ comment
on the Police career, since my job puts me in daily contact with
police on the job in all aspects (I\'m not a cop myself, but I
work for the NYC PD).

I\'ll take it section by section:

(1) Enlistment: OK as written, although you may want to consider
reducing the reenlistment roll to 4+.

(2) Automatic skills: Police should get Gun Cbt (Pistol) at level
1, and Vehicle (appropriate to local conditions) at level 1. This
represents the effect of initial training, and regular retraining
(in NYC, firearms retraining is once per six months; vehicle
retraining is annually while deemed necessary due to accident
statistics).

Also, automatic skill levels should be granted as follows (See
revised Rank table at #7):
 - Leader 1, upon achieving the rank of Sergeant, if the
character doesn\'t already have it.
 - Liaison 1, upon achieving the rank of Lieutenant, if the
character doesn\'t already have it.

(3) Assignment: Change _one_ of the \'Desk Job\' entries to \'Beat
Cop\'. By and large, the primary duty of the police is to patrol
with the intent of acting as a deterrent to crime, rather than to
actively interfere with attempts at crime - although that is part
of their duties as well.  You want low incidence reported, with
most of those being caught, rather than just a high arrest/
conviction rate.

Change \'Homicide\' to \'Detective\'.  Detectives are actually a
separate track from the rest of the department up to a point, but
investigation of \'major\' crimes is left in that bureau\'s hands -
Major crimes being, generally speaking, Homicide (causing the
death of another), Rape (use of \'sexual\' activity as the method
of a crime), assault (a.k.a. assault and battery) (causing severe
harm to a person), Grand Theft (high value - jewels, lots of
money, expensive property, etc.), Robbery (theft with force
directly from a person), Burglary (removal of property from a
premises), and Auto Theft (theft of a Vehicle).

Change \'Vice Squad\' to \'Elite Force\'.  Vice focusses on things
like gambling, prostitution, unlicensed bars/clubs, and so on.
There are other special units, such as SWAT (anti-terrorist,
hostage situations, etc.), Street Crime (gang activity, drug
activity, fencing, etc.), Task Forces (any crime, if it\'s showing
up as a \'hot spot\'), and so on. Of course, it includes Vice Squad
(now often called \'Public Morals Division\').

Change \'High-Tech Investigation\' to \'Elite Unit\'. These are the
people that don\'t really go into harm\'s way - in addition to
investigating white-collar and high-tech crimes, it includes
things like ceremonial units, publicity units, details assigned
to public events, and so on.

Change \'Down or Out\' to \'Disciplinary\' (explanation below).

(4) Resolution: Homicide/Detective and Vice Squad/Elite Force
should have it slightly easier to get a skill - it\'s not unusual
for a cop transferred in to those units to get special training
in whatever they\'re concentrating on at the time of the transfer.
Promotion should also be slightly easier for these units.
Optional change for Beat Cop should be slightly harder; a
character in Desk Job should be forced back to Beat Cop on a roll
of 12. Limit promotion to once per 4-year term.

(5) Skills: Forgery and Bribery should not be \'Desk Job\' skills.
Substitute Liaison and Legal.  \'Desk Jobs\' are generally not
directly involved in day-to-day crime fighting; rather, they
represent the administrative and logistical support for the
day-to-day crime fighting represented largely by Homicide/
Detective and Beat Cop.

Drop \'Brawling\' from Detective/Homicide. Substitute Legal.  This
is mostly an investigative position, rather than an active
go-get-them position. Once the detectives gather the evidence for
an arrest, they generally make it on a warrant and a quiet visit
- - \'Mr. Smith, I have a warrant for your arrest, please come with
me.\' Since detectives often work in plain clothes, it\'s not
unusual for a \'Beat Cop\' to accompany them; his purpose is to do
the brawling if necessary - and it usually isn\'t, surprisingly.

Drop Liaison from \'Beat Cop\' - they don\'t get the chance to
\'liaise\'.  A better one to substitute would be Carousing.

Drop Carousing from Elite Force/Vice Squad. This makes room for
Gun Cbt (long firearm).

Change \'Instruction\' in \'Beat Cop\' to \'Jack-of-all-Trades\'. The
street cop isn\'t going to get much chance to teach while on the
job; rather, he\'ll find where the teachers failed to deal with or
appreciate the _reality_ of the street - training is often
simplified over reality to drive home a point.

Change \'Jack-of-all-Trades\' in \'Desk Job\' to \'Instruction\'. The
trainer typically hasn\'t gone on the street in years, because
they discovered he had a talent for explaining things pretty
clearly - which is what you need when you\'re dealing with the
average street cop.

Change \'Bribery\' in Elite Force/Vice Squad to \'Vice\', which
cascades to Bribery, Forgery, or Intrusion (which covers things
like lockpicking, safecracking, and fingerprinting). Note that
the police cover these skills less from the point of view of \'how
to do it\' than from the point of view of \'how to detect when it\'s
being done\'. Intrusion also covers things like computer
cracking(hacking), wiretapping, and other high-tech
information-gathering techniques, but these would not be the
preferred skills in Elite Force/Vice Squad.  See the next
comment.

You really need a seventh slot in Elite Unit/High-Tech. Since we
