    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>> Several things:
>> Terrorist Attacks: High yield, small package, easy to smuggle that way.
>
> Ah yes, of course, should have thought of that one.

>> Infrastructure destruction
>
> Hmm, this is a posibility if you\'re not worried about the side-effects, the
> target is not hardened, and don\'t care if you take out everythng around the
> target as well. In recent wars it has been shown that precision-guided
> conventional munitions are much better for this purpose.

Depends. We\'ve yet to have a "small conflict" where we needed to take
out something big and sturdy. Closest we\'ve come were some of Saddam\'s
bunkers. 

> Of course, if no-one uses nukes, maybe they didn\'t bother, but I suspect
> spaceships are going to be EMP-proof by nature, given all the radiation they
> have to put up with normally.

Well, there\'s a difference between radiation (gamma rays, x-rays, and
high velocity particles) and EMP. Shielding against radiation won\'t do
diddly against EMP and vice versa. 

Unless a ship spends a lot of time *close* to a *very* active star,
their protection against EMP is going to be fairly minimal. 

>> Sensor Blinding: H-Bombs are VERY effective at short term blinding of
>> sensors; Orbital Flashing should cover even a massive jump-in
>
> This could be considered a draw-back of nuclear weapons, as it does the same
> thing to your sensors, though yes, if you need to blind everybody\'s sensors
> for a short time for some reason, they are good.

There\'s also the question of "what do you mean by \'blind\'?". Some
sensors suffer permanent damage from overloads above a certain level.
Other\'s just quit working until the signal gets reasonable. And some
have a period after the overload where they have to "recover" before
reaching full sensitivity. 

Woe unto the attacker who thinks the enemy sensors are the first kind,
or even the third kind if they are actually the second kind. Sort of
like attacking at night and then finding out the enemy has IR and
nightvision gear. Oops.

> But again they\'ll only affect electro-magnetic sensors, mass detectors would
> be unaffected, for example.

Maybe. Sufficiently advanced mass detectors (mass detectors generally
detect *density* variations, rather than actual "mass") might have
trouble with the rapidly moving density changes due to the shockwave
and the like. 

