    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>>Remember, there\'s *no* way to determine *in
>>advance* which branch a ship will be at several months from now.
>>So they *all* have to be able to deal with it. 
>
> I would think it would be very easy for a bank to determine which branch
> a ship will be making its\' payment at.  When the loan is first applied
> for the bank would want an exact business plan & itinerary on how the
> ship will be used to make a profit.  They would determine that the ship
> would have to stop off at a specific branch to make payments every so
> many months.  If the ship didn\'t show, it would automatically be
> reported to the authorities and a repo list.  A bank wouldn\'t approve a
> loan on a wide, far reaching, or risky route.

Sorry, but that\'s equivalent to requiring an *independent* long haul
trucker to file an itinerary months in advance. Just like Free Traders,
they go where the cargoes are. 

If you want them to pay at a specificplace, then you\'d better give them
a several month window. 

> That way the key system of encryption would be very useful without
> giving all branches all of the keys.

> That is the way it works IMTU anyway.

There\'s still another problem with anything that uses one-time pad
technology. Say the ship is going to be someplace 4 or 5 jumps away for
his next payment. Ok, that\'s 5 weeks to h\\get the proper key there. But
if something goes wrong (ship carrying the key disappears, branch
manager suspects it was compromised, etc) 5 more weeks to get word back
to HQ. It\'ll take *another* 5 weeks to get the new key there. And 5
more on top of that to be sure it was ok. That\'s *20* weeks. For a
*quarterly* payment. 

Also, the key for the contract/payments has to be "fixed" because you
can\'t contact the ship to arrange changes. So that means that every
single branch the ship has used has a copy of the key. Which makes it
vulnerable, especially since it is "old" and "unimportant".

For that matter, I just realized that we *have* to use "public key"
type method. Conventional encryption can\'t protect a message (or data)
from someone who already knows the un-encrypted version. And since the
owner of the ship *does* know, you\'re screwed already. 

