    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>>I suspect that\'s one of those silly archaisms, as most military tech _now_
>>can be proofed against EMP, assuming they want to pay for it, and how is
> EMP
>>going to effect laser or maser comms anyway? (unless the burst is in direct
>>line of sight for lasers
>
> The problem is that EMP proofing is very expensive compared to building a
> bigger nuke. What it boils down to is that you can harden your material all
> you want, and all I have to do is build a little bit bigger nuke, then all
> your hard work is for naught.

Not really. The EMP output of a nuke goes up a lot slower than the
yeild does. Also, since EMP is "merely" a magnetic field "spike", there
are limits to what it can do. There are also *inherently* EMP resistant
(or even immune) technologies. 

A faraday cage will ground out any practical amount of EMP. Of course,
it\'ll also shield against radio, and make it rather hard to use wired
links. But a fiber optic link between the indide and the outside is
perfectly safe.

This is because EMP works by inducing current in any conductors aligned
at an angle to its direction of propogation. Since optical fibers are
non-conductive, they aren\'t affected. 

The *voltage* induced in a conductor depends on the length of the
conductor, measured at right angles to the pulse propogation. So a 10
mile power line aligned with the path of the pulse might get less of an
induced "spike" that a metal yardstick at right angles to the pulse. 

Thermionic devices ("tubes" or "valves") are *highly* resistant to EMP.
This is simply because they are already designed to handle high
voltages, and the sort of high voltage, low to medium current spike
that EMP induces will merely cause a momentary arc between elements in
the tube after which the tube continues operating as before.
*Lightning*, being high voltage, high *current* tend to melt wires. EMP
doesn\'t.

Semiconductor devices are so terribly vulnerable to EMP because the
various sorts of "junctions" that they use for switching and amplifying
are effectively *solid* dielectric capacitors. And it takes very little
excess voltage to do permanent damage by "burning thru" the junction
(that\'s why anti-static precautions are so important). 

If we develop small, fast "optical switches" then we can merely place
the (laser?) light source inside a small faraday cage along with its
power supply. An optical fiber can carry the light to the "photonic"
devices. And EMP won\'t do a damned thing to it. 

Also, back in the late 50s/early 60s, the military developed some quite
interesting thermionic devices. Basicly, they miniaturized the tubes to
the size of a *dime*, and built the whole device as a "solid" block of
metal and ceramics (the only hollows were the insides of those dime
sized tubes, and maybe some capacitors). I\'d say the size of the
devices compared favorably with transistorized printed circuit devices,
or even early IC based devices. Rather than have to deal with tubes
failing because of filaments burning out, the whole block was run
inside what amounted to a small oven! By using the proper metals and
ceramics this worked just fine. 

These were known as TIMMs (Thermally Integrated Micro Modules, or
something like that). Besides being immune to EMP, they also tended to
be very resistant to high radiation environments. And, given their
design, they *loved* high temperatures. Red hot was just fine. Orange
hot might degrade their performance some (resistanaces and inductances
tend to change at those temps). 

Still, this "lost technology" really deserves to be revived. There are
a lot of places where it\'d do nicely. Smelters, instrument packages
intended to operate inside active volcanos (What do you mean we have to
insulate it becayse the volcano isn\'t *hot* enough! :-). And, of
course, it\'d be great for a Venus or mercury probe. 

But given that we have one technology that\'s EMP immune and are making
significant progress in another, I think the Imperium can deal with it.

