    'body' => '>As you can see, the 181 AD eruption is estimated to have put around one
>hundred cubic _kilometres_ of material into the atmosphere, and according to
>other sources I\'ve read, several of those cubic kilometres were blown into
>the stratosphere.

The web site says...
- ----
- ----
This eruption took place from a vent or vents near the Horomatangi Reefs, now
submerged on the eastern side of Lake Taupo. The eruption lasted between
several days and several weeks and produced a sequence of pumice deposits that
blanketed the landscape east of Taupo. In total about 100km3 was erupted.

...
At the climax of this eruption, about 30km3 of pumice, ash and rock fragments
was erupted in only a few minutes and travelled horizontally as a liquid flow,
moving at speeds estimated at between 600-900kmh. It crossed every obstacle in
its path except the top of Mt Ruapehu.

- ----
- ----

From this I would interpret that while one hundred km3 of material was
erupted, most of it didn\'t go "into the atmosphere" except in the sense of
flying upwards or sideways a few meters. If a typical eruption speed was the
600-900 km/h described above, the highest altitude the debris could
reach would be 3000 m or so, so I\'d be interested to see the "other sources"
suggesting several km3 made it into the stratosphere. (Elsewhere the
website does mention a column 50km high, so some fraction does make it
into the stratosphere.)

More fundamentally, how long particles persist in the atmosphere depends
strongly on their size. Even if several km get into the stratosphere, if most
of
it is pebbles of pumice, they\'re going to fall right back down again. It\'s
the ash and similar tiny particles that count; figuring out the ratio of ash
freed up by nuclear explosions/fires vs volcanoes is non-trivial, and a
direct comparison of material volumes isn\'t helpful.

Bruce
