>EMP-proofing processors is not done just by sheilding them, but by ensuring
>they are built with small enough tracks that the pulse can\'t generate high
>enough voltages to destroy anything, and by error correction mechanisms to
>deal with any spurious data caused by the spike. .
>
The problem lies more in the fact that the voltage requirements for
microcircutry to be blown WILL be generated with sections as low as 2CM
long consistantly if you are anywhere within the LD10% radius...
(Scientific american had something on this when I was in Jr. High... about
1980). Any conductive metalic substance will generate current from EMP. The
smaller the circutry, the smaller the spike needed to cause a failure. Note
the term failure doesn\'t mean it stops working; it means that it no longer
works as designed. If there is current flowing during the spike, you may
wind up with gates frozen in one position. Memory is even more prone to
this kind of failure. The static charge built up is also a problem.

The smaller the circutry, the lower it\'s voltage tolerances. Vaccum tubes,
mind you, are recoverable. Solid state, in most cases, is replace. Put 5w
through most 2W processors, and it\'s time to buy a new one. Put 50W
through, and you definitely need a new one.

Currently, EMP resistant processors use a combination of a faraday cage and
radiation shielding, along with spike resistant design. None is EMP "PRoof".

The FIB computers, in traveller, are the ones with a completely optical
secondary system which parallels the main one. If you look at the HG and MT
rules, EMP is not limited to just vaping computers.

EMP also has other fun effects: Fillings &/or orthodontia will generate
current & static charges. Surgical Pins, Plates, Screws, and meshes will
get hit with a charge, too. At high enough levels, even the Iron and trace
metals in your body will generate some current (But you\'d prolly be well
cooked by then).

One other thing: The primary route of EMP current generation is going to be
the power feeds. No computer operates without power. Even if you isolate
the system, using a battery, you will get some EMP effects.

>If you\'re just talking about EM-sheilding, then yes maybe a bigger nuke will
>generate a larger spike that might get through, but that\'s not true
>EMP-proofing, that\'s just waht you do to try and protect existing old
>equipment, an EMP-proof system needs to be designed from scratch. .
>
Unless you have a completely secluded system, any faraday cage (the best
defense against EMP from all that I\'ve read) will have some holes, even if
they are filled with fiber cables. You need a power feed... Either a
battery or generator inside the cage, too.

One other thing: Solar flares can and do generate EMP. In Alaska, it
sometimes gets strong enough (Courtesy of the polar magnetosphere gap) to
shut down computers and other sensitive devices. Especially in the
fairbanks and barrow areas. Strong enough that during high solar flares,
induced current has been known to make phones whose line is severed at the
house (non-payment) ring. If EMP-Proof equipment was feasable, it would be
in use north of 70deg N. As it is, most people just take the risks... Even
worse, the magnetic pole is close enough that it makes navigation a problem.

