    'month' => '11',
    'body' => 'On 11/28/99 at 03:03 PM,  "shadowcat" <meow@advancenet.net> said:

>Seriously, one of the quibbles I have about the various ship design
>sequences in Traveller is that one gains no extra benefit from
>increasing the number of computers (over the required number) linked
>into ship operations.  Perhaps for each additional doubling of
>computing power, the crew requirement could be halved.

I\'ve never been happy with computer hardware and software rules, and
being determined to get the Mae Lee\'s stats up on the web, I was
working on them this weekend.  Hoping I wouldn\'t have to reinvent
the wheel, I worked backwards through the versions looking for
something I liked...

First, GT.  GURPS has computer hardware and software rules that look
very good.  I don\'t like the 2xlog10 complexity, though.  Your TL-4
MainFrame (TL-10) complexity 6 can run 6 Complexity 6 programs, 120
Complexity 5 programs, 1200 Complexity 4 programs...argh!!!  I
forsee too much bookkeeping, but the idea *is* appealing.

T4, FFS2, CSC.  Sorry, but I\'m still scratching my head.  CSC comes
close, but...I just can\'t get into them.

TNE and FFS. Nooo, afraid not.

MT.  I\'ve got MT, first printing, and the amount of errata in my
books is such that I\'ve never been able to figure out how to use the
computer rules.  Heck, I don\'t think they work at all...as they
appear in my book. <sigh>

CT.  Forget High Guard, it\'s just a simplification of Book 2.  Hum,
Book 2...I think Book 2 had the beginnings of a good system.  There
were too few computer models, no rules for creating other models,
and we all know the volume, power and price problems, but I *really*
did like those individual programs, the juggling the PC\'s had to do
to get the right ones running at the right time, and the effects
they had on gameplay.  If only there *were* rules for creating new
hardware and software for the Book 2 model...

Surfice it to say, my final choice for computer rules was CT,
suitablly tweeked, of course.  I\'m going to (and frankly, I hope
someone out there has already) come up with hardware construction
and software writing rules eventually, but for now I just WAGed a
bunch of new models and new software programs to pick from.

Tweeks.

    1.  Shrink the volume of Ship Mainframes to 2 dtons or less.
        Although they are smaller, they continue to be larger than
        you might expect for several reasons: 

        a. they are *heavily* shielded from radiation and EMP
        b. they are constructed to be self-correcting and massively
           redundent
        c. they also include space for an occupied workstation
        
    2.  Reduce the power and cost to ~10% of the price listed in
        LLB2. 
        
    3.  Multiply the CPU by ~100 and Storage by ~500.  Now, you have
        room at the bottom of the scale for mini and micro
        computers.
        
    4.  Have the volume and cost drop, while capability (processing
        and storage) increase as the TL\'s change.

    5.  Include mini computers for optional dedicated procressing.
        Put one in the Astrogation station, in the Pilot\'s station,
        the Sensor Ops station, etc, and let them run the programs
        for that station..or, of course, keep the stations as smart
        terminals served by a big mainframe.  You get trade offs in
        cost, reliability and flexibility going either way.
        
    6.  Add many more available software packages.  Specifically,
        packages that reduce the number of technical personnel you
        need to operate the ship.  You trade off the cost of
        installing and maintaining more computers with the cost of
        hiring and maintaining Engineers and Techs.
        
I don\'t know how well all this works.  The added models *are* WAGs,
the software list is short and still in flux, and getting from the
guesses to a *system* of construction isn\'t a sure thing, but I\'m
pretty pleased with it as a first pass. 

I\'ll post the tables in my next post.

Eris
