>Is that a list of all the police ranks or did you just adapt it to
>Traveller?
>Do the police differentiate between enlisted and officers as the
>military does?

That\'s actually an adapted list; the complete list would be as
follows:

Recruit
Police Officer/Detective
Corporal/Detective Investigator
Sergeant/Detective Sergeant
Lieutenant
Commander
Captain
Deputy Inspector
Inspector
Assistant Chief
Vice Chief
Bureau Chief
Chief of Department

The Detective track and the rest of the department merge at
Lieutenant.  Departments that do not have their own police
academy normally omit Recruit; most municipal departments omit
Corporal/Detective Investigator (usually, State Police have this
rank).  Commander is generally omitted, but does occur in some
departments that don\'t have all four \'Chief\' ranks. Really small
police departments (rural villages, for example) may not have any
rank above Captain, and the Captain will be called \'Chief\'.

NYC omits Corporal/Detective Investigator and Commander, but has
all four \'Chief\' ranks.

Ranks are Civil Service (promote by examination and seniority) up
to Captain; ranks above Captain are political appointments.

There is a nominal distinction equivalent to Enlisted and
Commissioned, but in practice, it normally is meaningless.  Some
departments have strong policies against fraternization with
anyone of subordinate rank, others limit such policies to direct
chain-of-command, others have no policy.  NYC has a
chain-of-command fraternization policy, enforced only when there
are clear problems because of it.
