    'topic' => 'Mini Review: Lost Keith Supplements',
    'body' => 'Wow!  I want to run a CT game, *right* now! <g>

The long awaited collection of the Keith CT supplements came in a
nice folio, with a big \'Keith Brothers "Lost Supplements Collection\'
sticker on the side.  Inside there are 8, 8.5x11 stapled books, and
an envelope containing several small "goodies." 

The books have manila cardstock covers with Keith drawings on the
covers and "blurbs" on the back.  The pages inside appear to be a
good heavy stock and are *filled* with pen drawings interspersed
within the 2 column text.  The only shortcoming I can see is that
the covers don\'t quite cover the inner pages.  I suppose the only
way to make that work would be to have inner pages progressively
narrower, and I can\'t really blame Cargonaut Press for this...I
wouldn\'t have thought of it either.

I\'ve just finished reading the first two of the eight books, "Letter
of Marque" and "Scam", volumes I & II of the Rogues in Space
series.  There is a very large book "Faldor:  World of Adventure",
adventures on a primitive planet.  "The Arctic Environment", with
rules and adventures in that sort of environment.  "Starport
Planetfall", a collection of rules and encounter tables dealing with
starports and landings on planets. All these books were authored by
J. Andrew Keith  There is also "Reaver\'s Deep", a complete
sourcebook for the named sector, written by Paul Sanders, the
"Imperial Calender", mostly a book of large drawings, by William H.
Keith, and "The Volentine Gambit", a 30 page set of instructions and
background to a computer game, by Jim Long.

The envelope includes an adventure by Hans Ranke, "Hellion\'s Hoard",
the disk for the game mentioned above, maps of charted space and
Faldor, and cardstock forms for use with the two Rogues in Space
books.  It also contained a bumper sticker for Far Frontier Tours
advertising their tours on Faldor, a tri-fold brochure for Arctic
Adventures advertising their expedition cruises, a very ornate (and
official looking) Letter of Marque and Quitclaim Deed.  Finally,
there was a credit card sized (and plasticized) Bar Chit "Entitles
bearer to one free drink per day in any Imperial Starport
Establishment." <g>

I already own the earlier version of "Letter of Marque", and I don\'t
see any major changes in this second version.  Even so it is *much*
better.  The layout and organization of material makes it much
easier to read and use.  There are rules for generating pirates and
detailed rules for "commerce raiding" in all forms.  Additionally,
there are rules for damage control, repairs and breakdown though the
addition of a "Reliability" rating for various ship systems.  There
are 5 very complete adventure setups, and 4 ships complete with
deckplans. 

"Scam" is a complete treatment of con games and stings done for
Traveller.  Andrew extends the system to include 6 new attributes
detailing the personality and behavioral profile of the character.
His Universal Behavioral Profile (UBP), adds Persuasion, Charm,
Insight, Gullibility, Character and Will to the mix in the familiar 1
1 to 15 range, but also gives ways to "fake it" using the old UPP
characteristics.  These new characteristics, and a number of new and
changed skills form the heart for a set of rules covering lying,
intimidation, mimicry, bribery, haggling, blackmail and many other
nefarious and not so nefarious activities.  A complete character
generation system is included for the Con-man career.  Finally, 4
complete adventures are included.

Wow!  This is *good* stuff!

Eris
