Let\'s take another crack at it:
 
> >"DOMINATUS HOMINIS SPLENDET SPLENDIDE AMPLOIS OUAM 
> >GLORIAM ASTRIBUS"
> 
> DOMINATUS:  noun, nominative case, rule or dominion
> HOMINIS:  noun, genetive case, of man or of mankind
> SPLENDET:  verb, third person singular, present
> indicative or possibly subjunctive; splendere

splendere means "to shine"

> SPLENDIDE:  adverb, splendidly
> AMPLOIS:  no idea

I don\'t find any Latin words in Langenscheidt\'s that have "oi" or "ui"
following "ampl". Amplus is an adjective meaning "of large extent,
ample, spacious, roomy"; "strong, violent," "splendid, magnificent,
glorious, honorable," or "esteemed, distinguished, honored, ilustrious,
excellent, noble."  "Amplius" is a noun meaning "a greater amount; a
larger sum"

> OUAM:  probably "quam", which

Interrogative, "how much" or relative, "as much as"

> GLORIAM: noun, accusative case, glory
> ASTRIBUS: noun, genetive plural, of the stars

"The rule of man shines brightly to as great an extent as the glory of
the stars."

We humans are modest, if nothing else.

- --Glenn
