I\'ve also thought about the computer scaling problem with traveller. The
only way I see to get around it, if you go with the programs, is to have to
have more programs on larger ships. The combat programs are the easiest to
do this with. If every gun or perhaps battery requires another program then
we now will need more computer. If you then consider the program feeds a
gunnery program must have we end up with even more computer needed. Of
course to do this you have to take a look at all the programs your planning
on having in the game because we find that each helps and hinders the other.
Can you have a target program that is of x level if the sensors are of x-1
or even if the maneuver program isn\'t giving enough significant digits for
that matter.

The bottom line of course is that a small computer can run a very large ship
but not one that needs to do a lot of things. This means you can have a bulk
freighter that has a small crew but couldn\'t fight it\'s way out of a paper
bag.

I know this isn\'t keeping with the tread but I think of ships in traveller
much like the Sailing ships of old. If we are looking at ships of the line,
they were way over manned, had more sail and shot than they could use, and
had tall masts and extra rigging but ran out of water quickly and spent a
considerable amount of time in port. For having this large mast their
effective horizon was further away, they had plenty of people to keep up
with many things going on at the same time and had the equipment to meet any
contingency. The small brig that was trying to make a profit however had
barely enough people to keep up with the weather and would took so much time
to come about that the guns would be useless even if they were manned. In a
battle type situation they were simple overloaded with all the tasks that
needed to be performed.

Computers and manning levels in traveller should be the same way.

Btw eris I like the programs<G>
