One thing to consider, the larger the ship, the larger the I/O
requirements.  The greater the I/O requirements, the greater the storage
requirements.  Ponder this, for the equivalent of a PC the deciding factor
is the user interface, well that and making it big enough that you don\'t
easily loose it.

On the other hand a computer dealing with ships sensors is going to have to
have some pretty fancy interfacing hardware, and it will deal with all
kinds of inputs.

Same thing with the computer that deals with the Jump drive.  In fact for
the jump drive you may have individual inputs from points all over the jump
grid.  This could be a good reason for increased size and expense with
larger vehicles.  Each one of those sensors costs money, each one requires
an interface to the computer.  It adds up.

Then there is environmentals, failover systems, etc.


Think about the differences between Microcomputer, and
Minicomputer/Mainframes.  As an example I\'m typing this on a G4 PowerMac,
by todays standards it\'s a very powerful system, however, I\'ve got 3 PCI
slots, and one AGP slot.  Though I can hang a lot of stuff off it with
Firewire and USB, I can add SCSI and hang still more devices off of it.
But, a microcomputer really isn\'t that great and handling massive I/O
loads.

On the other hand off to my left is a PDP-11/73 Minicomputer, by today\'s
standards it\'s painfully slow, but it\'s got a 12 slot backplane, and I
could chain other backplanes to it in order to get more slots.  I can stick
an unbelievable range of I/O cards in it, that just aren\'t possible on a
Microcomputer.  As an example I could easily hang a dozen terminals on the
PDP-11 without any difficulty.  Or I could have a bunch of Analog to
Digital cards in it, and have it monitoring machinary.  I could have a
fully functional system with just three cards, but I could have a total of
20 cards in just this chassis.  The Mac is the size of a normal tower PC,
the PDP-11 the is size of a short filing cabinet, it makes a good endtable.

The real difference between Micro\'s, Mini\'s and Mainframes isn\'t the speed,
it\'s the I/O and storage capabilities.  You want something built for speed,
you go with a system built specifically for speed.  I think by a certain
tech level most all processors will pretty much be the same speed, speed
differences will be based on the number of processors (we\'re already
starting to see this).

Also, sometimes you don\'t want the greatest level of miniturization
possible.  Larger is easier to work on, and it might be more reliable.  The
smaller a device, the harder to repair, and the more specialized the
equipment needed to repair it.

Oh, and all those sensors hooked up to the computers generate logs.
Someone cycles an airlock, it\'s logged, someone turns on the lights in a
compartment, it\'s logged.  The larger the ship, the more you log.  The more
you log, the greater the storage requirements.  You might want redundant
storage in different parts of the ship on in case something happens to one
part of the ship.

Oh, and as for software costs.  Standard pricing schemes once you get out
of PC class computing seems to be the greater the size of the system, the
more it costs.  For example the software to backup said PC might cost $150,
but the *exact* same software being used to backup a 1.5TB fileserver migth
cost
$30,000.  Specialized software such as video editing software is likely to
cost $1000, yet you can get a Encyclopedia for $35.  There is no reason to
believe this won\'t continue on into the far future.

Just some random semi-disorganized thoughts.

