Hmmm, just took another look at your list.  You need to include databases
in it.  When the sensors pickup a target, the you\'ll need to have databases
for identifying things about it.  For example, on the Solomani Rim, you
wouldn\'t need the Zhodani Ships Database, but you might want it if you were
bouncing around behind the claw.  Other databases would included things
such as known weapons systems and sensors.

For example, you\'ve jumped into a system near the Zhodani boarder.  Your
sensor operator picks up a incoming track.  The computers would start
searching your Ships recognition databases.  Then if the operator clicks on
that track, the computer will display its best guess (or possibly guesses
(should be software selectable)).  Then the operator decides it\'s hostile
and queries about weapons systems, based on the data in the Ship
recognition database the computer pops up a list of suspected weapons
systems, and the operator can click on one of them and the computer will
pull it up from the weapons database.  All the while the computer is
processing sensor output, trying to get a better idea of what the track is,
and how it\'s configured, as time progresses any variances from the norm
would be displayed in a different colour.

Since this kind of tracking would suck up the CPU cycles, you\'d want to
also designate a target as display only, don\'t analyze.  On friendly ships
you\'d get most of this info from the transponder signals.

Software and databases would have a minimum of two quality levels, civilian
and military, and in reality, would probably have more.  For example, there
might be a level above military that includes data not normally available
to the military (spy ships of some sort might fall into this catagory).

Now here is a scarry thought, because all this is computer controlled the
Imperium might very well be able to arrange for certain classes of ships to
remain undetected simply by having the software not display the tracks!

BTW, what was the purpose of your list?

