Latin was a living language for a long time, so it\'s not surprising that
there are different ways to pronounce it.  My imperfect understanding is
as follows:  Classical Latin was spoken a very long time ago, like
before 0 CE.  Vulgar Latin and Church Latin are the more recent use, and
are pronounced somewhat like Italian.  Legal Latin differs from country
to country, and only vaguely resembles Classical or Vulgar Latin (that
is certainly the case in English).  Italian is known to some people as
Latin for regular people to use.

- --Glenn
