    'month' => '11',
    'body' => '>I don\'t have much problem with that. IMO the controls (in FF&S, MT,
>etc), which are volume dependent, represent the parts of the computer
>system that vary in size with the size of the ship. I see no real need
>to make the CPU and memory change in size with increasing ship size.
>However maybe it should cost more (for extra HD space, more expensive
>software, etc).

One question would be, to what extent is what we consider Hard Drive space
simply Computer memory at a certain techlevel?  Hard Drives are a thing of
the past, even for us, to many moving parts so reliability is a problem.
The future is most likely Holographic storage(1), or some form of RAM disk
along the lines of what a lot of digital cameras use.  This is current
tech, though not widely available or even known, who is to say what they\'re
using in the Imperium.

In any case the larger the ship the greater the requirements for CPU and
memory capacity.  Each thing the computer is keeping track of will require
at least a little memory, and the more things you keep track of the more
CPU horsepower it will take to track everything.

			Zane

(1) Holographic storage and optical computer have been around for over 10
years.  Recently some serious advances in Laser technology have seriously
increased the storage capacity of such things.  IIRC, 10 years ago a piece
of material the size of a sugar cube could hold the equivalent of a CD-ROM.
Unfortunatly this tech is still in the laboratory as far as I know.
