    'topic' => 'Traveller Adventure: The Acadian',
    'body' => 'Traveller Adventure Notes
"The Acadian"

I would appreciate suggestions!  Post them to the TML or
email me at eaglesto@nortelnetworks.com

This adventure assumes the PCs have a small starship (100 to
400 dtons), and a more or less normal crew.  I am also assuming
they are wandering around District 268, Glisten, Trin\'s Veil or
some other place with useful backwaters.  Our group has used
their characters in the Chamax Plague and Horde.  I guess these
characters are the Hard Luck PCs.


Scene 1. The Set-Up

[This scene is stolen material from Jens Rydholm... it looks good enough
to use!]

The PCs are hired by a megacorporation (SuSAG?) to take some
"medical supplies in sealed containers" to a research station somewhere
Far Away (TM).  They get paid well, but are ordered to keep the fact
that they are working for the company secret.

When the ship gets to the destination, they find out that the storage
limitations at the base requires the containers to be split inside the cargo
hold, and the smaller cases inside to be unloaded separately.

Inside the containers are several boxes about 2.5x1.0x0.5 meters. They
have some electronics attached to them, and look suspiciously like low
berths.

As the last cases are being transported out of the hangar using an old
four-wheeler of some kind, the PCs recieve their payment from an officer.
Suddenly, one of the cases crashes to the ground. The plastic breaks, and a
something shows through. A human hand. The officer rushes the PCs into
their ship, adds about 25% or so to their payment, gives them a warning
look, and leaves. They are more or less ordered to leave the station as
soon as possible.

After this, a number of things could happen. If the PCs go to some kind
of bigger media, they won\'t be believed. If they go to smaller, more
honest media, or perhaps seek rumors in bars or somesuch, they will hear
rumors of horrible experiments...

In any case, no matter if they talk about the affair or not, the officer
that paid the PCs will regret (after orders/threats from his superiors)
that he let them go. Agents of the corporation will begin to look for
the PCs. Depending on how public they have made themselves, they will be
more or less easy to find...


Scene 2.  Shock Value

The PCs arrive in yet another backwater system, to hear a GK
broadcasting from the outsystem.  They of course load their weapons
and sneak into the outsystem, where they find a Corsair drifting amidst
the wreckage of another, comparably-sized vessel.  The ship does not
respond to hailing.  Analysis of the Corsair reveals it has functioning
life support, though it appears to have only low levels of power.  Unlikely
as it seems, the ships appear to have collided, and the corsair somehow
survived, while the other appears to have been ripped to shreds.

Analysis of the wreckage indicates that the other ship was a 400
dton unstreamlined vessel.  Residual power signatures indicate it
had a standard drive/power system.

Boarding the corsair, the crew are randomly attacked by disgusting
parasitical? creatures lurking on board... which also, by the way, are
casually eating the corpses of the corsair\'s former crew.

The crew were wearing Imperial government uniform -- plain navy
blue with brass and a starburst.  No ID, no name tags... and no
ship\'s log.


Scene 3.  The Acadian

The PC\'s ship arrives in yet another backwater system.  Doing a
routine scan, they detect two other ships: one is a lab ship, hanging
out just on the edge of detectability, and the other is a trader, in the
inner system.  As is common out here, there is no data on either ship.
The crew notices that the trader is underpowered, and its transponder
is off, it is not accelerating, and its vector is off the plane of the system;
in fact, it appears to be adrift, and all attempts at communication will
result in dead space.

It\'s not necessary for the players to investigate, but it\'s most of the
work I\'ve done so far... the ship is the far trader Acadian.  Its
power plant is in sleep mode.  It has one laser and one sandcaster.
Its hull is in fine condition -- no signs of battle scars recent or old.

The ship is of a classic Vilani design -- the casual observer can\'t
really tell, but captains generally can -- and boarding the ship will
confirm the ship\'s construction.  Her registry is of the Aakkaad
Shipyards of Vland.  Vilani traders are known to be annoyingly
low-automation ships, with coded jump tapes, manual power plant
controls (i.e. control rods, flow valves, and mechanical pressure
gauges), an analog cockpit, and mechanical air compressors,
filtration systems, etc.  That said, it is noted that all these pieces
work beutifully well, giving a cool, smooth, metallic feel to controls
that would otherwise be digital-in-plastic with solid-state blinking
lights (Das machine control is nicht fer geverken by das dumkopfen!)

One divergence from the classic Vilani design is in the sensors --
they are excellent, better than most traders would bother with.
Of course, in these systems, having good sensors is understandable.

The PCs have two opportunities: they have salvage rights, which
entitles them to posession of the ship.  The ship is probably worth
MCr10... unless they take it to Vland, in which case it\'s worth maybe
MCr20.  However, a little digging will unearth the identities of the
former crew of the Acadia -- they look normal enough -- and the
interesting fact that there was a MCr50 policy taken out on the crew,
originated from a bank on a world a few parsecs away.  However, no
more data is forthcoming.  Perhaps it would be interesting to see what
the bank knows about this.

One of the crew opens the \'fridge, only to find that all the perishables
- -- stocked only a few days ago -- have gone badly rotten.


Scene 4.  Those Wacky Droyne

The next system has a few obvious ships: a system defense boat
or two, a trader or two, and another lab ship, which seems to hang
right on the edge of detection range.

One trader is a Droyne ship.  The Droyne are very friendly, and
a bit silly.  They have an annoying habit of buzzing the PCs ship.
At any type of contact they become obsequious to the extreme,
bringing gifts and interesting food on board if allowed, and inviting
PCs to their ship to dine with them, play video games, whatever.
Most are young, but even the older members of the crew seem a
little daft.  From the innumerable slide shows, party games, and
magic tricks, the PCs may conclude that the Droyne brain isn\'t
geared for focused thought.  A number of ship systems aboard
the Droyne trader are in disrepair and show signs of obvious
neglect.


Scene 5.  The Bank

The next system is empty, except for a lab ship in the inner system,
heading outsystem at a constant 1G in a straight line.  Should the
PCs trader take a close look at lab ship, they will see Droyne markings
plainly on the hull, yet the ship maintains communications silence.

If the PCs manage to make contact with it, for some reason (faking
an emergency and forcing interstellar assistance laws?), they will find
the ship crewed with humans, not Droyne, who will render as little
assistance as possible to the trader before scurrying off on their way.

When the PCs reach the bank which issued/holds the insurance policy,
they will find out that the policy has already been cashed in, by a
megacorporation... say, SuSAG.


Scene X.  Now We\'re A Concerned Party

Imagine their surprise and concern when the crew turns out to have
a policy placed on them by SuSAG!



Questions for you.

1) How and when do they find the policy taken out on their ship?
2) Where to go from here?  What new enigma should be thrown
on them?  It\'s been pretty innocuous up to this point...
3) How can I massage these scenes to blend better?  Or do they
work together fine?
4) Should I give them a framework to work within?  For example,
should they be working for a megacorporation delivering mail between
these backwater systems and a regional center of commerce?
5) Should Scenes 1 and 2 be switched in order?  And should Scene 1
be merged with, say, scene 3 or 4?


Answers from me.

A) No, I don\'t quite know where it\'s going.
B) Yes, I\'m trying to make this gritty and X-files-like
