> Different organization entirely.  Sheriff\'s Departments are
> generally at the county level, and often focus on _code_
> enforcement rather than _law_ enforcement, and deal in civil
> actions.  Thus, the massive ticket-and-tow operations when double
> parking gets out of control in an area are usually under the
> Sheriff\'s command; so is the service of subpoen or eviction
> notices - even though there will be cops involved with both.

Not where the Sheriff\'s department is the primary law enforcement
agency. In New York City the situation is pretty much as you describe,
even in much of suburban (to NYC) New York it\'s similar (since NY has a
large State Police force) I remember how surprised I was once, driving
along in NYC, to see a Queens County sheriff\'s car. ("Theres a Sheriff\'s
Department here??? I\'ve never heard of them. What do they DO???!!!")

OTOH, Los Angeles County has a very large Sheriffs department, which
handles the entire range of police duties, from parking violations to
homicide investigations. They cover the vast areas of the Los Angeles
Metro area that isn\'t _in_ Los Angeles proper, though you couldn\'t
easily tell it on the ground.

Here the Pima County, the Sheriff\'s department is about as large as
Tucson\'s PD, with all the same responsibilities with a much larger
geographical area to cover. (FWIW, about 1/2 of the total population of
Pima county lives outside of the Tucson City area, though mostly still
in the so called \'metro area\' around Tucson, the rest of the county is
pretty sparsely populated, and a great deal of it is Indian lands, which
have their own police forces.) There\'s a LOT of interagency stuff going
on, and there\'s also been talk of combining county and city agencies
into a single metro-area government.

- -- 
Bruce Johnson
