For a different take on the Police, see my version of Police for MegaTraveller.

Go to my website, then ==> Tavonni Repair Bays ==> Police Characters for
MegaTraveller.

This is actually based on the UK model portrayed in "The Bill". For those who
want a US-based version, use Jeff\'s ranks. For example, there is no "Lieutenant"
or "Captain" in the UK system, and the US uses "Chief of Police" rather than
"Commissioner of Police", since there is no monarch to receive a commission
from.

Naturally, since local law enforcement _by definition_ is local, there is no
problem for one world using the US notation, another using the UK notation,
another using something completely different (eg. "commisars" or whatever). You
can even split the ranks more, and have a "Customs Branch" ranking system with
various "Customs Officers", or a "Riot Brigade" that uses a more military
ranking system (good ideas for a big force on a Hi Pop Hi Law world). Jeff\'s
original article in 1995 even skipped ranks if the force was small.

The point about planetary police is that they ARE different. With subsector
police, I cheated a little to reduce the number of ranks. You can expand them
again to allow detectives at the subsector level, if you want. After all, It\'s
Your Traveller Universe.

Oh, and the query about "officer" and "enlisted" is a hard one. After all, every
policeman is a "police officer". Therefore, I use the terms "officer" and
"commissioned officer", which at first glance seems a tautology, but remember
that the military has "non-commissioned officers" as well.

Planetary Police                            Subsector Police
Rank Officer                                Rank Officer
E1   Probationer                            E1   Trainee
E2   Constable/Detective Constable          E2   Constable
E3   Senior Constable/Snr Det Constable     E3   Senior Constable
E4   Sergeant/Detective Sergeant            E4   Sergeant
E5   Senior Sergeant/Snr Det Sergeant       E5   Senior Sergeant
E6   Station Sergeant/Station Det Sergeant  E6   Station Sergeant
E7   Area Sergeant/Area Det Sergeant        E7   Area Sergeant

Rank Commissioned Officer                   Rank Commissioned Officer
O1   Deputy Inspector/Deputy Det Inspector  O1   Deputy Inspector
O2   Inspector/Detective Inspector          O2   Inspector
O3   Chief Inspector/Chief Det Inspector    O3   Chief Inspector
O4   Superintendent                         O4   Station Chief
O5   Chief Superintendent                   O5   Area Chief
O6   Deputy Commissioner                    O6   Bureau Chief
O7   Commissioner of Police                 O7   Subsector Chief

BTW, one of my sources was "Law Enforcer Characters", a TML article by none
other than Jeff Zeitlin back in 1995. To be fair, I used it as a reality check
on the skills I was giving out, rather than for the ranks. Also, I don\'t really
know if the UK has a "Station Sergeant" and "Area Sergeant" or whether some
sergeants are just more senior than others (eg. Bob from "The Bill"). However,
they seemed convenient titles to allow me to create the E6 and E7 ranks.

For the record, I think that the "Law in the Imperium" article from Challenge
could be said to be based on SOTE and the d\'Alemberts (note that IRIS hearkens
back here as well!). I agree with a previous poster who said that one MoJ
officer per 100,000 people was too many. This is closer to the SOTE structure,
where the Empire has closer controls over its member worlds than (IMO) the
canonical Imperium has.

Having said that, however, feel free to adopt the article for YTU, since it is
by no means an unreasonable approach. It goes back to your view of your
Imperium, as the Trav Geek Code recognises. The Imperium only has to be slightly
more "hands-on" for an organisation like SOTE (or IRIS  ;-) to exist.
