>So where does the rural sheriff and his deputy fit in ?

Different organization entirely.  Sheriff\'s Departments are
generally at the county level, and often focus on _code_
enforcement rather than _law_ enforcement, and deal in civil
actions.  Thus, the massive ticket-and-tow operations when double
parking gets out of control in an area are usually under the
Sheriff\'s command; so is the service of subpoen? or eviction
notices - even though there will be cops involved with both.
>>>

Depends where you are. In New South Wales , Australia , the whole system is
different.

Ranks:
1. Probationary Constable
2. Constable  / Detective Constable (one ceveron)
2. Senior Comstable / Detective Senior Constable (two ceverons)
3. Segeant / Detective Sergeant (Three ceverons)
4. Station Sergeant (Three ceverons and a crown, similar to Army Senior
Sergeant)
5. Inspector /Detective Inspector
6.Chief Inspector / Detective  Chief Inspector
7. Deputy Comisiorner
8. Comisioner

The NSW police is a state base organisation (State Trooper in US Terms) but
there is no local police force (Local Governments use Rangers, these are low
level enforcements).

The Courts however, has Sherrifs (a bit like the Sheriff of Nottingham in
mentatlity) used to protect the court facilities, as well as enforcing court
orders outside the perview of the Police (generally evictions).

IMHO , in Traveller this is a better system , as it differentiates from military
ranks but is equivelent to military ranks. Other nationalities have different
rank systems, and can be subsituted if desired (The French police ranks could be
fun if I knew what they where).

Darryl
