    'index' => 'ef294',
    'month' => '11',
    'body' => 'On 11/29/99 at 07:40 PM,  "Terry Carlino" <carlino@home.com> said:

>>So where does the rural sheriff and his deputy fit in ?

>The sheriff is an elected position, typically the highest in a county
>(or parish). 

And with budgets to match.  When it comes to power, follow the
money.  In many counties the Sheriff\'s budget dwarfs everyone except
the public school system, and in some it is even higher.

>Small sheriff departments have several deputies who may
>or may not be civil servants. Large sheriff departments, (in Chicago,
>for example) provide court bailiffs, serve court papers, and staff 
>jails. Large departments have deputy ranks  like chief deputy,
>lieutenant deputy, sergeant deputy, etc., sometimes including
>investigators.

I live in a small county, 100,000 people.  Three towns, Jay with
2,000, Milton with 8,000 and Gulf Breeze with 10,000.  The rest of
us live outside any municipality.  All of our law enforcement is
through the Sheriff\'s department.  There is a new 40 deputy
sub-station located a half kilometer from my house.  

Before we got the sub-station this year we were serviced by rolling
patrols working out of the Sheriff\'s headquarters 10 km away where
close to 200 deputy officers were based.  It is costing more, but
now there are 4 sub-stations sited strategically within the 4,500 sq
km of the county.  By spreading the deputies out we are getting
faster response in our outlying areas, and hence better protection.

And outside the big cities this is common all across the US.
Frontline law enforcement from deputies of the county sheriff\'s
departments.  Quick Draw, Boss Hog and Sheriff Andy are all figments
of urban imaginations when they suggest that\'s the way things are
today in non-urban America.

Ob Traveller:  
1.  Have the PC\'s run into jurisdictional problems between two or
more law enforcement agencies.

2.  Confront the players with a different system of law enforcement
than they are used to in their real lives.  If they are urban, put
them in an area where there are *no* city cops, only deputy
sheriffs, or vice versa.

Eris
