>So where does the rural sheriff and his deputy fit in ?

Sheriffs Departments, rural or otherwise, are a parrallel department. THe
sheriff is (Usually) the Chief of the Department.

In most useages, Police Officer means city or municipal law enforcement
officer. Sheriffs are  usually elected to head the county sheriff\'s
department, and sherfiff\'s departments typically replace "Police Officer"
with "Deputy".
State Troopers typically use "Trooper" in the same place.

Let us look at a typical american "big city", Detroit, Michigan. Detroit
really is a collage of small cities (typically under 64mi^2). The detroit
metorplex straddles 3 counties (Wayne, Macomb, and Oakland), with the City
of Detroit (proper) being in Wayne County. You have the Detroit Metro PD,
the Wayne County Sherrif\'s Department, the Macomb County Sheriff\'s
Department, and the Oakland County Sheriff\'s Department. In wayne county
alone, you also have the following other police departments: Trenton PD,
Wyandotte PD, Allen Park PD, Licoln Park PD, Taylor PD, Garden City PD,
Dearborne PD, and Livonia PD (I\'ve seen cars from these in wyandotte; there
was a Police Officer\'s funeral a day after my grandfather\'s funeral), plus
possibly 5 more PD\'s. Each county has a number of townships and
incorporated cities in it, and all of them fall under the Metro PD\'s
jurisdiction, as well. The sheriff\'s are elected by their county, the Metro
PD Chief is appointed, but I don\'t know how. I do know the city manager of
Wyandotte appoints the Wyandotte PD\'s chief. I also know that on a robbery
call, DMPD, WPD, and the WCSD all responded, as did a Trenton PD officer
(The named suspect was from trenton, which was 2 miles down the road.)

In almost all cases, for state crimes, the State Police or State Troopers
can get involved. Also, most state trooper agencies are specifically
charged with highway patrol duties. (California also has a separate highway
patrol, if I understand california correctly).

