this whole issue brings up the game design issue of Stats vs Skills in
resolving actions. Musicians, as a general rule, require a good bit of
manual dexterity, a high level of intellectual capability, a lot of
discipline, plus a number of distinct skills. Reading music is nearly
essential for serious musicians. (No offense here, but most rock and roll
is VERY musically simple.) A knowledge of one\'s instrument is also
essential. Ability to memorize, also useful (essential for solists and
vocalists). Ability to hear and relate to other musicians in the ensemble.
Ability to follow the conductor and read the music.

Skill with an instrument is a rote-learned series of associations of notes
to fingerings for most instrumentalists. On the stringed instruments, there
are several sets of fingerings per note, and are state-dependant upon arm
position (at least if you\'re going to make it). After a few years it
becomes reflexive: see the note, and if hand is in 1st position, use finger
X on string y; if in 4th position, yse finger V on String W.

When performing, most performers have at least partially memorized the
pieces (especially the page turns), and will alternate rapidly between the
music and the conductor. Vocalists typically are required to memorize their
whole program, usually by rote, and sometimes must also memorize dance
steps as well.

Writing music is little more than creating a melody, and plugging  in
whichever set of musical formulae you choose to use. Traditional classical
music is remarkably formulaic. Given the Bass and Soprano lines of a Bach
chorale, the average colege sophomore in a music program SHOULD be giving
you the exact same thing as Bach used. Soliere and even Motzart used the
same formula. Paul McCartney\'s music uses it, too... but not as tightly.

>So what skill level does this correspond to in Trav?
>I\'m imagining Level 6 for T4...
using t4 levels:
To be honest, most "Prodigies" should be about skill 4 (Professional) by
start of career (age 17/18), and gain probably about 1 level per two years
in their primary focus, plus pick up additional foci at the rate of 1 per
term. (The few I\'ve met who followed it on really aren\'t much better
rounded than they were in Junior High School... but they are really
impressive with their specialty).


>Sorry to bring up the whole "realism" question, I\'m
>just trying to associate real skill levels with game
>mechanics ones...

If you want realistic music skill rules, here\'s a patch for ANY edition
(except GT):

The music skill level is a representation of the overall level of musical
expertise of the character. To represent more realistically the wide range
of capabilities possible with similar levels of training, let us define
some sub-skills. Sub-skills do not count towards skill limits in CT/MT, but
the general music training level does.
The Sub-Skills:
	Strings - Viol Family
	Strings - Lute Family
	Strings - Harp Family
	Percussion (tuned)
	Brass
	Woodwinds
	Keyboards
	Singing
	Music Theory
	Conducting
	Interpretation
Each level of General Music Skill gives you two levels of subskills. You
may take any combination. When resolving tasks, use the subskill level,
rather than the general skill level. In general, the first level will be
put into the  interpretation and chosen instument subskills.
General Music at level (CT/MT 2, TNE/T4 3) provides level 0 in all
subskills, simply due to eventual exposure.

A note on the strings subskills: The Viol family includes the Viols, plus
the modern descendants known as the (double or String) Bass, the
(Violin-)chello, the Viola, and the Violin. All viols are typically played
with a bow drawn across the strings. The Lute family includes Guitars,
Mandolins, and Balilaikas, and are generally played by strumming or
plucking. Both the Lute and Viol families have a few strings, whose tone is
changed by pressing the string down against a neck. The Harp family is
generally comprised of instruments with a wide number of strings, and each
playable note is a separate string (although most modern concert harps have
foot pedals which shift a series of strings up in pitch by a small
ammount). All three strings skill serve as level 1 in the other strings
subskills if held at level 2+, level-0 if held at level one.

A few notes on the "Non-performing" skills:
Music Theory is writing music. Generally, each level should include one
style of music whose formulae are known, as well as a general knowledge of
how to write, transpose, arrange, and edit written music.

Interpretation is the ability to read music and to get more than just
mechanical notes from written music. It is generally not used much except
by soloists and conductors, but a basic knowledge is essential to a good
performance. If this subskill is not posessed, any solistic work should be
one level more difficult.

Conducting is the ability to get a group of performers to perform based
upon the conductor\'s interpretation of the music. It also includes knowing
how to arrange  musicians themselves for best effect.

