Just for the hell of it, here\'s a different take on it. 

Originally, "sheriff" was "shire reeve". That is, he was the "reeve"
(an office appointed by the Crown) of a "shire" (fair sized geographic
area, not under the direct control of a noble). 

So, is this "sheriff" a US style elected enforcement "officer" or a
Olde England style appointed by higher nobility enforcement officer? 

Note that in both cases they are responsible for "law enforcement" over
a large area (county/shire). But the US style is responsible to the
*people* (or at least to the local government of the area). But the
*appointed* variety is responsible to a high noble first, with the
locals only being a consideration to the extent that the law and the
noble say they are. 

