    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Kyle adds:
> But one Connery can be proud of is "Outland", set on a
> mining colony on Io where he\'s Sheriff.

No. He\'s a US Marshall. Big difference. Both are law enforcement, but
Sherriffs (US type) are elected and paid for *locally*. The type of US
Marshall Connery plays is supplied by a central government for a town
(or mining camp, back in the old west *and* in Outland) that doesn\'t
have its own police or sherriff. 

> I liked it for
> the dull, industrial feel of it, which I think more
> accurately represents what space travel is likely to
> look like and be like for the people doing it: more
> that than the toothpaste-tube cleanliness of Star Trek
> or Star Wars.

Starwars was famous for the *grunge* on all the privately owned ships,
and places like Mos Eiseley. 

Star Fleet ships look good because these people are professionals, and
they *want* to be there. And in the Academy, they problably got
demerits for untidy rooms. :-)

With civilian ships, you\'ll see a lot less "spic and span", but most of
the time you\'ll see *neat*. Even when things are greasy and grimy. Why?
Because improperly stowed gear onbard a ship can *kill* you. And even
if it\'s "merely" lightweight personal possessions in your cabin, you\'ll
stow them or fasten them down securely so *they* don\'t get damaged.

*Any* experienced seaman is going to take one look at a sloppy ship and
decide that he\'s got better (and less painful or quicker) ways of
committing suicide than shipping with people who leave gear unstowed,
or who don\'t keep the things that *need* to be clean clean.

The same should go for spacemen. Even moreso. On a habitable planet, if
things stink, it\'s a nuisance. In space, if things stink it\'s either
fault life support, or somebody not cleaning up stuff that might
compromise life support later. After all the "scrubbers" are supposed
to be removing trace chemicals, many of which are toxic *long* before
you can smell them. So if you can smell "stinks", even if they are
harmless, it means the filters aren\'t working. And what may be in the
air that you *can\'t* smell?

When you get to things like living quaters in a sealed environment
(like the "camp" in Ooutland) you\'ll find folks a lot more casual. But
either there will be frequent accidents or loss of life from
carelessness, or there will be *enforced* standards for "neat" in areas
where it matters (basicly anyplace where "clutter" or "dirt/filth"
could cause an accident kills/injures folks *other* than the person
responsibly for the "junk" or "dirt"). 

Also, the "old-timers" will be *really* leery of anybody who hasn\'t
learned what rules are *important*. I\'m reminded of Belters in Niven\'s
universe (and a few others). Newbies (immigrants, or kids just getting
old enough to go out on their own) are *required* to complete a "term"
running a one-man prospecting ship before they can work at *anything*
except clerical stuff or very, *very* "non-critical" jobs.

Why? Because until they\'ve proved that they can follow rules and be
*careful* enough to keep *themselves* alive, they aren\'t going to be
allowed into a situation where they can take somebody else with them
when they make a mistake. 

In spite of training, *most* kids/immigrants *don\'t* live thru this
term. The kids haven\'t learned they aren\'t immortal yet. The adults
from habitable planets haven\'t learned that in space *any* mistake is
going to be fatal. They aren\'t "paranoid" enough about safety checks
and the like. 

Spacers from belts or other "artificial environment" worlds are going
to be *real* sticklers for details that matter. And tend to be *real*
suspicious of folks from places where you can walk around on the
surface without artificial aids. At least until they\'ve "proven"
themselves. 

Y\'know, that ought to be a "world classification" like Non-industrial"
or "Agricultural". Say, "habitable", "marginal", "artifical". With the
"habitable" types and the "artifical" types *really* not understanding
each other. The marginals won\'t take things for granted, the way the
habitables do, but they aren\'t as paranoid as the artificals. (after
all, on a marginal world, forgetting (say) your filter mask may
"merely" put you in the hospital. 

> Reminds me of that great scene in "Armageddon" where
> the Russian cosmonaut claims he can fix the American
> equipment, they say, "No, it\'s American components,
> you won\'t know how to use them." He barges in and
> starts hitting the equipment: "American components
> (bash!) Russian components (bash!) all (bash!) made in
> (bash) Taiwan! (bash! machine starts up again)" Sounds
> right to me.

A semi-rational attitude. If you *need* the equipment, it\'s not
working, and you don\'t have "proper" tools or instructions "bashing" it
(not hard enough to break it, but hard enough to jostle loose
connections and stuck valves) *is* a reasonable response. If you *do*
have tools, manuals and parts, you go by the book (unless you\'ve
learned the book is wrong,, or that 90% of the time the problem is a
bit of corrosion on a connector. Then a "bash" may be the "right" fix
again. :-)

