    'topic' => ' Low TL Medicines (was:  Rule of man coin)',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Bringing this back to Traveller:
>
> At least here on Terra, advances in medicines have often been aimed at
> reducing the side-effects of otherwise-effective drugs.  Thus, paregoric
> (which was often prescribed to relieve diarrhea, as opiates tend to
> cause constipation) was replaced by compounds which also relieved
> diarrhea, without the narcotic side-effects of paregoric.  Similarly,
> there has been a trend in antihistamines toward compounds that are less
> likely to cause drowsiness.  Presumably, as a general rule, as TL
> increases, drug side-effects decrease.
>
> The question then become:
>
> To what extent (if any) does the Imperium regulate the interstellar
> transport of medicinal compounds between worlds, if said compounds are
> legal on the world of origin?  If there is no formal Imperial regulation
> of such compounds, does the Imperium at least attempt to help worlds
> maintain their own regulations on importation of medicinal compounds?
>
> In other words, are PCs who purchase laudanum on a TL-4 world subject to
> Imperial sanctions if they sell said laudanum on a TL-13 world that
> strictly regulates opiates?

The impression *I* have always gotten is that the Imperium doesn\'t care
much about local restrictions. You can haul anything that isn\'t under
*Imperial* proscription (say, thionite) from anywhere to anywhere. But
at your destination, if their isn\'t a port (complete with extrality,
which BTW seems to be an idea borrowed from Norton\'s SF) then you are
subject to local laws as soon as you leave the ship. Possibly as soon
as you land. 

If there is a port, then as long as you are inside the extrality line,
you aren\'t subject to local laws. You can sell your cargo to anybody
*inside the port*.

If you cross the extrality line, you are under local law, and could get
arrested for selling the wrong thing to a local. 

Thus, there will be notices listing the more important contraband
posted near the exits with terminals (high TL worlds) or printed lists
(low TL) giving the entire list. Even so, it\'s still possible to run
into a situation where you are the first person to discover that the
locals consider the harmless X you are trying to sell to fall into
prohibited category Y.

Unless things are really bad, being the first person *should* get you a
warning, and the product confiscated. You *may* be abler to petition
for its return if you promise to take it offworld. 

After all, in most cases neither the locals nor the Imperium want
traders to get surprised. But there may be times when it isn\'t that
simple. :-)

The Imperium will *always* want trade to go smoothly. Thus they\'ll
always be in favor of local laws being *clear* about products and
activities that are forbidden, so as to avoid surprise for traders and
visitors. 

Most worlds will agree, since even under "guilty until proven innocent"
type legal systems, it\'s both harder to get a conviction, and *very*
bad publicity if someone can legitimately claim that they had no idea
that the law meant *that*...

Some worlds won\'t like visitors. And they\'ll resent the Imperium. So
there, you\'ve got the local Imperial officials trying to keep an eye
out for legal boobytraps even as the locals try to construct more of
them without being obvious. Just the sort of place a GM likes to make
players visit. 

And, of course, even if the contraband list is posted and clear, there
are people who will smuggle things across the line because of the
profits. The Imperial officials are likely to give reasonable amounts
of help to the locals, unless the locals are some sort of fanatics, or
otherwise annoy the hell out of the officials. 

So on worlds where there are good relations, the exits from the port
may have "average Interstellar" tech sensors scanning for contraband,
even if the local TL is lower. The locals will have either paid for the
installation and maintainence, or they\'ll have made some sort of
concession to the Imperials.

On worlds with strained relations there may be "customs inspectors"
*manually* searching everything going in or out of the port. 

