    'body' => 'From: Walter Smith <SmithW@HARTWICK.EDU>


> Bonus points to Chris for pushing the loaded term level from "biased" to
> "brainwashed", with extra points for adding the "slander" label to
> a fellow TMLer\'s opinion. <weg>

Yes, you used the term biased. On the other hand, you also made the claim
that, "...most of the people who pay serious attention to the Bible believe
that it is accurate (or at least truthful) before they even learn to read,
much less learn how to study history."

In my estimation, such a statement goes beyond mere bias into the realm of
"brainwashing". My apologizes for the mischaracterization if the above
statement is not what you meant, and yes I do find that to be "something of
a slander" on those who have participated in the scholarly study of the
Bible.

How I read your statement was that it is impossible for anyone who studies
the Bible to be incapable of being in anyway impartial.

> Without a personal belief that the Bible is a highly significant
> document, you will not study it rigorously enough to produce any
> insights sufficiently developed to be accepted by respected Bible
> scholars as significant.

What do you mean by that exactly? I\'m not trying to trip you up here, but
your statement can be read in several ways, and there are many levels within
Biblical study: theology, biblical archeology, and the fuzzy areas where
several disciplines merge.

>The majority of people performing these studies
> are of a religious bent, even if they are currently in a doubting or
> skeptical phase.
>
> How about this: the majority of those studying the Bible have a
> spiritual bent, as those without one generally dismiss it out of hand.

With all due respect, I\'m unsure how any student of history, specifically
Western and Middle-Eastern history could dismess the Bible out of hand. Even
those who don\'t follow a faith or creed that is based on the Bible can see
that it is the work with the most influence on Western culture. The Old
Testament alone is central to three of the world\'s major religions. I\'m
betting you said that with a straight face, too. ;)

> With a spiritual bent - either for or against Chrisitianity - the Bible
> has value, either as a basis for a belief system, or as a weapon
> against belief systems (including Christianity).

It also has value on many, many other levels. Which was my original point.
Even in theology, which is perhaps the study of the Bible at its most
"religious" is marked by a great debate concerning interpretation itself.
Still, the statement above is a complete turn around from your original
statement.

>If spiritual matters
> are unimportant, then the Bible is a historical and literary artifact,
> more valuable as a source of indirect historical/social information
> (as the Greek myths provide context to Mediterrenean cultures)
> rather than for it\'s limited direct historical references.

This is the case for many people to whom spiritual matters *are* important
as well. It\'s been that way ever since the early 18th century! Even so, it\'s
not a terribly indirect document. There is no doubt that the Bible was
*written* by people who lived in antiquity, and has over the course of
millenia remained pretty much unchanged. If my memory serves me well, the
fragments and books of the Old Testament known as the Dead Sea Scrolls don\'t
differ significantly from other later versions of the books of the Old
Testament. This is of real importance, as you\'re dealing with a text that
has remained unchanged nearly from the beginning of recorded history.

If that\'s not a direct voice from the past, I don\'t know what is. ;)

Now, on the other hand, the study of the Bible\'s "limited, direct historical
references" is only one small part of the study of the Bible, even though it
is the one which is most popular. Everyone loves books like "The Passover
Plot," and the evidence of the "real" flood discovered in the Middle-East
makes for great news filler...

Ach, this is terribly off topic. ;) If you want to move it to private mail I
surely won\'t object.
