    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Shadow wrote:
>> With civilian ships, you\'ll see a lot less "spic and span", but
>> most of the time you\'ll see *neat*. Even when things are greasy
>> and grimy. Why? Because improperly stowed gear onbard a ship
>> can *kill* you. And even if it\'s "merely" lightweight personal
>> possessions in your cabin, you\'ll stow them or fasten them down
>> securely so *they* don\'t get damaged.
>
> While I liked Outland I preferred the BBC series Star Cops  (only
> ran 9 episodes).
>
>     "In space, anything you forget to  bring  with  you  will
>     kill you.  Anything you *do* remember  but  doesn\'t  work
>     will kill you.  If in doubt assume everything\'s going  to
>     kill you!"
>
> Workers in zero-G had a \'swear box\' and had to put in a $1  every
> time they let something drift away.

That\'s nice idea!

>> Y\'know, that ought to be a "world classification" like
>> Non-industrial" or "Agricultural". Say, "habitable",
>> "marginal", "artifical". With the "habitable" types and the
>> "artifical" types *really* not understanding each other. The
>> marginals won\'t take things for granted, the way the habitables
>> do, but they aren\'t as paranoid as the artificals. (after all,
>> on a marginal world, forgetting (say) your filter mask may
>> "merely" put you in the hospital. 
>
> Hmmm, how about this:
>
>     Mod = local Pop digit + TL digit - 17
>     (more than zero equals 0, less than -8 equals -8)
>
>     Apply  Mod  as  penalty  to  reaction  rolls  of  spacers  to
>     outsiders.  Local Pop digit is *local* pop digit (so if on an
>     orbital base of 500  people  then  local  pop  digit  is  3).
>     Reduce penalty by sum of Zero-G-Environment skill, Vacc  Suit
>     skill, and years of service in Scounts or Navy.
>
> Thus, the higher the TL the more robust the  environment  is  and
> thus the less paranoid spacers are.

Well, remember, part of the paranoia is something that I don\'t think TL
advancements are going to change. Namely, the fact that it\'s *very*
hard to protect against morons whho *think* they know what they are
doing. Such people will cheerfully ignoring warning signs, flashing
danger lights, and even tell interactive voice systems that yes, they
really *do* want to dump the atmosphere from cargo bay two (this while
they are *in* cargo bay two!). 

The problem is that the very same functions that a moron will use to
kill people unintentionally are also functions that may be needed to
*save* lives (or property) in an emergency. And short of the sort of AI
Traveller doesn\'t have, you *can\'t* "limit" the controls enough to
prevent this sort of stupid user error. 

> I\'ve found lots of engineering PCs (and non-engineering PCs  too)
> bash things as a first resort  ...  "Emergency  Repair  Procedure
> number 1" they call it.  Just to keep them on  their  toes,  next
> time they bash  some  misfunctioning  piece  of  equipment:  have
> something drop off!  <evil grin>

Or set off some *embarassing* alarm. Say the PC hits the Nav console
and the ship\'s collision alarm goes off. 

- -- 
Leonard Erickson (aka Shadow)
