    'body' => 'As a Marxist and Democratic Socialist, I often find it amusing to see how 
other people treat Marx as some sort of demigod especially by those who have 
only made a cursory reading of his numerous writings.  For Marx, it must be 
remembered was many things and naturally there will be countless 
interpetations of his work.  But, I must laugh at the attempts that make 
East Europe, Russia or China the prime examples of Marx\'s thought put into 
action.  Marx would be the first victim of the gulag as were many Marxists 
in those above mentioned countries - for an economy which which relied on 
state-control and primacy given over to the military industrial complex and 
controlled by a small narrow elite was certainly not Marx or what has been 
termed Classical Marxists had in mind.  For Marx, he foresaw the emergence 
of a society based upon freely-associated producers (by which he meant the 
workers would have a stake in running industry or the economy) coupled with 
a dramatic redistribution of the world\'s net wealth (which he hoped would 
would lead to abolishing one class which was the most numerous in his time 
and ours - the poor thereby making everyone part of the Rich or the 
bourgeoise - fancy french name for the middle class)and prosperous content 
society which would be able to maximize production toward social ends 
(otherwise allow each individual to maximize her or his potential as a human 
being).
    How does this all relate to Traveller.  Traveller like all other 
cultural artifacts is product of the time in which it was made and out of 
the experiences contained therewithin.  RPGs, including Traveller, were 
created in the aftermath of the American defeat in Vietnam.  Many of the 
creators also served a tour of duty in S.E. Asia so for them a society 
ordered around the military or state service was a natural outgrowth (look 
at how CT had 4/5 of the six "careers" to be in the military and even when 
Citizens came around we had flyers & wet navy etc filling the gaps left my 
the Other - the mysterious outsider akin to the hippie experience for many 
growing up in the 1960s).  Soon Traveller developed an Enemy befitting 
America at that time which were the Zhos or the (Sov)iets.  But, reflecting 
the ever changing world around it Traveller by its flexibility absorbed 
other influences around it.  Trade and Commerce the life-blood of capitalism 
or any other society it seems gained in importance.  Even the "Alternative" 
lifestyle found a niche in the form of the career of the Scouts.  The 
mutations into the other forms of Traveller be it MT, TNE, T4, G:T all 
reflect a fundamental anxiety which is at the heart of American or the 
societies of the West. Which has gripped the Western and now the globe since 
1973 oil crises and the resulting paradigm shift that has occurred as 
Capital went global and asserted it\'s independence from the nation-state, 
along with other things such as the failures 1968 which led to the formation 
of New Social Movements, etc. As it was expressed by Gramsci when he said,
	"The crisis consists precisely in the fact the old is dying and the new 
cannot be born; in this interregnum a great variety of morbid symptoms 
appear."

   What that new is?  That is the subject for contestation.  For some it may 
mean good old fashioned values, others it may mean revitalized neocapitalism 
which seeks to dismantle the old welfare state-form and others something 
fundamentally new which goes by the old fashioned name of Socialism (the 
definition of which may be incorporating some of Marx\'s above stated ideals 
in addition to new challenges).  Without exception if Traveller is to 
survive, it will have to coast along these turbulent waters to remain 
credible to all its fans without choosing one side or another but all the 
time tapping into the ziegest of angst of the time.  Marx\'s much vaulted 
Stage theory of History was not his creation rather he was following the 
example of English economic historians, like Marx when he was writing 
Capital, saw that societies appear to be individual but go through similar 
stages of development which may abstracted from actual history.  Marx never 
meant this to serve as a master blueprint for the development of humanity 
but rather as a guide for human action to change the world by observing that 
things are not the same as they have always being therefore humanity has the 
ability to change its order.  Marx sought these changes as Social 
Revolutions.  He reasoned that the extension of the franchaise would allow 
in sufficiently democratic countries such as Britain or the United States 
that Socialism could be achieved through the ballot box.  As a consquence, 
Marx did not forsee the collapse of all government but the transformation of 
the State into one where popular will could be exercised without the 
repression that dominated 19th century and much of the third world today 
exercised by the State and Capital.  Therefore, what one is essentially 
taliing about is a different kind of State which has yet to be realized.
    Traveller canon aknowledges that workers\' governments have formed but 
all fall to into decay and decandence.  Which perhaps is due to American 
perception of the Soviet and Chinese experience.  Following those examples 
one would have to agree that Workers\' control is doomed but remember Marx 
saw that socialism would have to become a global system much as capitalism 
is today for it to be effective.  What we see in China as we saw in the 
Soviet Union earlier, is a capitalist class emerging from a country which 
remained very much feudal despite the presence of rapid industrialization 
protected by the state.  Much as the English genty began the the enclosure 
movement, thus privatization of state industry is going on now in 
"socialist" countries.
   The vision of the Far Future provided by Traveller is sufficiently 
diverse to accomodate real socialism on one world.  But, to believe that the 
3I is going to evolve into a socialist state is highly unlikely. As we see, 
in the official and variant timelines, reformers are cast aside.  Impeutus 
will have to come from those who pull the strings which are too much tied 
into existing power structures to want to change the status quo - an irony 
the same quandry that we find ourselves in today as we enter the next 
century.  One should always remember in the 3I that democracy is a 
subversive word that even those who suggest it in the end perish.  The 
situation resembles France before the Revolution however, there still is 
great deal of fluidity between the classes.  So the better analogy is 
America today.  In short, Traveller is what you make it but its twists and 
turns reflect very much the reality of the times in which it was created.  
It will be interesting to BITS contribution as the British experience of 
combining a "feudal" or inherited wealth-based aristocratic society with a 
dynamic capitalism is long part of the British experience.
    For those interested in further readings of late 20th century American 
culture from a Marxist perspective.  I would recommend books by Frederick 
Jamerson, Mike Davis, and rather dated Michael Harrington for US readers.  
For British, E.P. Thompson and much of what came out the Cultural Studies 
