    'id' => undef,
    'ts-index' => '1999-11-30.ef368',
    'body' => '>The sheriff is an elected position, typically the highest in a county (or
>parish). Small sheriff departments have several deputies who may or may not
>be civil servants. Large sheriff departments, (in Chicago, for example)
>provide court bailiffs, serve court papers, and staff  jails. Large
>departments have deputy ranks  like chief deputy, lieutenant deputy,
>sergeant deputy, etc., sometimes including investigators.
    The organization of the sheriff\'s department is almost always a choice
made by the elected sheriff and the local county commisioners.  In areas
such as New York, Chicago, and L.A., they tend to be police support
organizations as mentioned elsewhere in this thread.  In largely rural
areas, the sheriff\'s department will be the main police force in the
county and the constables, marshalls, and police of the towns will
usually defer to them.  It\'s still not an uncommon practice for a sheriff to
deputize a town marshall or constable or for a small community to
ask the county sheriff to station a deputy semi-permanently in the
town, thereby directly and formally subordinating local law enforcement
to the county.  Many large countys with full civil service-style sheriff\'s
departments will also include detectives, investigators, and specialist
forensic experts who are not in any way considered deputies, although
they are subordinate to the elected sheriff (or sometimes the county
coroner).


>From: david.d.jaques-watson@centrelink.gov.au
>This is actually based on the UK model portrayed in "The Bill". For those
who
>want a US-based version, use Jeff\'s ranks. For example, there is no
"Lieutenant"
>or "Captain" in the UK system, and the US uses "Chief of Police" rather
than
>"Commissioner of Police", since there is no monarch to receive a commission
>from.
    Actually, U.S. citys sometimes have a Police Comissioner as well,
although
it is a completely different concept from the Police Chief.  A Chief is
usually
a political appointment (although, rarely, it may be a civil service
position)
but is usually, if not almost always, a career police officer who has worked
his way up the system to Captain\'s rank or above.  He handles implementation
of policy and standards and is analagous to a U.S. military Chief of Staff.
A Commissioner, either individually or as a member of a Police
Commission, is always a political appointment and almost never from
within the department.  Instead he is a "civilian" charged with either
making
policy decisions or conducting "outside" investigations of the police
department.  He is more analagous to the U.S. Secretary of Defence, the
"civilian" boss of a para-military organization.  Commisioners will usually
only be found in the largest of cities, however.
                                            Lyle
