>
>There\'s something *seriously* wrong here. Light sails, without laser
>boosts or the like *can\'t* do even *1* g. 1/10th or even 1/100th g is
>more like light sail performance. They are *not* high accel!

>> 1 light sail (145.1 tonnes thrust)      0.5     22.7    25.0    -       -
>
>And just how *big* is this sail? And what does *it* mass? I bet you
>forgot to add the mass of the sail to the mass of the ship before
>calculating acceleration.

Then fire off a letter to SJG and get GURPS space errataed, because that\'s
where I pulled the numbers from. Just a simple thrust/mass=acceleration
calculation.

I can see no reason why a light sail couldn\'t be a high-acceleration
vessel, assuming that the sail was big enough. GS/3 doesn\'t give sizes, but
I suppose you could do a backwards calculation from the thrust and average
solar energy in earth orbit.

Looking at page 21 of "Starsailing" (by Freidman), I see that F=2P/c
(force, power, speed of light). Given that F=ma, then we can derive a=2P/mc
(acceleration, power, mass, speed of light)

The mass of the yacht includes the mass of the sail (check the numbers).
Dividing tons thrust by tons mass should give me the acceleration in
gravities, right?  (I usually work in Newtons and kilograms, not American
units, so may well have made a mistake here.)

In any case, we can calculate teh area of the sail because we know the
force. 145.1 tonnes thrust is 145100 kg times 10 m/s/s (approx), thus
1451000 N. Rearranging the first equation about to get P = Fc/2, I get P =
1,451,000 x 300,000,000 / 2 = 2.2 x 10e14. The Square root of that is about
10e7, so the sail is a square 10000km along a side.

According to GS/3, the sail is 240 square miles per space. I see that I
forgot to multiply the thrust by 0.5 (for the half space) but GS/3 lists
the thrust as 160 tons/space.

I think we\'ve found an errata in GS/3.
