    'body' => '<Lurk mode off>

This is something I have concitered at times as well. If you look even at
earth\'s history and at the "technological" diversity that some isolated
cultures derive, you do come up with "commom denominators" when it comes to
tasks.

As for any species approach to space travel, there are common denominators
to conciter:

Power Plants: Although the technique may be different, in a traveller
universe, there is one fuel above all else that will eventually get looked
at - Hydrogen - and thus one type of power plant will get developed -
Fusion. Pre fusion technology may end up being very different between any
two species, so this could get fairly diverse. ("Hey Pete, what do we do
with all these cow droppings?" -- "Toss them in the converter, we have to
get to orbit somehow!")

Control System: Our human concept of silicon/optic crystal computational
systems may or may not be developed by an alien species. Here is where the
most diversity would be found. Organic neural networks could be developed
easier by one species than we could, and some may actually develop life
forms to act as computer cores. In traveller terms, however, it\'s the
rating that counts, not the material. IYTU, a computer of a given number
may or may not need be silicon based.

Thrust: Here is where the most thinking can come to play. The laws of
physics will be your guide. It\'s logical that rockets of some kind, solar
sails, and subatomic thruster units are technologies that any space-faring
civilization must develop along with (in the traveller universe) jump
drives. It is the construction techniques that will be the real diversity.
I can imagine some very beautiful architecture going into solar sail
construction.

Hulls: It\'s got to be strong, it\'s got to be airtight, and it has to resist
outside radiation. Thus the material used must be able to form hulls that
fit the above rules. If you can get a type of wood to do that, then you
have a race that can use wooden hulls. Translate it into traveller
compatable hull ratings for YTU and have fun with your players reaction to it.

As far as weapons, you may run into races that have different ideas on
weapons. Some may never arm ships, some may arm ships with weapons no one
has seen before. Here is where you, as a GM, have freedom. If it fits you
traveller universe, open fire. Just make sure it\'s something you would want
your players to get their hands on. If you know one of your players would
use this weapon to get his backside seated on the Iridium throne, don\'t use
it (unless you want him to be Emperor or get him killed trying).

Just my thoughts :)

