    'body' => '"Bob Sanders" <bsanders@amghome.com> wrote:
>
> Reading the ship designs using solar sails, and looking at FF&S, Gurps, etc.
> I have some questions that has always bothered me about Traveller, and would
> like to get some ideas from the crowd.  Why is it that every race in the
> Traveller universe uses the same technology?  Jump drives I can understand,

Really? So, why is that?

If you really understood, you\'d be running around in circles, gouging 
your eyes out and screaming...

> put power plants, maneuver drives, hulls, computers, weapons, etc, could and
> should be different.  

Not if everyone copied them off the same basic prototype.

> And if they are different (thus adding much to the
> alien flavor to the game) what would each race be likely to use?
> Imps: basic stuff

Based on models found in Sol\'s asteroid belt, on Vland and on
Zhodane.

> Droyn: sails, solar collectors, geneered brains?

Back to this...

> Aslan: fusion drives?

Actually, they all look like Solomani ships - that\'s where they
copied the jump drive from, they probably copied the maneuver
drive (which the Terrans copied from the Vilani) and so on.

> Hivers: Grown ships (like the pentapods (sp) from T2300)

Hm, early Hiver ships probably looked semi-different (although
as another poster pointed out, their laws of physics are the
same as ours and there are a limited number of "optimal"
designs for ship hulls, etc).

Once the Hivers "invented" regular jump drive and stopped using
the "inferior" version that they really invented, they probably
started using standard thrusters, power plants, etc.

> Others?

All the same too. The Vilani discouraged regionalism during
their rule(s), thus forcing out local & regional technologies
in favour of "standard Vilani" designs.
 
Have I posted this lately? Stop me if you\'ve heard this one before...

Grandfather invented the jump drive, the gravitic maneuver/thruster
drive and probably perfected the catalyzed fusion plant before 
moving on the antimatter power generation and dimensional gates.

In the process of seeding humaniti far and wide and visiting the
homeworlds of the various non-human "major" races, he (or his
children) left behind samples in the from of semi-broken or abandoned
ships. Most of the "major" races made a decent push into their
near space (the Vilani and Hivers being the most successful, followed
by the K\'kree, then down to the real copycats, like the Solomani,
Zhodani, Aslan and Vargr) during which time they lucked upon a
derelict Ancient ship which they proceeded to copy with impunity.
(without impunity?)

The Vilani, Hivers and K\'ree all get extra credit though. The Vilani
colonized several worlds via sub-light generation ships before 
discovering jump. The Hivers actually invented the darn thing themselves,
perhaps proving them the smartest race in the galaxy, but droped their
own version, which was inferior to the real thing. The K\'kree
seem to have discovered gravitics independently in their quest to wipe
out the race inhabiting their nearby moon or planet (I forget which
it was). 

The only race to ever have been "caught in the act" are the Genoee,
who were originally considered a "major" human race during the early
Vilani period, until the Vilani also discovered the ship the Genoee
had copied. Having copied jump drive instead of "inventing" it reduced
the Genoee to a mere "minor" race in the Vilani taxonomy (and of course,
at the time, the Vilani were the only "major" race).

Whether the discovery of the Ancient derelict ships was covered up
on purpose by the "race at large" or whether the "inventors" of
the jump drive simply wanted all the fame and fortune is unclear
and probably unprovable one way or another.

Ethan
