    'body' => 'With the discussion of Dead-Fall Ordnance going on on the 
GT:Navy playtest group, I got to thinking about Babylon 5 and the 
weapons that the Shadows (or was it the Vorlons ...) used to kill 
planets.  They simply dropped large chunks of streamlined metal 
through the atmosphere and the concussion was enough to 
penetrate the crust and break the planet up from inside.

Well, here is a 6 cf, Radically Streamlined, Highly Armored Dead-
Fall missile.  It has limited manuevering capability, just enough to 
slow it down for reentry so aerobraking is not necessary.  You just 
drop it from orbit and when it hits, it does massive amounts of 
damage (5dx2000 (2) ... more than a 0.0001 kiloton MicroNuke and 
almost as much as a 0.001 kiloton).

I will try to list all locations where I found appropriate rules.

Body              : 6 cf, empty space
Structure Profile : TL7 Extra Heavy Frame, Very Cheap Materials, 
Robotic (I used low TL stuff for its weight)
Armor Profile     : TL6 DR 1200 Cheap Metal (I used low TL stuff for 
its weight)
Total Cost        : MCr0.064
Size Mod          : 0

Total Weight is 17402 lbs.  This means for it has the equivalent of 
17402 lbs of thrust from gravity. VE2/157, Falling.
Terminal Velocity in conjunction with the Reactionless Thruster 
(which is the top speed) is 15780 mph. VE2/157, Falling

According to VE2/164, Space-to-Ground Capability, a vehicle must 
decelerate by (orbital velocity - top air speed) / 1500 minutes before 
it can enter the atmosphere.  Earth\'s is 17800 so this missile must 
decelerate for 1.3 minutes if it were aerobraking.  As it is not (it shall 
use its Reactionless thruster), we don\'t have to worry about that.

According to VE2/164, Space-to-Ground Capability, the vehicle is 
approximately 15,000 miles up when it enters the atmosphere.

According to VE2/157, Falling, a vehicles gains 20 mph per second 
until terminal velocity is reached.  Well, we are already at terminal 
velocity so we don\'t have to worry about that, either.

We now have a 8.7 sTon hunk of metal screaming throught the 
atmosphere at Mach 21 (more in the upper reaches of the 
atmosphere).

According to VE2/159, Hitting Buildings and Immovable Obstacles 
(I assume the planet should suffice for this definition), we use the 
TBone Collision rule from VE2/158 which directs us to the top of 
the page.  Effectively : (120 (the HPs) x 15780) / 200 Dice of 
Damage or 9468d.  And if we put a special point on it, 9468d (2).  
Lets round to 10,000 and we have 5dx2000(2) points of damage.  
That\'s 70,000 average points of damage.  A standard missile only 
does 16,800 average points of damage (assuming the armor 
divisor of 10).

Of course, this missile is a lot heavier and a twice as expensive as 
the standard, but considering you don\'t have to worry about 
guidance or targeting, just drop and forget, you could lay thousands 
of these in an upper atmosphere and wreak all kinds of havoc.  And 
most important of all, it works with the standard missile launchers!

