>Chris said:
>>>"Commissioner of Police", since there is no monarch to receive a commission
>>>from.

>>Anyhow, we *do* have Commissioners here in America. In Gotham City there\'s
>>Commissioner Gordon (he should be hitting retirement any day now).

>Doh! I should be shot for forgetting him! I was just going off Jeff\'s comments,
>and not actually *thinking*.

>Wasn\'t "The Commish" set in the suburbs? Different jurisdiction from the city
>beat? Jeff, help!?!

Don\'t know about the setting for the show, but in the NYC Metro
Area, each municipality has its own PD, separate from NYC proper.
In Detroit, there seems to be a slightly different arrangement,
based on my understanding of the post that described that area,
and I suspect that Los Angeles is Yet Another Model.

In addition, don\'t overlook the fact that there may be
_overlapping_ jurisdictions with multiple departments, and not
just city-contained-in-state-type of overlap - going back to NYC,
we have the following:

New York City Police Department: Jurisdiction within the legally
defined boundaries of the incorporated City of New York

New York State Parks Police: Jurisdiction within all State Parks,
including those within NYC.

MTA Railroad Police: Jurisdiction on the property of the
railroads operated by the Metropolitan Transportation Authority
(of NY State) - Metro-North Commuter Railroad and Long Island
Railroad.

New York City Sanitation Police: Jurisdiction over waste-disposal
violations within the legally defined boundaries of the
incorporated City of New York.

New York City Environmental Police: Jurisdiction over New York
City watershed and water supply protection.  This includes over
the reservoirs upstate that serve the City.

Up until a couple of years ago, there was also:

New York City Housing Police Department: Jurisdiction within
housing projects owned or operated by the City of New York.

New York City Transit Police Department: Jurisdiction within the
New York City public transportation system (busses, subways, and
Staten Island Rapid Transit).

Both of the latter agencies were merged into the NYCPD a couple
of years ago.
