    'body' => '>>Here is a \'corrected\' version of the Goryo. Whether this is possible
>>without a larger sail than specified in GS/3 is debatable. This fits the
>>rules, but whether the rules fit reality...
>
>A 1-G solar-sail powered craft that is only about 33% (by mass) sail?
>Not even remotely plausible with any concievable technology; the formulae
>(or your interpretation of them) must be messed up. Could you post the
>exact formula from GS/3?

First off, my earlier post with equations is wrong. Never to math on an
empty stomach, after an 18-hour day. :-/

The problem is with GS3/e, I think.

A light sail module takes up one space. At GTL8 it has an area of 15 sq
miles, at GTL9+ an area of 240 sq miles.  It provides 10 tons of thrust at
GTL8, 160 tons of thrust at GTL9+.  Mass is 50 tons at all tech levels.

Another try at the equations:

Force = 2 x Power / lightspeed		NOTE: assumes a perfect reflector

The solar power constant for Earth (the baseline GS3/e uses) is 1400 Watts
per square metre. Assuming a square mile (1600 m x 1600 m) the equation
becomes:

Force = 2 x 1600 x 1600 x 1400 / 300,000,000

This will be in Newtons per square mile.

(Please check the next bit for boneheaded math error, because I hate
conversions and aren\'t that good at them.)

To convert Newtons to tonnes-force, I used F=ma where m=1000kg and
a=9.81m/s/s, to get:

1 tonne-force = 981 N

Thus:

Force = (2 x 1600 x 1600 x 1400) / (300,000,000 x 981)

Finally, there are 0.907 tonnes in a ton, therefore I get:

Force = (2 x 1600 x 1600 x 1400) / (300,000,000 x 981 x 0.907)	NOTE: in
tons/sq mile

Crunching the numbers (I kept them whole to avoid dumb transcription
errors), this is:

Force = .02685347213 tons/square mile.

Thus, for the 15 square mile sail I get 0.4 tons thrust, while for the 240
square mile sail I get 6.4 tons.

Have I made any boneheaded mistakes? Please let me know, so I ccan update
GT Shipyard to create realistic lightsails.
