    'body' => 'From: Ian Ferguson <ian@vax2.concordia.ca>


> Just my Cr 0.02: There are differences in power generating
> plants around Terra, but most of these are either minor
> variations on the same technology, or based on resources
> that vary considerably in availability.

Well, yes and no. The same idea may be at work with nuclear plants and coal
plants, the two are very different animals.

>It could also be
> argued that TL differences contribute.  Nevertheless, how
> many different kinds of cars are there?  Sure, they may
> look different (actually, they mostly all look the same to
> me), and a mechanic might take a while figuring out the
> details of some foreign cars, but almost all of them use
> metal frames, rubber tires, and internal combustion
> engines.  That despite the wide range in environments in
> which these vehicles must operate.

I know you said "almost all", but if you head up north where there\'s a good
deal of snow and you\'ll find lots of vehicles which use a combination of
skies and treads, not rubber tires. These vehicles fill the same role as
cars, but they\'re not cars.

To go a step further than that even, Buckminster Fuller designed the
Dymaxion (sp?), a three-wheeled car that was quantifiably better than most
cars of the time, but an unfortunate accident caused funding to dry up.
While the Dymaxion was not radical in the sense that the difference between,
say, using solar power on a starship and using fusion power would be, it\'s
still a design which is different enough to be notable.

To stick with automobiles as an example, even with very similar technology,
cars themselves can come in a variety of different shapes and sizes.
Sometimes, as with the popularity of compact and sub-compact cars, the
change is a result of *function*, while at other times the change is purely
a result of aesthetics. Take a look at the rise in popularity of the SUV
among America\'s "soccer moms".

To further complicate issues, you\'ve got things like motorcycles on the
roads as well, which look and feel very different from automobiles. If
everybody in America started to drive motorcycles, for whatever reason, the
country would look and feel quite different.

So, even using the same core technology, you can have any number of
permutations which, in most cases, are functionally different in a
quantifiable way.

These are above and beyond *mere* differences in tech levels.

One thing that\'s interesting, which nobody has mentioned yet, which is not
surprising given the rational and optimization-happy nature of this list, is
that something which may be functionally and quantifiably better may be, for
whatever reason, unpopular, or the idea might not catch on. Look at the
Betamax / VHS brawl, as an example, or look at the story of the Tucker car,
or even the military vehicle that Tucker and his team designed for the U. S.
Army. Laserdiscs are another good example. Let\'s see... what else? Ah! Fax
machines owe their popularity in the 80s and 90s not to their being "better"
than other forms of technology, an email system has many advantages over the
fax machine, but to the fact that Japanese executives conduct their business
in a specific fashion, and the Japanese both make and consume lots of
electronics.

So, even on a single planet it\'s quite possible to have many different
approaches to a problem. People\'s priorities can also be very different.
While many on this list may lean toward optimization, most people *don\'t*.
Tradition and industrial inertia are very powerful forces, even for those of
us who aren\'t Vilani.

In some cases, even very brilliant people can\'t think far enough "outside
the box" to see that there may be a different way of doing something. The
rise in popularity of "alternative medicines" in the West is a good example.
Acupuncture, which just came up on the list in another discussion, is quite
different from other methods of dealing with certain medical problems.
Similarly, the difference between the therapy dominated field of psychology
and the empirical approach of psychiatry are really very different.

I could go on and on, but I think that I\'ve made my point. ;)
