> > Most people may not lean towards optimization, but those who design and
> > build things *do*. The rest of the world has to live with what we build.
> > <sound of laughter>
> 
> That is when the engineers can get their units right. ;)
> 
> Then again, anyone who thinks that engineers build solely with optimization
> in mind need only look at the American automobile industry during the 70s,
> or any one of a thousand different examples.

Under the paradigm of the times (before the Arab oil embargo of 1973),
the American auto industry _was_ optimized.  In other words, American
auto manufacturers gave their target market (the American public)
exactly what it wanted:  big, fast cars, that would last until the next
major style change (3-6 years).

Once the paradigm shifted (gasoline costs and availability became
important concerns), the American auto industry initially quickly
shifted to small, [relatively] fuel-efficient cars, that would last
until the next major style change (3-6 years).  It took a few more years
for the industry to shift completely to the new paradigm (reasonably
fuel-efficient vehicles, built to last at least 6 years), but the
American auto industry soon adjusted to the current paradigm.

Thus, within ten years of a major change in conditions, the American
auto industry was able to make a radical shift in focus, and therefore
once again became an optimized industry.  That seems pretty agile to me.

ObTrav:  The transition from one TL to the next will probably seem
disjointed at the time.  A couple of centuries later, OTOH, the
transition will appear to have been much smoother.

- -- 
