    'index' => 'ef505',
    'body' => '>Is it possible for list-members from other countries to give a basic run
>down of their police agencies for people to use in their TU\'s ?

Wow. Metro Detroit with a zillion different police departments... 

Anyway, up here north of the border, it\'s much simpler. In Edmonton, we 
have the city police department and the RCMP (Royal Canadian Mounted 
Police). There is an Alberta Highway Patrol, but that\'s merely a division 
of the RCMP in Alberta.

The RCMP has federal, national jurisdiction. (In Canada, criminal law is
a federal matter, unlike the USA where it\'s at the state level.) However,
in areas that have their own local police departments (generally, 
communities legally incorporated as a City), the Mounties will generally
defer responsibility for law enforcement to the local PD. Towns, villages,
and the spaces in between and outside the communities, the RCMP handles
local law enforcement.

The exception: two provinces, Ontario and Quebec, have their own provincial
police forces (the OPP and QPP, respectively); in these areas, the OPP / QPP
handle the law enforcement outside cities that have their own local PDs,
leaving the RCMP to handle anything of a multi-jurisdictional nature, like
the FBI in the USA.

As far as I can tell, the different departments do co-operate very nicely.
If for example I was wanted for a crime committed in Ontario, the Edmonton
PD could arrest me, then hand me off to the RCMP, who in turn would turn 
me over to the OPP (or the city police if the crime was in a particular
city)... we don\'t seem to get the jursidictional turf wars that I keep
seeing on American police televison dramas... 

- -- g


