    'index' => 'ef527',
    'month' => '12',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> From: "Luther Martin" <tml@ksarul.com> who wrote:
>> One fundamental reason that everyone uses the same technology is that the
>> laws of physics are the same for all players.
>>
>> Engineering is an exercise in constrained optimization, with the
>> constraints being physics, economics, etc, so the engineering solutions to
>> problems will be similar, given that the constraints are similar. It seems
> that
>> economics does not vary significantly across the Traveller universe, so
>> with the same laws of physics we should not be too surprised to find
> similar
>> (note that I said *similar* but not *identical*) technology.
>
> I agree, but we also know that many roads can get you to the same
> destination.  ForEx. look at the many different types of power generation
> plants in the world.  Gas, coal, nuke, solar, wind, etc... they are all
> optimized (the best they can be at existing technology) for their function.
> However they all still provide power.  That doesn\'t answer my question of
> how the different races all developed the same solution to the engineering
> problem produced by space travel.

Sure it does. Almost all those power plants you listed work *exactly*
the same way. They convert rotary motion into electricity by spinning
coils in a magnetic field (or spinning magnets inside coils, same
difference). What\'s different is where they *get* the rotary motion. 

Solar is the one exception, and it\'s *damned* expensive. It directly
converts light to electricity. 

Everything else uses moving fluid to turn blades. Wind generators use
giant propellors. Hydroelectric uses turbines driven by water flowing
downhill. Modern gas fired (and a few oil fired?) plants use gas
turbines, basicly a jet engine with the shaft coupled to the generator.
The rest use various forms of heat to generate steam, which drives a
steam turbine. 

Fusion (when and if it arrives) will likely be used to generate steam
as well. But there are a couple types of fusion that *may* be able to
produce electricity more or less directly. Those will have to be a
*lot* more expensive to not drive the others out of business. That\'s
because they\'ll both be more *efficient* (ie more of the energy
produced in the reactor will wind up as *useful* power), and because
they\'ll be *far* less complicated. 

 
- -- 
