    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> <Lurk mode off>
>
> This is something I have concitered at times as well. If you look even at
> earth\'s history and at the "technological" diversity that some isolated
> cultures derive, you do come up with "commom denominators" when it comes to
> tasks.

The "spear thrower" (aka atl-atl, aka woomera) has been invented at
least three seperate times. Bagpipes have been invented *four* times.
Ditto for a lot of other things. 

> Power Plants: Although the technique may be different, in a traveller
> universe, there is one fuel above all else that will eventually get looked
> at - Hydrogen - and thus one type of power plant will get developed -
> Fusion. Pre fusion technology may end up being very different between any
> two species, so this could get fairly diverse. ("Hey Pete, what do we do
> with all these cow droppings?" -- "Toss them in the converter, we have to
> get to orbit somehow!")

At lower TLs, nuclear power *is* an option for power plants on board
ships.

> Hulls: It\'s got to be strong, it\'s got to be airtight, and it has to resist
> outside radiation. Thus the material used must be able to form hulls that
> fit the above rules. If you can get a type of wood to do that, then you
> have a race that can use wooden hulls. Translate it into traveller
> compatable hull ratings for YTU and have fun with your players reaction to 
> it.

Well, as an example, if there was a race that was affected by *heavy*
radiation doses about as much as were are by excessive heat, they\'d not
need much radiation shielding on the ship, and, likewise, they might
not *bother* with fusion power. After all, since they\'d not need all
that *heavy* shielding, for them a fission reactor might be preferred
because it\'s *compact*. 

Mind you, they don\'t get a lot of passengers from other races. :-) 

Another possibility would be aliens that are far more sensitive to
jumpspace than humans. They know about J-space, they just can\'t *use*
it. Giving them a different FTL drive might be a problem as far as game
balance goes. Giving them a manuever drive that lets them get to
relativistic speeds is even worse. But if they live long enough, they
can just use normal manuever drives to travel between stars. So what if
the trip takes 100 years. If you live 5000 years, that\'s merely
inconvenient. 

But just because aliens have thrusters, jumpdrive, lasers, etc
*doesn\'t* mean that the "technologies" are the same. So far we know of
at least 5 ways to build computers. Mechanical (Babbage engines),
thermionic (tubes), semiconductors (transistors/ICs), fluidics and
optical (still being perfected). And that\'s for *digital* computers.

Consider aliens who prefer to use *analog* computers. Analog computers
of all the above types are (or should be) available. And they work
*very* differently.

A digital computer crunches away and returns an answer, to however many
places. The answers are "exact" within the precision limits. But they
can also be *very* wrong if you are "outside the range" of the
algorithm or the program has a bug.

Analog computers return answers *immediately*. That is, entering the
imput values causes the output to assume the value of the answer. But
the answer is "fuzzy". That is, the value of the answer depends on how
closely you can read the scaler that the pointer moves along. 

A slide rule is an analog computer. So are the gunnery computers on the
New Jersey!

Electronic analog computers are mostly based on op amps, not gates. 

Analog computers do require "programming, but it\'s a lot different from
digital computers.

Aliens using analog computers might actually have *better* "gunnery"
than the players with their fancy digital computers. But their
"predict" function might be fairly lousy. Or maybe not. 

But both sides would drive themselves nuts trying to get anything
useful to *their* setup from examining the other guy\'s setup. :-)

Now consider construction techniques. We bolt things together when we
may want to take them apart later. What might aliens use? What might be
"just as good" as screws, nuts and bolts, but *different*? 

One possibility I can wrap my head around is some sort of glues. But
that doesn\'t mean there aren\'t others. One I just remembered from some
SF story  is fasteners based on magnostriction. Basicly the "bolt" is a
simple rod inserted into the holes in the parts to be joined. When you
remove the tool that you used to insert it, the rod *expands* enough to
be about as immovable as a nut and bolt. Why, because it\'s an alloy
sensitive to magnetic fields, and the tool was magnetized. Though there
are better ways to use this sort of metal to fasten things. 

Picture the PC\'s poor engineer trying to figure out how to open up
pieces of a equipment on the alien ship the players are trying to
salvage. :-)

Same *function*, different methods.

