>
> Okay. Sorry \'bout the rant there.

Also, keep in mind that Jason was talking about the New
Testement.  As to the *accuracy* of the Bible as an
historical document, the New Testement covers very little
ground (historically speaking).  Only the first 5 books
have much to do with history.  Although, there are a few
nuggets here and there amonst the remainder that point
to the then current events.

The last I heard, with the exception of Theophilos (to
whom Luke wrote his account of the gospel and what is
now referred to as the Acts of the Apostles) every
notable name (political figures, etc.) mentioned in the
New Testement has been found in other historical
documents.

I doubt that there will ever be an historical Theophilos
found.  While the use of terminology like "most excellent"
or "O" (a term used in formal address) would seem to
indicate that Theophilos was a dignatary of some sort or
other.  However; there is another interpretation that I think
to be more likely.

I believe that Theophilos was not a specific person, but
rather a group of people.  In most societies, names have
everyday meanings.  Some English examples would
include names like June, Skip, Mason, Alley and
Hammer, just to name a few.  In Greek, Theophilos
means "Friend of God" or "Lover of God."  So for Luke
to write to "most excellent Theophilos" or "O Theophilos"
would be like my writing a letter in this forum that started
out something like "Dear Traveller," or if I was attempting
to indicate my respect for the members of this forum, I
might make the greeting, "Most Excellent Traveller:".

You would understand that it was written to you.  If you
thought about it, you would also know that I was writing to
all the other travellers on this list.  That\'s why I believe
that Luke was writing to me (and other lovers of God),
and not to some historical figure.

There have been several items that seemed at first blush
to contradict the New Testement (historically speaking);
however, further examination of the historical documents
have vendicated the authenticity of the New Testement
(as a historical document).  Again, I am only speaking of
the New Testement.

When we come to the Old Testement, its authenticity as
a historical document is also well documented.  Parts of
it are quite ancient.  As to its historicity (value as history),
most archiologists that study in areas covered in it use it
as a first in text.  Over and over, the historical accuracy
of the Bible has been vindicated by those digs.
- --
Jason
