    'body' => '>In a recent discussion the subject of Bribery came up. I don\'t use it as a
>skill
>in MTU. How difficult is it to bribe someone anyway?!?  Is it like electronics
>or medical, or even gun combat? How much training or experience is actually
>involved to advance to a higher level. I accept it as a task, but not as a
>separate skill!  I assume that anyone with Streetwise would be successful at
>bribery. Any opinions out there?

The distinction is that bribery, typically, isn\'t the streetpunk paying off
a cop. It\'s more often the punk\'s supplier offering the cops stuff in ways
that are
A) Not easily traced/tracked
B) discreet
c) not likely to be connected directly with the actions desired.

I\'ve done a little bribery myself... of Maitre\'d\'s at posh restaurants.
There are distinct skills for doing this. Like placing your hand on the
podium, with just a corner of the bill showing, watching to see if he
notices, asking if there is a table available, and seeing if he\'s looking
in the book or your hand, and then leaving the bill so that only he sees
it. Not quite sleight of hand, but not far from it, plus the nuances of
seeing whether he smiles or not at seing the bill. It\'s in the details of
doing it. The streetwise may tell you which cop will take a bribe, but no
cop is going to take an obvious bribe on a righteous bust unless severly
compromised already. An obvious approach to bribery often gets rebuffed.
Also, it\'s like knowing that Claude, the Maitre\'d at the crows nest for
many years, knows you know how to behave, and that the tip is for
overlooking your underage status and sending the wine-steward over... he
knew me, and knew my folks wouldn\'t raise a stink for dinner at a 4-star
restaurant to be eaten with a light wine. And, that for a C-not, he\'ll let
you in without reservations. And knowing that you mustn\'t let the other
staff see, otherwise he only gets 10% of it. Likewise, Michelle, from the
Corsair, will seat you for $50, but will put you with the waiters in
training, won\'t even think of sending you a wine steward for less than $500
(He\'s been popped on serving to minors before), and that you must pass him
the bribe to his palm, rather than letting him close the book on it, and do
so as you thank him for the seat. Then again, there are 3 four-star
restaurants in town... and Marx Brothers, the last of them, had a much
higher standard, even if they had a FAR less restrictive dress code... The
one time I offered the bribe to get a seat, I was offered a "Tour of the
staff lounge", whereupon I was threatened with a police call in exchange
for my $100 bill. I later heard rumors that that Maitre\'d was an ex-cop...

Likewise, birbery of government clerks is a matter of knowing how to offer
them what they want without costing them their job.

In all cases, it requires a set of skills at reading both their
receptiveness, as well as knowing how to deliver without compromising the
safety or job of the bribee. Streetwise will tell you who\'s corrupt...
bribery tells you how to get them on YOUR payroll. And how to keep them
where you want them while paying them.

In societies where graft is common, yeah, substitute either carousing or
streetwise... it\'s just part of normal life. But where it\'s prohibited (or
at least severely frowned upon) it requires a certain set of skills to pull
off. Which, unless you have more interpersonal skill IYTU than I have IMTU,
seem to best be summed up under bribery.

William F. Hostman  |  "Smith & Wesson: THe original Point and Click
interface!"
