    'body' => '>>Is it possible for list-members from other countries to give a basic run
>>down of their police agencies for people to use in their TU\'s ?
>
>Wow. Metro Detroit with a zillion different police departments...

The Police Officer\'s Funeral was attended by representatives of 46
different officers, according to the press release to the local news.
Likewise, some other areas have similar levels of overlap, all with
jurisdiction for all crimes.

I was lucky enough to be able to read a few of the cars, and then asked a
few locals about it. And saw a response near the house where I was staying.
(Anyone in the detroit metro area, it was on 9th street in wyandotte).

While LA is often claimed to be 100 villages in search of a City, Detroit
really is 20+ cities who just happen to fill their turf right to the
borders, with a muni gov\'t thrown on top to FORCE cooperation.

Likewise, Portland, Oregon, really is six cities under a municipal
government. (And crossing at least two counties). I don\'t recall seing
local police there (Portland Metro, plus two sherrifs departments, those
I\'ve seen). Detroit is an extreme of the US system.

The city where I live (and grew up) is much the opposite. Alaska has no
counties, only Burroughs and Municipalities. In Alaska, a Municipality is
when a City government merges with a Burrough government. Burroughs are
physically HUGE. Burroughs are forbidden tohave police forces of their own,
but municipalities may. Cities may have PD\'s, too. And we have the State
Department of Public Safety, with 4 divisions (State Troopers, Airport
Police, University Police, and Fish and Wildlife... the first and last are
one administatively and training wise, the middle two have separate
training and hiring, but answer to the state director of public safety).
When Achorage was young, it had 3 neighboring "Incorporated Cities", plus
housed the "Greater Anchorage Area Bourough" (GAAB) government, separate
from the city government. As anchorage expanded, it surrounded, then
absorbed the Cities of Mountain View, Spenard, and Jewel Lake. The
Incorporated Townships of Eagle River, Chugiak, Peter\'s Creek, Girdwood,
Indian, and Turnagain were too far away for this to happen. In 1976,  the
city and the GAAB sought a municipality. All the above now fall under the
jurisdiction of the Municipality, and in theory, could have APD services.
Girdwood then became a city, but doesn\'t have a mayor since that would
confuse the titles with the Mayor of Anchorage, who is THE mayor for all
the residents of the former GAAB. Several townships are not covered by APD
even though they are surrounded by areas that do. Girdwood doesn\'t since
there\'s 60 miles of nothing between the south end and girdwood. Eagle Rive
does, as do Chugiak, Peter\'s Creek, and Eklutna (Those run North from
anchorage, in the order presented) even they are streched along the glenn
highway between 10 and 25 miles north of the North-east corner of Anchorage
proper. Mind you, the APD doesn\'t police the highway itself, even though
that\'s the only way to get between anchorage and the "Valley" (Eagle River
Valley, properly). State troopers have no "Routine" authority inside city
limits... but they may pursue, investigate, or arrest anywhere.... BTW,
Girdwood, 60 miles away, has Anchorage Fire Department Service, while
Chugiak , 15 miles away,doesn\'t have AFD, and isonly five miles past Eagle
river which does have AFD services...

Which brings me to another Ob:Trav diversion....
IYTU, how common is it to integrate the various emergency services?
(Police, Fire, Emergency Medical, Public Health)

